<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Writer Condemned to Jail Term for Attacking Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Roger Garaudy, a 85-year-old
author of "the Founding Myth of Israel" and some other works in
which he attacked Israel, was sentenced to nine months in jail
plus 160,000 francs (27,000 U.S. dollars) in fines by an appeals
court of Paris on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He was convicted of contesting crimes against humanity, racial
defamation, and provocation of hatred by the 11th Chamber of the
Appeals Court of Paris, which rejected an appeal by Garaudy
against an earlier sentence by a lower court against him.
</P>
<P>
Garaudy, a former member of the politburo of the French
Communist Party but now converted to Islam, was sentenced on
February 27, 1998, by the first instance of the court of Paris to
pay 120,000 francs in fines for contesting crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
In "the Founding Myth of Israel" and others, Garaudy said the
number of dead in the Holocaust as was claimed by Israel was
exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
Garaudy also fiercely attacked the policy of Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanhyahu and reaffirmed his theory on
Holocaust in his 1998 book "The Trial of Israeli Zionism."
</P>
<P>
The court also sentenced the publisher of "Founding Myth of
Israel" Piere Guillaume, who is the boss of the publishing house
La Vieille Taupe, to six months in jail and 30,000 francs (5,000
dollars) in fines for contesting crimes against humanity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
