<HEADLINE> U.S. to Sell Kuwait Howitzers in Big Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States is
offering to sell Kuwait its Paladin howitzers in a package worth
up to 750 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has received an official U.S. response on Kuwait's
purchase of the U.S.-made guns, Deputy Prime Minister and Defense
Minister Salem Sabah Al-Salem Al-Sabah said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking during a graduation ceremony of army officers at the
Mubarak Al-Abdullah Military College, Salem said he had received a
letter from his U.S. counterpart William Cohen. But he didn't
reveal its content.
</P>
<P>
On December 7, the Kuwaiti defense chief said the Kuwaiti Army
was "in dire need of the U.S.-made howitzer guns to fill the
shortage suffered by the land forces."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that Kuwait was planning to equip three
battalions with howitzers and was studying offers worth a total of
750 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Several big powers including the United States were bidding for
a share of the purchase. Washington was offering its M109 A6
Paladin howitzers.
</P>
<P>
Defending the government decision to buy U.S. guns, the defense
minister said the selection was made according to reports by
several specialized committees which studied all its technical
aspects.
</P>
<P>
Competing guns lacked several technical details offered by the
U.S., including "the possibility to amend it according to our
needs," Salem noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the purchase sparked fierce controversy in the
country. Some of the lawmakers strongly criticized the government
plan, saying the U.S.-made guns are outmoded and not compatible
with the Kuwaiti armament system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
