<HEADLINE> Pope Wecomes World stars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Pope John Paul II, a former top
goalkeeper in Poland, said he hope the exhibition match to be
played by a group of world football stars in Rome Wednesday would
help promote peace among nations.
</P>
<P>
The match at the Olympic stadium, part of the Italian soccer
federation (FIGC) centenary celebrations, pitches the national
side against a team of FIFA World Stars including Brazil's
Ronaldo, Argentinian Gabriel Batistuta and France's Zinedine
Zidane, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming players to the Vatican, the Pope said: "It is my
fervent hope that such a major event will highlight the true
meaning of sport -- in helping young people, promoting
understanding between peoples and furthering the cause of peace."
</P>
<P>
Reports said the Pope's visitors also included Italian
national football coach Dino Zoff and officials from the FIGC,
UEFA and FIFA.  
</P>
</TEXT>
