<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ASEAN Leaders Focus on Economic Recovery at Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the Hanoi Declaration they approved at Wednesday's meeting,
the leaders admitted that the economic and financial upheaval
afflicting the region's economies "has severely set back many of
the gains that our nations and our association have achieved."
</P>
<P>
They pledged to "overcome those economic and social
difficulties by working together in ever closer cooperation and
ever stronger solidarity."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN region, which was one of the fastest growing areas in
the world in the 1980s and 1990s, was plunged into a financial
crisis last year, reducing the growth rate of some member
countries to the negative and forcing them to seek assistance from
the International Monetary Fund and other organizations and
countries.
</P>
<P>
The leaders pledged to keep ASEAN markets open to attract
long-term investments which they described as "the key to
strengthening and stabilizing the region's currencies and
economies."
</P>
<P>
They also reaffirmed their commitment to the greater
integration of their economies "as a primary expression of our
cooperation and solidarity."
</P>
<P>
The leaders agreed on the immediate implementation of a number
of "bold measures" to improve the investment climate in the member
countries "to regain business confidence, enhance economic
recovery and promote growth."
</P>
<P>
According to the measures, the ASEAN countries, in an effort to
attract foreign direct investment, will extend incentives and
privileges to qualified ASEAN and non-ASEAN investors in the
manufacturing sector, including a minimum three-year corporate
income tax exemption, or a minimum 30-percent corporate investment
tax allowance, 100-percent foreign equity ownership, duty-free
imports of capital goods and domestic market access.
</P>
<P>
In the Hanoi Plan of Action, the leaders pledged to restore
confidence, regenerate economic growth and promote regional
financial stability through maintaining sound macroeconomic and
financial policies and strengthening financial system and capital
markets so as to avoid future disturbances.
</P>
<P>
The plan contains a number of concrete measures for improving
the member countries' trade and financial systems and facilitating
trade among ASEAN members and that between the ASEAN members and
other countries through accelerated implementation of the ASEAN
Free Trade Area (AFTA) and other liberalization measures to remove
trade barriers by cutting tariffs to 0-5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, the ASEAN countries will promote liberalization
of the financial services sector and intensify cooperation in
money, tax and insurance matters including feasibility studies on
the establishment of an ASEAN currency and exchange rate system.
</P>
<P>
The leaders also agreed to go ahead with the establishment of
the ASEAN Investment Area, where each ASEAN member country will
give foreign investors the same privileges of their own nationals
in an effort to attract more direct investment into and within the
ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
The summit also agreed to admit Cambodia at an admission
ceremony to be held in Hanoi as soon as possible, thus fulfilling
the vision of ASEAN-10. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
