<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian FM Calls U.S. Natural Security Partner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov has described the U.S.-Russian relations in recent years as
"natural security partnership" despite differences in approaches
to their common goals.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the newspaper "Nezavisimaya Gazeta"
published Wednesday, Ivanov said Russia and the United States have
converging strategic goals as far as the resolution of most
international problems is concerned.
</P>
<P>
However, different measures and methods to reach the strategic
goals are often suggested and sometimes they cause serious
differences, said the Russian foreign minister, who is paying an
official visit to Spain.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov noted, "Russia believes that international relations
should be based on the supremacy of international law rather than
on the use of force."
</P>
<P>
"Practice shows that an intention of using force, especially
when circumventing the U.N. Security Council, may spawn very
dangerous consequences for international security," he said.
</P>
<P>
Moscow is opposed to attempts to use Russian-Iranian relations
in certain fields as a lever of pressure on Russia, Ivanov stated.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the pan-European processes, he said, "Russia
realizes the need to preserve the Trans-Atlantic dimension and
does not think that the United States should be squeezed out of
Europe."
</P>
<P>
"But we will not accept attempts to push Russia aside in
Europe," Ivanov stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also emphasized the importance of economic and technological
cooperation between the two countries. He said that Russian-U.S.
trade last year doubled and reached 8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov pointed out that bilateral economic relations are still
facing quite a few problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
