<HEADLINE> France Calls on U.N. Council to Decide on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- France Wednesday called on the
United Nations Security Council to decide on the follow-up actions
on Iraq, and stressed that the report submitted by the UNSCOM
conflicted with that of the International Atomic Energy Agency
(IAEA).
</P>
<P>
"We noted that the first document (by the UNSCOM) is negative
and the second (by the IAEA) is positive," said French Foreign
Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
The report submitted by chief of the UNSCOM Richard Butler said
that Iraq had failed to cooperate fully with his weapons
inspectors, while the letter from IAEA chief Mohamed El Baradei to
U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan said that Iraq had provided "the
necessary level of cooperation" to IAEA inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"Concerning Mr. Butler's report, its substance and the question
it raises must be examined in depth by the Security Council. The
Security Council will then decide on the follow-up actions," said
the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
She also criticized the U.N. for failing to consult the members
of the Security Council, as it was in previous cases, before
withdrawing weapons inspectors from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"This decision was not preceded by consultations within the
Security Council, as should normally be the case, and as we have
asked for in the past in similar circumstances," she said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council will hold an emergency
session Wednesday to discuss the situation of Iraq, during which
France and Russia are expected to oppose the stand of the United
States and Britain on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have threatened to strike Iraq
without pre-warning and without U.N. mandate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
