<HEADLINE> Hodler under Pressure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Marc Hodler, the
vice-president of the International Olympic Committee (IOC) from
switzerland, said on Wednesday he was undeterred by the storm
which had arisen over his accusations of corruption in the
Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
"My feeling is that certain people were afraid of this affair
and were intent on sweeping it all under the carpet. I wanted to
put the pressure on," Hodler was quoted by the Neue Zuercher
Zeitung as saying.
</P>
<P>
The plot had earlier thickened after Hodler said he was under
political pressure to tone down his attack for fear it could harm
a Swiss bid for the 2006 Winter Olympic Games, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Hodler, whose allegations of financial wrongdoing in the
bidding process caused a row at the weekend, said Swiss Foreign
Minister Flavio Cotti had advised him against pressing for the
creation of a commission of enquiry in case it scuppered the
Swiss city of Sion's attempt to stage the 2006 Winter Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
