<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Education Holds Key to Development: Ethiopian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Education Genet Zewdie said Wednesday that education, particularly
that of young girls and boys, holds the key to the development.
</P>
<P>
Launching of 1999 State of the World's Children Report at the
United Nations Conference Center here, Genet noted that education is
the most important factor in combating many social and economic
problems prevailing in developing countries, without making education
accessable to their people, developing countries can not achieve
economic growth and increase social development on a sustainable
basis.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the focus of this year's State of the
World's Children Report is education, which "is one of the major
challenges that we all face as we move towards the new
millennium."
</P>
<P>
According to the report, about 21 percent of primary
school-age children worldwide are out of school and an estimated 855
million people (nearly one-sixth of humanity) are likely to be
functionally illiterate at the end of this century. While in
developing countries, over 150 million children started school but did
not reach grade five.
</P>
<P>
Referring to educational state in Ethiopia, Genet said the
budget to education grew from seven percent to about 14 percent in the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
A five-year Educational Sector Development Program aims at
increasing the primary school enrollment to 50 percent and girls
enrollment to 45 percent by the end of the year 2001, she added.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launching ceremony, Per Engebak, Representative
of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF), pointed out that
"Mass illiteracy exists because of the world has failed to make good
on its commitment to ensure the right of basic primary education for
every child."
</P>
<P>
He said that the global cost of meeting those commitments has
been estimated to be an additional 7 billion U.S. Dollars a year over
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
"Seven billion Dollars is less than its spent each year on
cosmetics in the United States -- or ice cream in Europe. And
the total education spending package of 70 billion Dollars is
less than one-tenth of what the world spends militarily in just
one year," he stressed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
