<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three EU Members to be Sued Over Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is to
take actions against France, Belgium and Germany for the trade
barriers they have allegedly set up to block the free movement of
goods.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive branch, made the
decision after receiving a number of complaints against
violations of relevant EU rules on the part of the three countries.
</P>
<P>
These violations include a French case involving automobile
spare parts in transit and a Belgian case concerning labeling
requirements for certain foodstuffs.
</P>
<P>
The commission said it will give reasoned options to these
countries regarding to their unlawful acts. The three countries
will face actions before the EU Court of Justice, the EU's supreme
court, if they failed to give satisfactory responses to these
options within two months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
