<HEADLINE> Annan to Attend Security Council Meeting on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan said Wednesday morning that he would attend the
Security Council meeting on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Annan said he would discuss the issue of
Iraq with the council members so as to know what was happening on
this side.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he had got a phone call from Peter Burleigh, U.S.
ambassador to the United Nations, who said that U.S. personnel in
the Gulf region had been asked to leave and the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) had been advised to withdraw from
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Annan said some of the U.N. humanitarian personnel had left
Iraq and the Untied Nations had grouped the remaining personnel in
one location for their own safety.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, executive chairman of the UNSCOM in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, reported late
Tuesday that Iraq had failed to live up to its promise to
cooperate fully with the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States have threatened to launch
military strikes against Iraq at any time.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council has decided to meet on
Iraq Wednesday morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
