<HEADLINE> Summit on Congo (K) Crisis Re-scheduled for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Wednesday disclosed that the proposed Lusaka summit on
ncy ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The summit was put off due to commitments by various heads of
states on the dates that were earlier proposed, Chiluba explained
when briefing the press before departure for Burkina Faso to
attend a meeting of the Organisation of African Union (OAU) which
takes place Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
Answering whether the rebels fighting President Laurent Kabila
in Congo (K) will be invited to the discussions after they were
denied access to previous meetings, Chiluba said he is positive
they will be invited.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian leader has been mandated by the Southern African
Development Community states to mediate the Congo (K) conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Many steps have been made and all parties to the conflict
will attend and possibly agree to a ceasefire before other
internal procedures take place," Chiluba noted.
</P>
<P>
The summit, which was originally scheduled for December 8 and
later re-scheduled for December 14, were postponed because of the
objection of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
South Africa argued that it was wasting time to hold the
meeting without the participation of the rebels who claimed to
have controlled half of the territory of the vast central African
country.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, who has invited Zimbabwe, Angola, Namibia and Chad to
help quell the rebellion, insisted that his government only
wanted to hold talks with Uganda and Rwanda that are backing the
Tutsi-led rebels.
</P>
<P>
While the rebels earlier expressed clearly their stand that
any cease-fire would be meaningless if the government didn't hold
direct peace talks with them.  
</P>
</TEXT>
