<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnia Peace Conference Adopts Madrid Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The fourth Bosnia Peace
Implementation Conference ended here Wednesday after adopting a
Madrid Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The declaration urged the three ethnic groups of Muslims,
Croats and Serbs in Bosnia to comprehensively fulfill their
commitments in the 1995 Dayton peace accords, and called for
respect for the country's independence and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The document said the international community would gradually
reduce its aid to Bosnia in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it said, the Bosnian people should make good use of
the time to develop their economy, create more job opportunities
and improve their living standards so that they could manage to do
without foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
The declaration called on all parties in Bosnia to work harder
to create political, economic and security conditions for the
return of the large number of refugees in 1999.
</P>
<P>
It promised that the international community would provide
necessary aid to facilitate the return of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also called on the Bosnian authorities to
closely cooperate with the international community and shoulder
greater responsibility in the implementation of the Dayton peace
accords.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, which opened on Tuesday, had
participants from 43 countries and 17 international
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
