<HEADLINE> Iraq Has Broken Its Promises, Says Blair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- United Kingdom Prime Minister
Tony Blair said Wednesday that the Iraqis had broken pledges to
let the United Nations arms inspectors return to Baghdad and
resume their work unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Blair told the House of Commons, the lower house of parliament,
that U.N. chief inspector Richard Butler's report to
Secretary-General Koff Annan clearly listed obstacles such as
delays and refusal to provide documents.
</P>
<P>
The allies had the necessary authority needed to launch air
strikes, he said.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said the Iraqis operated a "plan of
deceit" to prevent inspections.
</P>
<P>
In the last round of the Iraqi crisis, the prime minister had
warned that the United States and UK forces in the Gulf would
strike Iraq without previous warning next time when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Tuesday Iraq had failed to restore full cooperation
with his weapon experts.
</P>
<P>
Blair's spokesman said earlier that the Moslem holy month of
Ramadan, due to start later this week, was a serious consideration
in deciding the time of any attack.
</P>
<P>
"This is not something that can be done in the click of a
finger," the spokesman said when asked about the possible timing
of a strike. 
</P>
