<HEADLINE> Security Council to Meet on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Wednesday suspended its scheduled consultations to meet on
Iraq at 11:30 (EST), the U.N. Spokesman's Office announced.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told reporters Wednesday
morning that he would attend the council meeting on Iraq after he
received a call from Peter Burlegh, charge d'affaires of the U.S.
Mission to the United Nations, who said that Washington has asked
U.S. citizens in the Gulf to leave the area.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would discuss the issue of Iraq with Security
Council members to know what was going on inside the world body.
</P>
<P>
Some of the U.N. humanitarian personnel had left Iraq and the
United Nations had grouped the remaining personnel in one location
in Iraq for their own safety, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The council decision to shift its focus of attention to the
issue of Iraq came after chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler
has presented his long-awaited report to Annan, who later handed
it over to the 15-member Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The report, issued late Tuesday, said that Iraq had imposed new
restrictions on arms inspections, that was seen as Baghdad's
failure to offer full cooperation with the U.N. arms inspection
group, known as the UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Butler said Iraq's lack of full cooperation made it impossible
for inspectors to determine that Baghdad had eliminated its
prohibited weapons, a key requirement for lifting stringent U.N.
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council held a scheduled meeting Wednesday morning
on the maintenance of peace and security and post-conflict
peace-building.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided to suspend the consultations and
immediately go into the discussion on Iraq, a U.N. official told
Xinhua. The council is expected to resume consultations on
peace-building at the end of the consultations on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government called for an emergent meeting of the
Security Council while a French government spokesman voiced the
hope that a military strike could be avoided. 
</P>
</TEXT>
