<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Urges Congress Not to Impeach Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore
called on Congress Wednesday to "turn away from the bitter
partisanship" and spare President Bill Clinton from impeachment.
</P>
<P>
"I believe on Capitol Hill there is still time for Democrats
and Republicans to come together and embrace a bipartisan
compromise to seek a resolution that is both quick and fair and
try to turn away from the bitter partisanship that we have seen so
far," Gore said at the White House.
</P>
<P>
The vice-president's call came one day before the House of
Representatives is expected to start debate Thursday on the four
articles of impeachment approved last week by the Republican-led
House Judiciary Committee. They include two counts of perjury, one
of obstruction of justice and one of abuse of power in connection
with the Monica Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
A House vote for impeachment would send the case to the Senate
for a trial, where 67 votes, or two-thirds majority, would be
needed to remove Clinton from office -- a result no one expects.
</P>
<P>
Gore canceled a trip to New Hampshire to stay in Washington and
he tried to rally fresh support to stop Clinton from becoming only
the second chief executive to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
The prospects for Clinton avoiding impeachment in a House vote
continued to worsen as more undecided Republicans declared their
intention to vote to remove Clinton.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, whom
Clinton defeated in the 1996 presidential race, suggested that the
Senate could head off a protracted impeachment trial by passing a
joint resolution to censure Clinton and sending it to the House.
</P>
<P>
In a report to the House justifying the four articles of
impeachment along party lines, Judiciary Committee Republicans
said Clinton "disgraced himself and the high office he holds."
</P>
<P>
"His high crimes and misdemeanors undermine our Constitution.
They warrant his impeachment, his removal from office and his
disqualification from holding further office," the Republican
report said.
</P>
<P>
A draft version of the minority report, by the committee's
Democrats, concluded, "We do not believe that the nature of the
misconduct is the mettle with which the founding fathers intended
impeachments to be made."
</P>
<P>
Repeating a theme sounded by Democrats in impeachment hearings,
the minority report said that even if the allegations were true,
they don't merit "impeaching a president, thereby decapitating the
executive branch and disenfranchising the electorate." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
