<HEADLINE> Schroeder to Review Tax Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN. December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
plans to review his government's much-criticized tax reform
proposals prior to starting work on tax legislation, a government
spokesman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see whether certain objections of small and
medium-sized companies are justified," said Schroeder's spokesman
Uwe-Karsten Heye.
</P>
<P>
The review of tax reform plans by Schroeder's full cabinet was
expected to take place on February 17, he said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's tax plans have come under furious criticism from
Germany's business and banking communities.
</P>
<P>
Under the center-left government's current plan, corporate
income tax would only drop in 2002, although Schroeder has said a
cut might come in 2000 if enough revenue was available.
</P>
<P>
Personal income tax rates, which now range from 25.9 percent
for low earners and 53 percent for higher incomes, would be
trimmed on a step-by-step basis to between 19.9 and 48.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, Germany's central Bundesbank joined the attack on
Schroeder's tax reform in its December report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Whereas reductions mainly benefit private households, the
counterfinancing is mainly concentrated on companies so that there
is an additional tax burden for this sector despite tax cuts,"
said the Bundesbank report.
</P>
<P>
"This could make investment conditions more difficult, even if
domestic private consumption is positively influenced," said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
