<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Government Still Divided on Nuclear Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's
Red-Green government Wednesday ended its last cabinet session
before the Christmas holiday divided over how to push ahead with
plans to shut nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
"In its objective the coalition is in full agreement, but the
way to get there has not been fully agreed," admitted Schroeder's
spokesman, Uwe-Karsten Heye.
</P>
<P>
Heye said parameters for a law aimed at long-term closure of
nuclear plants would be agreed by a January 13 meeting of the
chancellor and his economic and environment ministers.
</P>
<P>
Bonn's center-left government agreed in its coalition pact to
shut Germany's 19 nuclear power stations, which produce about 30
percent of the country's electricity.
</P>
<P>
Green Environment Minister Juergen Trittin wanted a fast
closure and had sought to force through strict nuclear power
legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
But Schroeder and his Social Democratic (SPD) Economics
Minister Werner Mueller want to reach a consensus over closure
with nuclear power station operators, meaning the process will
take much longer to complete.
</P>
<P>
At dispute are possible legal demands for compensation both
from nuclear operators and from British and French reprocessing
plants which have contracts to take spent German nuclear fuel.
</P>
<P>
Trittin and the Greens believe there is little danger of the
government being forced to pay compensation either for shutting
plants -- which currently have indefinite operating licenses -- or
for breaking contracts with British and French reprocessing
concerns.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder and Mueller, however, fear that without talks on a
consensus basis the plant closures could end up with a massive
bill for the government.
</P>
<P>
Heye told reporters that talks with Germany's nuclear plant
operators would start in late January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Gets Better Harvest This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Angola sees a better harvest
this year over last year, with a plenty of rain in most parts of
the country and increased supply of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
A bulletin issued Wednesday by the Agricultural Ministry said
that in northern part of the country, the output of maize
increased by 51 percent, and that of cassava by 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
But because of the continued military conflicts in northern
Angola's Malange Province, many farmers have been forced to fleed
their homes and the province has to depend on relief food.
</P>
<P>
In central part of the country, many farmers harvested next to
nothing, after the farmers had used seeds imported from Brazil,
which have proved as unsuitable for the climate in central
Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
The Cunene Province in southern Mozambique experienced severe
drought and locusts plague this year which marginally reduced the
agricultural production in the province.
</P>
<P>
The war-ridden country, which has to rely on international
food aid for 10 years, was estimated in May by the World Food
Program to need about 470,000 tons of food aid this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
