<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls on Security Council to Do More on World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday called
on the U.N. Security Council to respond positively to the repeated
appeals of African countries and translate its attention to
African issues into concrete deeds.
</P>
<P>
It also urged the Security Council to refrain itself from being
involved in internal conflicts in some countries.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Qin Huasun, China's permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor at the
Security Council on the maintenance of peace and security and
post-conflict peace-building.
</P>
<P>
"The prime responsibility of the council in maintaining
international peace and security is both unshirkable and
irreplaceable," Qin said.
</P>
<P>
In regions like Africa and Central Asia, where war and conflict
persist, to put an end to the conflicts at an early date so as to
create a secure environment for their socio-economic development
has become the top priority of the international community, and
thus calls for the meaningful support and assistance of the United
Nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary for the council to respond positively to the
repeated appeals of African countries and translate its attention
to African issues into concrete deeds," he said. "The council
should play an especially constructive role" on such questions as
that of Somalia, Sierra Leone, the Great Lake region, he added.
</P>
<P>
The council "should take into serious consideration the
reasonable requests of Africa, effectively assist in and
coordinate with the African efforts and give active support to
regional organizations like OAU (the Organization of African
Unity) that are in want of necessary funds and technical
expertise."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese ambassador called upon the Security
Council not to get involved in internal conflicts in some
countries.
</P>
<P>
"In recent years, the council has become more, rather than
less, involved in the internal conflicts in some countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese delegation has always held that the council should
strictly adhere to the purposes and principles of the U.N.
Charter, act upon the consent or request of the country concerned
and make every endeavor to help resolve the conflicts through
peaceful means," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the multi-nation military actions, Qin said that all such
actions authorized by the council should strictly oblige their
activities and standardize the mechanism of fulfilling
responsibilities to the council, reporting to the council and
accepting the council's political guidance.
</P>
<P>
"China is strongly opposed to any act of power politics that
unilaterally resorts to the use of threat or the use of force in
international relations while circumventing the council," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
