<HEADLINE> IAEA Relocates Its Personnel From Iraq to Bahrain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The director-general of
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Mohamed Elbaradei,
had decided to temporarily relocate to Bahrain all its personnel
currently in Iraq, a U.N. release said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The release said this action was taken after the decision by
the Untied Nations Special Commission (UNSCOM), on whose logistic
support the IAEA's activities in Iraq are dependent under the
existing arrangement, to withdraw all of its personnel from Iraq
and out of concern for the safety and security of IAEA personnel.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, executive chairman of the UNSCOM in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, reported late
Tuesday that Iraq had failed to cooperate fully with the U.N. arms
inspectors in the past month.
</P>
<P>
The IAEA Tuesday said it got satisfactory cooperation from Iraq
since it promised to resume full cooperation with the U.N. on
November 14.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to launch military strikes
against Iraq for its failure to cooperate fully with U.N. arms
inspectors at any time and without consultations with the Untied
Nations Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
