<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister: Bank Sale Report "Misleading" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan cabinet minister
Wednesday categorically refuted a report of the country's leading
daily New Vision on the sale of Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB) as
misleading.
</P>
<P>
Kehoash Mayanja Nkangi, the Ugandan Minister of Justice and
Constitutional Affairs, told a press conference that the report
entitled "Nkangi Names State House in UCB Sale" implies that
President Yoweri Museveni was involved in the UCB saga while he
did not mean it in his defense report in the parliament Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister clarified that Engineer Kabanda, the former
principal private secretary of the president had inquired whether
the 49 percent shares of UCB bought by a Malaysian company could
be sold to anybody else.
</P>
<P>
He advised journalists to find and check and to be
responsible for their reporting.
</P>
<P>
The Westmont Holdings of Malaysia bought 49 percent shares in
UCB last year and it reportedly sold the shares to Salim Saleh,
President Museveni's younger brother, which is a clear breach of
the sale agreement.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that the buyer of the shares cannot
sell them within three years unless authorized by the Ugandan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
Saleh admitted 10 days ago that he used Westmont as a front to
buy UCB because his Greenland Investments was disqualified as a
bidder by the Bank of Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The illegal transfer of shares reportedly led to heavy losses
to the government and some ministers involved in the matter
either resigned or are facing censure from the parliament.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
