<HEADLINE> Iran Optimistic to Pipe Central Asian Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad
Khatami here Wednesday expressed optimism that Iran would win in
the competition to become the main route for transporting Central
Asian oil and gas to Europe.
</P>
<P>
"Despite all the efforts by the U.S. and the Zionists
(Israelis) to prevent transfer of the Central Asian energy to
Europe through Iran, I am of the belief that Iran would be the
route for transfer of the energy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to staff members of the Oil Ministry, he said that the
European countries would give priority to their national
interests, the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The United States has strongly opposed the option to pipe oil
and gas across Iran, which it regards as an avowed enemy.
</P>
<P>
Tehran hoped economic considerations will finally prevail,
saying that Iranian route is the shortest and the most economic
one for Central Asian energy to reach world markets.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said the U.S. sanctions against Iran's vast oil
resources accentuate the importance of the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Over the past half century, he said, 90 percent of the
country's foreign exchange revenues and 60 percent of its
domestic income have been from the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
He called for fundamental changes in the oil industry.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been vying for the vastly rewarding project of
transporting oil and gas from the Caspian nations to Europe, with
other competitors, among which are Russia and Turkey, which has
the backing of Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
