<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank Sees Dark Clouds Ahead for German Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank, the
Bundesbank, has painted a bleak economic picture of Germany in its
latest monthly report, with uncertainty created by the
government's new tax plans adding to the loss in growth caused by
the emerging markets crisis.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the Bundesbank said in its December report
released Wednesday that slumping foreign orders had left
"significant economic skidmarks," with the export of goods falling
in the third quarter of 1998 for the first time in about three
years.
</P>
<P>
And with German unemployment remaining at stubbornly high
levels, Germany's influential central bank said that Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder's new center-left coalition could help to boost
jobs and investment by offering companies cuts in taxes and other
levies.
</P>
<P>
In the light of the current uncertain economic outlook, the
Bundesbank appealed to the government along with both employers
and unions to help to ensure a stable political climate.
</P>
<P>
With this in mind, the Bundesbank called on the unions and
employers to promote a moderate wage outcome in the country
combined with steps aimed at dealing with the jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Bundesbank argued that creating jobs and
consequently ensuring a lasting reduction in unemployment should
also be accompanied by increasing productivity together with
employment incentives for companies.
</P>
<P>
But the Bundesbank was also clear about the role the German
government had to play in underpinning the labor market.
</P>
<P>
"The government could contribute more to investment and new job
creation if it held out the prospects for companies of a
significant reduction in taxes and the total burden of levies,"
the Bundesbank said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the fall in foreign orders from oil-producing
nations and regions hit by financial turmoil, the Bundesbank saw
German export industries facing tough price competition from Asia
and as a result having to offer goods at more competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
This is also likely to occur against the backdrop of a weaker
U.S. dollar, which would be expected to hit German exports.
</P>
<P>
In its report, the Bundesbank singled out two key German export
industries, the chemical and machine engineering sectors which it
said had suffered in recent months as a result of the state of the
global economy.
</P>
<P>
During the third quarter, the delivery of German goods to Asian
nations had dropped by 31 percent compared with a year earlier,
falling by 10 percent to Japan and 10 percent to OPEC
oil-producing countries, which have faced a slump in oil prices
following the emerging markets crisis.
</P>
<P>
But the Bundesbank noted that because of the comparatively
small role of exports to regions hit by financial woes, the
economic fallout on Germany could be limited, with exports to key
markets in the European Union and the United States likely to grow
by 4.5 percent and 11.5 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
A key pillar of domestic orders has been the recent strong
performance of Germany's car industry.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank, however, saw limits on the growth in domestic
consumer spending with the marked expansion of consumption partly
a result of consumers resorting to savings.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bundesbank, at 11.75 percent, private savings
are now at an historic low. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Issue Depends on Two Communities: Peres </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres said here Wednesday that a solution to the political
issue in Cyprus depends on the two communities in the island.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, Peres said his advice to the Greek
Cypriot and Turkish Cypriot communities on the island was "to get
on with the process" themselves.
</P>
<P>
"My best advice is for them to decide. We can help, we can
support but basically it is in your hands, as it was in our case,"
the Nobel Peace Prize winner said.
</P>
<P>
However, in the case of Cyprus "it is a little bit more
difficult because negotiations are not only between the Turks and
the Greeks who live on the island but also between Turkey and
Greece."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since Turkey landed
 its troops and took over the northern third of the island in
1974 following a failed pro-Athens coup. The U.N.-led efforts to
reunite Cyprus have so far yielded no results.
</P>
<P>
Peres also expressed the view that a solution will be found
once all three countries, Cyprus, Greece and Turkey become
European Union (EU) members.
</P>
<P>
Peres was here to present trade awards to 12 Cypriot companies
which have close business ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is very clear. the island should be united, the
parties should discuss," Peres said.
</P>
<P>
Peres left here later Wednesday. During his stay in Cyprus, he
met with Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Speaker of the
House of Representatives Spyros Kyprianou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
