<HEADLINE> Cyprus Urged to Release Israelis on Spy Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Former Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres on Wednesday called on the Cypriot authorities to
show mercy to the two Israelis charged with spying.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two Israelis committed a "mistake but not a
crime," saying that they were fighting terrorism and not acting
against Cyprus and that he would like to see them released.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference at the end of his two-day
visit, Peres expressed regret for what he described "a local
accident" and said "they did not want to cause any harm or hard
feeling between our people."
</P>
<P>
Expressing respect for the independence of the judiciary in
Cyprus, as far as the case is concerned, he said "we can ask for
understanding but we cannot force anybody to do anything."
</P>
<P>
Peres said if Cyprus does not consider this a mistake it would
harm bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
"It was not any attempt to spy on Cyprus or against Cyprus,
this is nonsense. It is a local accident which we regret very
much because we learned that it caused some bad feelings among the
Cypriot people and this surely we did not want," Peres said.
</P>
<P>
The two Israelis, Udi Hargov, 37, and Igal Damary, 49, were
arrested in November on charges of spying, conspiracy to spy and
possession of banned audio equipment. They are due to appear
before court on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
