<HEADLINE> MPs Sign to Censure Minister in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Over 120 members of
parliament in Uganda have so far signed a motion seeking to
censure a minister who they said should be responsible for the
improprieties in the privatization of parastatals in the country.
</P>
<P>
The MPs accused Sam Kuteesa, state minister in charge of
planning and investment, of playing a part in messing up the
privatization process of the country's key parastatals, Radio
Uganda reported Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians told Radio Uganda Wednesday afternoon
that they would censure him if he does not resign, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Previously, the minister said he is not corrupt and has not
used his close relationship with President Yoweri Museveni to
manipulate his way in business.
</P>
<P>
He also attacked the report of a parliamentary probe team,
saying it was unfair to him and vowing that he will not resign.
</P>
<P>
Kuteesa, who married the sister of the First Lady Janet
Museveni, bought 20 percent shares in the ground cargo handling
services under a consortium through his private company Global
Airlinks.
</P>
<P>
Some MPs accused the minister of political influence peddling,
financial impropriety and stripping the government of its assets
through dubious deals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
