<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Envoy on Upholding World Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China Wednesday voiced
its support for the active involvement of the U.N. system in the
efforts for peace-consolidating and peace-building in
post-conflict regions.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the statement as the U.N. Security Council met on
the maintenance of peace and security and post-conflict
peace-building.
</P>
<P>
"To maintain and consolidate peace after conflict requires
enormous efforts. In regions where war just ended, effective
support and assistance from the international community are needed
since the political and security structures in these regions are
still delicate and their economy has been severely damaged," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, Qin put forward three proposals on making and
consolidating peace in post-conflict regions.
</P>
<P>
First, equal attention should be given to all post-conflict
regions.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted with concern that certain hot issues have become
the focus of attention while some others have been unfairly put on
the back burners," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We see that in some places where there is no longer the threat
to international peace and security, U.N. peace-keeping operations
are still on the ground; while at the same time, other places,
like Africa, in much harder humanitarian and economic situations
are stuck in various kinds of difficulties in getting capital
assistance and the involvement of the United Nations," he said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, in the peace-consolidating process in post-conflict
regions, international efforts should be turned to the will of the
country concerned.
</P>
<P>
"The international community should get involved only on the
basis of the commitments to maintaining the sovereignty,
territorial integrity and political independence of the country
concerned," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Consideration should be given to the most pressing needs of
the country concerned, namely, the funds and technical assistance
that it needs most in its rehabilitation and development," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"China has all along been opposed to attaching political
conditions to assistance, even more strongly to the practice of
using the involvement in post-conflict peace-building to sell
one's own value or achieve any political ends," he said.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, what is most needed in post-conflict reconstruction is
capital and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Being gravely concerned over the marginalization of relevant
U.N. functions, Qin said, "The role and capacity of U.N. organs in
the socio-economic field should be strengthened."
</P>
<P>
"We are even more strongly opposed to the weakening of the role
of U.N. organs in the socio-economic fields on the one hand, while
putting the large load of social issues on the agenda of the
Security Council on the other," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are not in favor of putting all the problems in all
conflict areas in the hands of the Security Council, not least on
the ground of the division of work among the various organs of the
organization," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not good for the normal functioning of other U.N.
organs, including the General Assembly that is composed of all
U.N. member states," he said. "At the same time, such practices
might dilute the priority and impair the efficiency of the work of
the Security Council." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
