<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Rap Netanyahu for Procrastinating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) blasted Israel Wednesday for its decision to
postpone the pending troop withdrawal under the latest peace deal
but vowed it would be committed to its obligations.
</P>
<P>
Upon returning from a short trip to Cairo, PNA Chairman Yasser
Arafat said in Gaza that the decision made by the Israeli cabinet
earlier Wednesday was "clear and dangerous violations" of the Wye
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he doubted that Washington, who helped broker the
deal in October, would agree to the postponement.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet reaffirmed at a special meeting Wednesday
morning that Israel will not begin implementing the second stage
of troop withdrawal on Friday as scheduled because the PNA has not
fulfilled its obligations.
</P>
<P>
PNA Planning and International Cooperation Minister Nabil
Sha'ath said the Palestinians have fulfilled and will be committed
to all of its obligations.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian negotiator Hassan Asfour, however, warned that the
PNA would consider suspending implementing its part of the
agreement in reaction to Israel's decision, stressing that the
commitments must be mutual.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who convened the
cabinet meeting to report on the three-day visit by U.S. President
Bill Clinton to Israel and Palestinian areas, repeated his
position that Israel will not carry out its part of the agreement
until the Palestinians fulfill all their obligations.
</P>
<P>
He put the troop withdrawal on hold last week amid widespread
violence in the West Bank, sparked by Israel's refusal to release
Palestinian political prisoners, and other alleged Palestinian
violations.
</P>
<P>
During his trip, Clinton failed to persuade Netanyahu, who
faces strong pressure from the hardliners in his coalition, to
stick to the timetable set in the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Netanyahu and Arafat at the White
House in October, calls on Israel to relinquish 13 percent more of
the West Bank in exchange for tougher Palestinian measures on
anti-Israeli violence.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu repeated at the cabinet meeting that the Palestinians
have to meet a list of demands before Israel agrees to carry out
the troop withdrawal, including curbing violence, confiscating
illegal weapons and abandoning the intention to declare a
Palestinian state unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
But the PNA said it has fulfilled all of its obligations,
including revoking the anti-Israel clauses in its national
charter as demanded, and accused Netanyahu of shifting his
internal pressure on the Palestinian side. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
