<HEADLINE> U.S. Poised for Air Strike at Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. military forces are
"in execute mode" as President Bill Clinton was pondering how to
make a response to what Washington believed was Iraq's lack of
full cooperation with weapons inspectors, U.S. officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, just back from the Middle East, sat down with his
foreign policy advisers Wednesday morning in the White House
Situation Room. They met there for about 45 minutes and were
expected to confer throughout the day, one official said.
</P>
<P>
"We're in an execute mode," a senior defense official said. "If
somebody dials 911, we're ready to go."
</P>
<P>
"This is obviously a very serious situation. All options are on
the table," including air strikes, one White House national
security aide said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. force strength in the Gulf was unusually high with over
200 warplanes and 20 warships and 15 B-52 bombers on the Indian
Ocean island of Diego Garcia, each capable of firing 20
air-launched cruise missiles with 2,000 pound high explosive
warheads.
</P>
<P>
The missiles can fly up to 1,000 miles (1,600 km) and guided by
satellites in space, strike small targets with pinpoint accuracy.
</P>
<P>
Britain has 18 Tornado attack jets in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Radar-avoiding U.S. F-117A stealth attack jets have not been
sent to the Gulf this time, and defense officials said privately
initial attacks are likely to chiefly involve cruise missiles to
keep U.S. and British pilots out of harms' way.
</P>
<P>
In addition to more than 70 naval aircraft on the aircraft
carrier Enterprise, the U.S. Air Force has four big swing-wing B-1
bombers based in Oman and some 90 F-15, F-16 and A-10 attack jets
based in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
