<HEADLINE> Lebanese Lawmakers Debate New Government Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese parliament started a
two-day debate Wednesday on the policy statement submitted by the
newly formed government two days ago.
</P>
<P>
Eleven deputies representing their factions in the 128-seat
parliament addressed the meeting, during which the new cabinet is
pending a vote of endorsement.
</P>
<P>
Although parliament member Walid Jumblatt, former Druze militia
leader during the country's 1975-1990 civil war, attacked some
proposals in the statement and decided not to vote for the
cabinet, most deputies gave backings to the new government.
</P>
<P>
The 16-member cabinet was formed by Prime Minister designate
Salim Hoss early this month following the resignation of former
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri. Hariri served over the past six years
under former President Elias Hrawi.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts attributed Hariri's quit mainly to his
struggle with current President Emile Lahoud over the formation of
the new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
He was also disappointed that some of his one-time allies in
his cabinet refused to nominate him as head of the first
government under Lahoud, who took office in October, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to parliament procedures, the legislators will go on
with their debate Thursday morning and cast their votes in the
evening. Analysts forecast that the government will be approved.
</P>
</TEXT>
