<HEADLINE> Security Council to Continue Meeting on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council will continue emergency consultations on Iraq Wednesday
afternoon, council president Jassim Buallay said.
</P>
<P>
The council started the closed-door meeting at 10:45 a.m. (EST)
Wednesday on the follow-up actions after chief U.N. arms
inspector's report raised the specter of a military confrontation
between the U.S. and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, with the attendance of U.N. Secretary-general Kofi
Annan, adjourned at 1:20 p.m. and Buallay said the discussions
will resume at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
He is expected to tell the press about the outcome at the end
of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, executive chairman of the U.N. Special
Commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, reported late Tuesday that Iraq failed to live up to
its promise to cooperate fully with the U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States have threatened to launch
military strikes against Iraq "at any time."
</P>
<P>
The council had a scheduled day-long meeting Wednesday on the
maintenance of peace and security and post-conflict peace
building.
</P>
<P>
As the Iraq issue has emerged, the 15-member council decided to
suspend the scheduled meeting and began consultations on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It intended to resume the scheduled meeting at 3:00 p.m., but it
changed the agenda again, leaving the afternoon session to
consultations on Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
