<HEADLINE> Iraq Says Butler's Report Against Fact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Iraq said Wednesday
that it has offered "full cooperation" with U.N. arms inspectors,
especially during the past three weeks, and the U.N. Special
Commission, or UNSCOM in charge of disarming the Mideast country,
presented a report which "is against the fact on the ground."
</P>
<P>
Nizar Hamdoon, Iraqi permanent representative to the United
Nations, made the statement after the Security Council adjourned
its morning session on Iraq. The 15-member council is scheduled to
hold consultations on a report presented by Richard Butler, the
chairman of the UNSCOM, at 3:30 p.m. (EST).
</P>
<P>
"The report is against the fact that has emerged on the ground
over the last three weeks" and "the UNSCOM is very much
politically motivated, very much politically motivated and very
influenced by the policy of the United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Butler said in the report, presented to U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan late Tuesday before Annan handed it over to the
Security Council, that Iraq failed to fully cooperate with U.N.
arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq has done its best to meet its obligation" by fully
cooperating with the UNSCOM, Hamdoon said. The Iraqi statement was
supported by a Tuesday report from the International Atomic Energy
Agency, which said that it had got satisfactory cooperation from
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Butler has had a heavy attack" from some of the 15 Security
Council members Wednesday morning as he was briefing the Security
Council on his report, Hamdoon said, adding that Butler was
criticized for "his way of preparing his report and his decision
to withdraw personnel out of Iraq without informing the Security
Council at appropriate time."
</P>
<P>
However, the U.N. Spokesman's Office quoted Butler as saying
that he made the withdrawal decision after his conversation with
Annan.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM, a body under the Security Council, should seek the
council's approval before taking any decision.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president of the Security Council for the month of
December, Jassim Buallay of Bahrain, told reporters that he could
not speak any more beyond the simple announcement of the council's
resumption of the discussion Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
But he promised to inform the press of the outcome after the
council's upcoming afternoon session on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council, which suspended its previously scheduled
consultations on other issues, decided to begin discussion on
Butler's report at the request of Russia, who called for an
emergent council meeting on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the council's peace efforts, championed by China,
France and Russia, Iraq has narrowly averted the U.S. military
strikes in mid-November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
