<HEADLINE> Chechen President Not to Impose Curfew </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 16 (Xinhua) -- There is no plan in the Chechen
administration to impose a curfew on the breakaway republic
following the declaration of a state of emergency, the Chechen
president's spokesman Mairbek Vachagayev said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The decision to exercise a one-month state of emergency on the
territory of Chechnya was declared by the Chechen parliament
Tuesday. The state of emergency began at 0:00 local time
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya declared the state of emergency in order to step up
the crackdown on criminals and to end the nearly daily kidnappings
in the republic.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of a state emergency would not affect
citizens' basic rights and freedoms, and it "allows Chechen
President Aslan Maskhadov to tackle crime problems more promptly,
involve reserve forces and use weapons," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, by Wednesday morning, five regiments and nine
battalions had been formed out of reservists.
</P>
<P>
It was said that on Monday, the parliament turned down a
request by Maskhadov to mobilize army reservists as part of the
anti-crime effort. Lawmakers said reservists could only be
mobilized in the face of an external threat.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Interfax reported, ideological
preparations for special operations to combat criminals have
reached their peak.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov has urged the population to gather in Freedom Square
Thursday and state their attitudes on criminals and on actions to
combat them.
</P>
<P>
On the whole, the situation in Chechnya remains tranquil
despite the declaration of a state of emergency.
</P>
<P>
Kidnappings have become more and more frequent. Last week four
foreign hostages were beheaded in Chechnya, which shook the whole
world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
