<HEADLINE> NATO Not to Make Enlargement Proposals at Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 16 (Xinhua) -- NATO will not make proposals
of enlargement at the summit due in Washington, next April,
marking 50 years of the alliance's existence, Bruce P. Jackson,
president of the U.S. committee for NATO expansion, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Romania continues to be an important candidate for NATO
accession and will probably be invited to join the alliance in
2002-2003, Jackson told a news conference in Bucharest.
</P>
<P>
The integration proper will occur around 2003-2004, said
Jackson who is currently paying an official visit to Romania. He
added he wants Romania to become, at least militarily, "a de facto
NATO member" before becoming a "de jure" one, with the completion
of the technicalities required for adhesion.
</P>
<P>
Jackson stressed that a political decision on the alliance's
expansion schedule will be made only after the presidential
elections in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
