<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Hints at Possible Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said Wednesday he would initiate early
elections next Monday if he could not muster a necessary majority
for his policy on the peace process with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Likud gathering celebrating the Jewish festival
of Hanukka in Tev Aviv, Netanyahu urged his coalition members and
opposition to support his decision to suspend the pending troop
withdrawal from the West Bank stipulated under a recent
land-for-peace deal between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Palestinians of a series of failures to comply
with the agreement and reiterated that Israel would not carry out
its part of the accord until the Palestinians fulfill all their
obligations. The cabinet reaffirmed his decision Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
He was obviously calling on the opposition Labor Party to form
a unity government with the Likud coalition by saying that "we
must unite the forces."
</P>
<P>
But in an effort to avoid the impression that he was wooing
the opposition, he stressed that "I'm not going to run after
somebody, to race after somebody."
</P>
<P>
"If there is no necessary majority to support this
decision...I will initiate new elections in order to get from the
people the mandate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu faces a no-confidence vote in the parliament next
Monday. Since some hardliners in his coalition who opposed the
peace agreement have vowed to topple his government, it seems
that he would certainly lose the vote.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were seen as a last bid to win back those rebels
in his coalition and to form a unity government with the Labor
Party before being forced to initiate early elections.
</P>
<P>
Since the Labor Party has no interest in rescuing him from the
brink of being brought down, his words could virtually be
interpreted as an announcement that there would be early
elections in Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
