<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Trade Minister to Visit Middle East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian International Trade
Minister Sergio Marchi will lead a trade mission to the Middle
East from February 22 to 28.
</P>
<P>
The visit will include stops in Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, the West Bank and Israel, and will highlight a range of
sectors, including information technology, telecommunications,
education, agri-food, engineering and construction.
</P>
<P>
"These four markets together accounted for more than 1 billion
Canadian dollars (650 million U.S. dollars) of Canadian exports in
1997," said Marchi in a release issued Wednesday. "I welcome this
opportunity to support Canadian companies active in the region and
help them gain a competitive edge."
</P>
<P>
In Riyadh, Marchi will participate in the ninth session of the
Canada-Saudi Joint Economic Commission and meet with a number of
Saudi government officials. In the United Arab Emirates, he will
open the new Canadian Embassy building in Abu Dhabi. On his first
visit to the West Bank, the minister will officially open the
Canadian Representative Office in Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
Marchi will also review the two-year-old Canada-Israel Free
Trade Agreement (CIFTA) and explore ways to further improve trade
with Israel. Under the CIFTA, two-way trade has increased more
than 34 percent, with exports to Israel surpassing 243 million
Canadian dollars (158 million U.S. dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Canadian exports to Saudi Arabia reached over 545
million Canadian dollars (354 million U.S. dollars), and over 257
million Canadian dollars (167 million U.S. dollars) to the United
Arab Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
