<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Unemployment Rises for Second Month in Row </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- British unemployment is
continuing to rise with the two measures of counting the number of
people out of work going up for the second month in a row.
</P>
<P>
The Office for National Statistics (ONS) announced Wednesday
the number of British claiming jobless benefits rose by 5,900 last
month, after jumping by 10,700 in October.
</P>
<P>
Employment Minister Andrew Smith conceded that the rise in the
number of people claiming unemployment benefits was consistent
with an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
However, the jobless rates remained unchanged at 4.6 percent of
the workforce on the claimant count and 6.2 percent on the
International Labor Organization measure.
</P>
<P>
The measure of unemployment which introduced by the government
earlier this year as a better reflection of the numbers looking
for work showed a fall of 129,000 on a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the labor market generally continued to improve,
with employment rising and record numbers of job vacancies.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Lyons, an economist in the City, said, "Any rise in
unemployment is not a good thing for the economy but the market
was expecting a 10,000 rise."
</P>
<P>
Now the figure "is consistent with a modest pace of slowdown in
the economy," he added.
</P>
<P>
Analysts believe unemployment will rise next year. Accountants
Chantrey Vellacott said it could increase by 400,000 over the next
two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
