<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Decide Missile Issue After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus will maake a decision
on the issue of missiles after the U.N. Security Council adopts
its resolution on Cyprus, said Cypriot Foreign Minister Ioannis
Kasoulides here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides said after a cabinet meeting that "if, in the next
few days, the Security Council and particularly the international
community show sufficient and convincing interest and sensitivity
towards our security concerns and if this meets one or both of the
preconditions we have set out, then the National Council (top
advisory body to the president) will be in a position to examine
these prospects and decide accordingly."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus insists that the Russian-made S-300 anti-aircraft
missiles will be deployed in Cyprus unless productive talks begin
or unless the prospect of a reduction of military presence is in
sight with a view to the demilitarization of the island.
</P>
<P>
However, Kasoulides said that he was not speaking about
cancelling government plans for the missiles but about relevant
decisions the National Council may take on the matter.
</P>
<P>
He said the European Union (EU) cannot be indifferent to
developments in Cyprus as the island is negotiating its accession
to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides confirmed that "some relative progress has been
made" in the separate meetings U.N. resident representative Dame
Ann Hercus held with Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
And the shuttle talks will continue after Hercus returns from
New Zealand where she is spending Christmas holidays. The talks
will focus on such issues as commitments to rejecting the use of
violence or the threat to use violence and to avoiding any further
military buildups, Kasoulides said.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy S-300
anti-aircraft missiles but postponed the arrival of the missiles
until the end of December amid Turkey's threat to launch
preemptive strikes on the missiles if they are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
