<HEADLINE> Romanian Police Reports Huge Seizure of Forged Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Police cracked
down on a ring of money counterfeiters, seizing 54,600,000 lei
(about 5200 U.S. dollars) in 50,000 lei bills, the largest such
operation in recent years, the national Rompres news agency
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Technical Department" of the ring was headed by a 21 year
old computer-addicted guy, Marius Constantina, who was graduated
from a computer technology high-school and built his personal
computer out of no-name components.
</P>
<P>
With a scanner and a color printer, Marius Constantina began to
forge money in January, this year. He worked secretely in the
house of one of his two assistants.
</P>
<P>
The police seized a full set of computer equipment and heaps of
special paper with 50,000 lei bills printed on both sides.
</P>
<P>
Further investigation showed that the ring composed of 7
persons has put in circulation so far hundreds of millions of
counterfeited lei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
