<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Suez Canal Revenues Drop in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt saw a continued decline in
revenues of the Suez Canal in 1998, Chairman of the Suez Canal
Authority Ahmed Fadel said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The canal authority collected 1.76 billion U.S. dollars this
year, down 3.4 percent from last year, Fadel told a news
conference held in Ismailia at the midway of the canal, 110
kilometers east of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
Fadel attributed the fall in revenues to the economic turmoil
in Southeast Asia and the sharp slump of oil prices on the world
markets, which he said withered the maritime transport.
</P>
<P>
He said that 13,478 ships sailed through the world's longest
lock-free canal in 1998, a drop of 6.6 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
The canal revenues, one of Egypt's four largest foreign
currency earners, were 1.822 billion dollars in 1997. This was
already 3 percent lower than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A circular released by the authority Wednesday said the transit
fees of the ships going through the international waterway will
not be changed in 1999, meaning that the tolls which have been in
place since 1994 will be kept intact.
</P>
<P>
The authority is to offer new services in a bid to lure more
ships to pass through the canal, Fadel said. It is seeking a
partnership deal with foreign companies for maintenance within 36
hours for vessels carrying up to 350,000 tonnes of cargoes, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The official said the depth of the canal will be increased to
72 feet (about 21.95 meters) for the world's largest oil tankers
to go through.
</P>
<P>
The 193-kilometer canal stretches from Port Said, 160
kilometers northeast of Cairo, to Suez city, 120 kilometers east
of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The canal, linking the Mediterranean and the Red Sea, was
opened in 1879 and nationalized in 1956. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
