<HEADLINE> Tanzania-Zambia Railway Reshuffles Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzania-Zambia
Railway Authority (TAZARA) board of directors have decided to
retire the managing director Kingsley Mkandawire and his deputy
Ayub Ritti because of their poor management.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued in Dar es Salaam Wednesday said that the
board of directors made the decision after a meeting in the city
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, signed by TAZARA board chairman S. H. Msoma and
co-chairman X. E. Vlahakis, said that the board has appointed
Charles Phiri and M.P. Banyikwa as acting managing director and
deputy managing director respectively.
</P>
<P>
During the 1997/98 fiscal year (from July 1997 to June 1998)
the authority's losses fell to 16.6 million Shillings (25,150
U.S. Dollars) from 18.8 million Shillings (28,480 Dollars) in the
previous fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
But the improvement in operations and financial controls was
increasingly threatened by various problems in the management
style, such as lack of management-worker contact and default in
paying workers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
Six months ago, TAZARA workers complained about mismanagement
by TAZARA and demanded the resignation of Mkandawire, who is a
Zambian. 
</P>
</TEXT>
