<HEADLINE> Romania: Opposition Reads Out No-confidence Motion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian Opposition read
out on Wednesday in Parliament a no-confidence motion against the
current government. The motion is to be debated by the two Chambers
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The motion was tabled last Friday in the Permanent Offices of
the two Chambers of the Parliament and was signed by 97 deputies
and 46 senators from the parliamentary groups of Party of Social
Democracy of Romania (main force in the opposition), Greater
Romanian Party, and Romanian National Unity Party.
</P>
<P>
The motion refers to "the incapacity of the current majority to
lead the country as well to its incapacity to understand and
defend the national interest."
</P>
<P>
The authors of no-confidence motion consider that the
government led by Radu Vasile demonstrated in the eight months
since it took office lack of responsibility for the economic and
social situation in the country, that it "caused chaos in Romania,
its failure is evident on all planes."
</P>
<P>
The motion says that Romania is today in the grip of the most
serious social crisis after 1989. The Opposition hopes that the
motion will be voted for, the Radu Vasile Government will be
withdrawn trust, and "a responsible and competent Executive will
be formed, that will prepare premature elections."
</P>
<P>
The leader of Party of Social Democracy Ion Iliescu explained
that the motion was determined by the country's arrested economic
and social development, not political calculations. He said the
motion had been meant to "trigger out" serious public debates on
the effects of the current leading coaltion's mistakes and the
ways to put an end to the current "dangerous fall" of economy and
living standards, and also to reinvigorate the country's economy
and society.
</P>
<P>
President Emil Constantinescu said that the Opposition's action
is "ill-timed," since right now all forces and energies have to be
focused on the economy restructuring process. He believed that
the motion shall be "used for a serious analysis of the Power's
management short-comings, for suggestions on a better
communication between Power, Opposition and the civil society."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
