<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Departing House Members Voice Displeasure over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, Xinhua 16 (Xinhua) -- Some of the 40 departing
House members are voicing displeasure about capping their
congressional careers by voting on whether President Bill Clinton
should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
"It's a terrible way to go out," Representative Lee Hamilton, a
Democrat, told ABC's "Good Morning America" on Wednesday.
Hamilton, a foreign affairs expert who is retiring after 34 years
service in congress, said "there are 1,001 other issues I would
prefer to vote on."
</P>
<P>
Hamilton opposes impeachment. Others in the group of lame-duck
lawmakers, including impeachment supporters, share his distaste
for the upcoming votes.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think anybody is really excited about making it but
it's one of those tough votes as an elected official you have to
make from time to time," said Representative Vincent Snowbarger, a
Republican, who supports impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The House is scheduled to take up the four articles of
impeachment against Clinton on Thursday that the House Judiciary
Committee approved last week.
</P>
<P>
Three of the 40 departing House members -- Republicans Jim
Bunning, Michael Crapo and Democrat Charles Schumer -- were
elected to the Senate and would serve as jurors during possible
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
Schumer, who opposes impeachment, also serves on the House
Judiciary Committee. Bunning and Crapo were undecided on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
But some of those who won't be in the new Congress that opens
January 6 said they weren't concerned about political
repercussions, instead saying that returning members are the ones
who need to be worrying about it.
</P>
<P>
"My career I think will speak for itself," said Representative
Louis Stokes, a Democrat, an impeachment opponent who is retiring
after 30 years. "I think the ones who have to worry about their
place in history are the ones who have instigated this type of
embarrassment on the part of the nation."
</P>
<P>
Retiring five-term Representative Mike Parker, a
Representative, doesn't care about fallout.
</P>
<P>
Parker said he votes "my conviction" after examining facts,
adding "That's all I can do. I don't worry about how it fits into
the scale of the other votes that I cast."
</P>
<P>
Representative Paul McHale, a Democrat, said, "The last thing I
want to do is leave public life by voting for the impeachment of
the president of my own party." The three-term representative
said, "I will recognize that this is a duty that I have to meet,
but it certainly is not a pleasant one." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
