<HEADLINE> Syria Denounces U.S. Air Strikes on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Syria on Thursday denounced
the air strikes launched by the U.S. and Britain on Iraq Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
Speaker of the Syrian People's Council Abdel Kader Kaddura said
that the attack against Iraq was completely uncalled for. It was
conducted beyond the U.N. resolutions. And it would hurt the Iraqi
people, particularly children and civilians, increasing their
sufferings and pains.
</P>
<P>
He added that "we in the People's Council, while denouncing,
censuring and condemning this attack, call upon the international
community to denounce it and have it halted immediately."
</P>
<P>
After months of disputes over weapons inspections, U.S. and
British forces launched the biggest air strikes against Iraq since
the 1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The attack came hours after the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) chief Richard Butler presented a report accusing Baghdad
of failing to fully cooperate fully in weapons inspections as its
promised one month earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
