<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NORWAY: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vollebaek held Iraq responsible for the current situation in
the Gulf, and said that Norway would watch the developments
instead of playing a direct role in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Vollebaek also accused Iraqi President Saddam Hussein of
non-cooperation with the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
ALBANIA:
</P>
<P>
-- The Albanian government said Thursday that Tirana is fully
supportive of the U.S.-led air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Soko Gjoka said in a statement that
the U.S. took the military action following it received a report
by the United Nations Special Commission on Disarming Iraq's mass
destruction weapons, the Albanian government held that the
military action against Iraq was in line with relevant United
Nations resolutions.
</P>
<P>
POLAND:
</P>
<P>
-- The Polish government said Thursday that it is necessary to
take military actions against Iraq after political means failed to
solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities had refused to implement the U.N.
resolutions and their cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission
had been suspended, said a government statement.
</P>
<P>
In order to make Iraqi President Saddam Hussein adhere to
U.N. resolutions, it is necessary to take military actions, the
Polish Press Agency quoted the statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, Poland also held out hope that the actions will not
bring damage to the civilians.
</P>
<P>
Also on Thursday, Polish Foreign Minister Bronislaw Geremek
told reporters that he "deplored and was disappointed" over the
fact that the Iraqi crisis was not solved through political means
and the United States and Britain had to resort to force.
</P>
<P>
GREECE:
</P>
<P>
-- Greece's armed forces have been since Wednesday closely
monitoring the situation in Iraq following air strikes launched
overnight by the U.S. and Britain against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Greek National Defense General Staff's operations center
had been put on alert since Wednesday after the evacuation of
U.N. arms inspectors from Iraq, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) quoted sources close to the National Defense General
Staff (GEETHA) as saying Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
