<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Condemns U.S. Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov Thursday condemned the military strikes against Iraq as
"outrageous" and said that the action has further worsened the
Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Primakov blamed Richard Butler, head of the UN Special
commission, for his negative role in the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Russian President Boris Yeltsin met with
Primakov and high-ranking military officials to discuss the
situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said the president stayed up all night and issued a
strongly worded statement against the attack.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense Minister Igor
Sergeyev were summoned back from overseas trips for consultations.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Federal Council, or upper chamber of Russia's
parliament, released a statement urging the U.S. and Britain "to
respect the U.N. Charter and international law."
</P>
<P>
The State Duma, the lower house of parliament, is expected to
adopt a resolution denouncing the strikes, which is likely to
include a provision on Russia's withdrawing from the
U.N. sanctions against Iraq, said the State Duma Chairman Gennady
Seleznyov.
</P>
<P>
The Itar-Tass news agency said that Russia's mass
organizations, such as the Labor Union and the Congress of Russian
Communities, have categorically denounced the air strikes and
urged boycotting contacts with U.S. officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
