<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tunisia Concerns About Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Tunisia expressed concern
Thursday about the escalation of the military operations against
Iraq, calling upon all parties concerned to exercise restraint and
halt military actions immediately.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Tunisian Ministry of Foreign Affairs
reiterated Tunisia's firm position it had expressed in November,
which had appealed for the concerned parties to exercise
restraint and to pursue diplomatic means in dealing with the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The ministry expressed its deep regret for the serious
consequences of the air strikes. It called upon the international
community to act and halt the military actions immediately.
</P>
<P>
It also called for returning to diplomatic means, the only way
to resolve conflicts in conformity with the U.N. Charter and
international norms.
</P>
<P>
The statement also expressed sympathy and solidarity with the
Iraqi people to end their sufferings. It further voiced utmost
concern about the negative consequences of the air strikes on the
security and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British forces launched air strikes against Iraq
midnight Wednesday under the pretext of Iraq's failure to
cooperate fully with U.N. weapons inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regulation on Urban Housing Reform Passed in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Municipal
People's Congress today adopted a regulation on urban housing
reform submitted by the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
The regulation sets the deadline for commercializing housing on
December 31, 1999, by which all new apartments that will be
delivered and existing government-built apartments for sale will
be sold to workers and staff members.
</P>
<P>
Since the housing reform was tried out in the city in 1994,
700,000 households have bought government-built
apartments. Per-capita floor space in the urban area has reached
9.3 sq.m.
</P>
<P>
The government-allocated funds for housing construction will be
converted into housing subsidizes.
</P>
<P>
A housing guarantee system for lowest-income families will be
introduced to enable such families to rent inexpensive
apartments. By the year 2000, there will be no family in Shanghai
with a per-capita floor space of less than four sq.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
