<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Doubts Effectiveness of U.S.-British Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- France is sceptical about the
effectiveness of the ongoing U.S.-British missile strikes against
Iraq, said French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We are always not convinced, we cannot but be sceptical about
the effectiveness of the military strikes in respect of the
objective which is that of the international community, that is
how to maintain a real control to ensure that this country... not
become dangerous for the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The sooner the strikes stop, the better it would be," said
Vedrine, who made the statement at the French Senate.
</P>
<P>
He said that the problem of making Iraq fully cooperate with
U.N. arms inspectors could be solved through political and
diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
"We think that this question, these conflicts, these
impossibilities should be overcome through political and
diplomatic work," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier statement, the French minister said that Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein bore primary responsibility for the
U.S. strikes.
</P>
<P>
"I regret that he (Saddam) and the Iraqi leadership failed to
properly cooperate," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
