<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Needs Huge Investment for Highway Repairs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Canada's highways are scarred
with potholes, cracks and rough patches that would take the
various governments more than 17 billion Canadian dollars (11
billion U.S. dollars) to fix, a new national study says.
</P>
<P>
The country's 25,000 kilometers of provincial and
interprovincial highways -- the lifeblood of Canada's trucking
industry and a huge component of the national economy -- are at
least as bad as the they were 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The study says that fixing the roads immediately would cost the
federal and provincial treasuries 17.4 billion Canadian dollars
(11.3 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The news comes despite the fact than 11 billion Canadian
dollars (7.2 billion U.S. dollars) has been spent on the system
since 1988 and that annual expenditures on highways are twice what
they were 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Canada has about 800,000 kilometers of roads, but only 25,000
are classified as highways. About 30 percent of travel takes
place on this system.
</P>
<P>
The study found that levels of rideability -- or road roughness
-- are unacceptable on 7,000 kilometers of road, up from 5,200
kilmetres in 1988. More than 5,300 kilometers of the roads could
not carry vehicles operating at 90 kilometers an hour or higher.
That figure is up from 4,200 kilometers in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
