<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Veteran Fan Saves China for Third Straight Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Veteran defender Fan Yunjie
headed in a golden goal five minutes into the second half of extra
time to pace China for a 1-0 win over DPR Korea in the women's
soccer final.
</P>
<P>
It was China's third straight title for women's soccer at Asian
Games.
</P>
<P>
Just as the time was running out and penalty shoot-out in
sight, China got a corner kick at the left. Zhao Lihong sent a
cross to the 26-year-old Fan, who raced to head the ball past
South Korea's out-charging goalkeeper Kye Yong-Sun into the net.
</P>
<P>
China, inferior to their DPR Korean opponents in both speed and
stamina, got a lot of chances in the goalmouth, only to see their
shots repeatedly blocked by DPR Korea's tight defence.
</P>
<P>
The DPR Korean team, which lost to China 0-2 last December for
runners-up in the 11th Asian Women's Championships, whipped up
waves upon waves of attack on China's goal at the beginning of the
match, with forwards Jo Jong-Ran and Kim Song-Ryo running China's
defence ragged. But their shots went to no avail before Chinese
inspired goalkeeper Gao Hong.
</P>
<P>
China, who never lost in the Games' women soccer after it being
inaugurated in the 1990 Beijing Asiad, got a good chance in the
40th minute when defender Wen Lirong chipped a pass to unmarked
Sun Wen, but Sun's blank-point shot was fingertipped by Kye
Yong-Song over the crossbar.
</P>
<P>
The DPR Korea also surprised China in the 84th minute when Yang
Kyong-Hui saw her direct freekick hit the cross-bar.
</P>
<P>
After a 90-minute scoreless regular, both sides had to fight
for the extra which was ended by Fan's sudden-death goal.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first extra since I took the helm of China's women
soccer," said coach Ma Yuanan.
</P>
<P>
"This is an unexpected hard fight for us," he said. "I
originally expected us to win by at least two goals, but our
players failed to psych themselves up for the match."
</P>
<P>
"They bore some mental burden as they were much eager to win
the title, and this affected their performance," he added.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jilong, vice president of Asian Football Confederation,
held that the hard win reflected DPR Korea's gnawing at China's
lead in Asian women's soccer.
</P>
<P>
"The DPR Korean players took us aback with their speed, stamina
and footwork," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The era of China's domination in Asian women's soccer is near
the end," added Zhang, who also serves as vice president of
Chinese Football Association.
</P>
<P>
China, who conceded no goal in the Games, has swept the last
six Asian Women's Football Championships since they first entered
in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
