<HEADLINE> Asiad Ticket Revenue Possible to Reach Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Revenue from ticket selling in
the 13th Asian Games has reached 153 million baht (4.25 million
U.S. dollars), making it possible to reach the 230-million-baht
(6.4 million dollar) target, an official from the Bangkok Asian
Games Organizing Committee (BAGOC) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 153 million baht has not included the income from the men's
soccer semi-finals between host Thailand and Kuwait on Wednesday,
which is estimated at 15 million baht (416,667 dollars), Keattisak
Wongpanich, Assistant Secretary of BAGOC's Ticket Sub-Committee,
told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The BAGOC had expected to earn some 230 million baht (6.4
million dollars) before the Games was opened on December 6.
</P>
<P>
The most popular sports are soccer, gymnastics, boxing and all
events in the acquatic center, Keattisak said.
</P>
<P>
"The most unexpected sport is Taekwondo," he said. "Before the
Games, we estimated that there will be 400 spectators daily at
most, but the real spectators doubled our estimation, with some
day seeing more than 800."
</P>
<P>
Monsak Nuntasaen, senior manager of Power Telecom Company,
which is appointed by BAGOC for producing and selling Asian Games
tickets, said Thursday that tickets for soccer and boxing matches
are the most popular ones.
</P>
<P>
"Although the match between Thai and Chinese soccer teams for
the bronze scheduled on Saturday is arranged in the southern
province of Songkhla (some 600 kilometers south of Bangkok), the
tickets have been quickly sold out," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government has launched a campaign to lure more
students from drugs to sports by lowering the price of student
tickets to only 10 baht (28 cents) each.
</P>
<P>
But despite the campaign, it is still possible for BAGOC to
meet its target of earning 230 million baht from ticket selling,
Keattisak said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
