<HEADLINE> Chinese Mainland, Taiwan, HK Cooperation Forum Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 100 representatives
from the Chinese mainland, Taiwan and Hong Kong gathered here
Thursday to discuss prospects for their trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the opening ceremony of the forum, Jing Shuping,
visiting vice chairman of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference, stressed the vital importance of further
expansion of their trade and economic cooperation under the trend
of global economic integration and the changing world economic
environment.
</P>
<P>
Jing, also chairman of the All-China Federation of Industry and
Commerce, noted that the Chinese mainland, Taiwan and the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) have become one of the
most vigorous regions in economic growth in the world.
</P>
<P>
He said it is known to all that the mainland is a potential
market with rapid economic growth while Hong Kong and Taiwan have
been playing extremely important roles in world economy.
</P>
<P>
They have their own advantages and at the same time need to
develop. "Our close economic links and effective cooperation have
opened up broad prospects for us," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it is imperative to seize the chance and
strengthen cooperation, turn advantages into actual effectiveness
so as to achieve the goal of common development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chau Tak Hay, secretary for Trade and Industry of Hong Kong,
said that he was optimistic about their development and
cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
He said the mainland is abundant in science and technology
resources, thus laying an important foundation for industrial
innovation and technology improvement.
</P>
<P>
The mainland, Taiwan and Hong Kong cooperation covers a wide
range of areas such as the study of traditional Chinese medicine
and the development of computer's software for Chinese language as
well as biological products, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chau said that the reform of the mainland's state-owned
enterprises provides foreign entrepreneurs with more chances for
investments.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the large, medium and small-sized state-owned
enterprises reform involves various aspects such as
re-organization of assets, structural readjustment and upgrading
enterprises' technological and management level.
</P>
<P>
Entrepreneurs from Taiwan and Hong Kong will play an important
part in this regard, particularly a unique role that Hong Kong
will play in introducing to these enterprises its international
commercial operation experience, modernized management and the
application of law, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Under the principles of market economy, the Special
Administrative Region will neither guide nor interfere in our
businessmen's investment," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Herbert Liang, president of the Chinese Manufacturers'
Association of Hong Kong, said Hong Kong and Taiwan are
respectively the first and the third largest places of the sources
of the overseas investment. Their accumulated investment accounts
for over 60 percent of the total direct foreign investment that
the mainland has absorbed.
</P>
<P>
Hsui Sheng Fa, chairman of the Taiwan Chamber of Commerce and
Industry, expressed the hope for sustainable economic growth of the
mainland, Taiwan and Hong Kong with their close cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was jointly sponsored by the All-China Federation
of Industry and Commerce, The Chinese Manufacturers' Association
of Hong Kong and the Taiwan Chamber of Commerce and Industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
