<HEADLINE> NATO Not to Cancel PJC Meeting With Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) on Thursday said it was not the side that will
propose to cancel the Permanent Joint Council (PJC) meeting with
Russia.
</P>
<P>
A NATO official told the press that the western military
alliance was not considering cancellation of the meeting,
scheduled for Friday, after reports reaching here said Russian
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev would not come to Brussels as a
protest against the U.S.-led air raid on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The official said NATO is not the side that cancels the PJC
meeting and that the meeting may still go ahead with other
officials from the country to discuss issues ranging from nuclear
transparency to computer "millennium bug" problem.
</P>
<P>
"I can't confirm that the meeting will not be held as
scheduled," said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was in the interests of both sides to sit
together and discuss issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
But the official made it clear that Iraq is not a NATO
responsibility. "It is not something that NATO as an organization
handles," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, NATO Secretary General Javier Solana issued
a brief statement concerning the American-British joint air raid,
but his statement was described by the official as personal.
</P>
<P>
Russia and China are strongly opposed to the use of force
against Iraq, while France deplored the military attack as one
without the mandate of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Russia withdrew its representatives from Brussels in protest
after NATO ordered air strikes against Yugoslavia in mid-
October. But the Russian representatives returned shortly
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Joint Council was established after the signing
of the NATO-Russia Founding Act in May last year to serve as a
consultation platform for the former Cold War foes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
