<HEADLINE> Singapore, Malaysia Agree to Solve Bilateral Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong said Singapore and Malaysia have agreed to work out a
package to settle the disputes over the CIQ (Customs, Immigration
&AMP; Quarantine) and Railway Land problems along with other
outstanding issues between the two neighbors, media reports said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the revelation to reporters after a 30-Minute meeting
with Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad following the ASEAN
Summit in Hanoi, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
After the divorce 33 years ago, quite a number of issues have
been left to be resolved in the bilateral relations between the
two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the problems over relocation of Malaysian CIQ
facility at Tanjong Pagar and Malaysian-owned Railway Land both
within Singapore, the two countries also face the issues such as
the CLOB, that was an out-of-counter exchange for trading
Malaysian shares and was forced to suspend after Malaysia imposed
capital control in early September, the withdrawal of Singapore's
Central Provident Fund (CPF) for Malaysian workers who contributed
to CPF while working in Singapore, and the entry and use of
Malaysian airspace by Singapore's air force and Singapore's water
requirement from Malaysia
</P>
<P>
Singapore was happy to discuss all the issues as a package and
the new package will be a win-win situation for both countries,
Goh was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Goh also said that the new package was a change from the
earlier water-for-funds deal being worked out by both sides as
Malaysia is now able to get funds on his own.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the deal reached on November 5 when he made
a surprise meeting with Mahathir in Kuala Lumpur. Under the deal,
Singapore agreed to help Malaysia raise funds while Malaysia
agreed to discuss future water supply to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Goh described the agreement to work out a package as "a good
sign for Singapore."
</P>
<P>
Goh told Singapore parliament in late November that the
Singapore government sent a draft agreement on water to Malaysia
on November 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
