PARIS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- France has held Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein responsible for the missile strikes by U.S. and
British forces and refrained from publicly criticizing
Washington and London.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine said on Thursday that
Saddam Hussein was primarily responsible for the present
situation, because he and other Iraqi leaders had not shown enough
proof of cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
However, the Socialist Party, Communist Party, Greens and other
leftwing forces which make up the ruling coalition have all
expressed opposition, to different degrees, to the U.S. and
British action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party Thursday called for "an immediate stop" of
the bombings, which it said were "a unilateral resort of force in
violation of international laws."
</P>
<P>
Communist Party National Secretary Robert Hue said that he
regretted that France failed to show more firmness in its
opposition to the U.S.-British military operation against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Deplore is not enough; we should condemn," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hue said that the Communist Party, some trade unions and
leftwing parties will hold a protest rally in front of the
U.S. embassy in Paris Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The rightwing opposition parties said that they support the
policy of the government, which they said is realistic and
balanced, while the far-right National Front has condemned the
U.S. bombings.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac, who has not made any public
comment on the bombing, Thursday expressed his concern over the
safety of French nationals in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Chirac is keeping contact with his U.S. counterpart Bill
Clinton, presidential spokesman Catherine Colonna said.
</P>
<P>
The French military said that the French combat aircraft
participating in the "Southern Watch" operation in Iraq have
received order to stay grounded since the beginning of the
U.S.-British strikes Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
France has deployed one C-135 oil supply plane, five Mirage
2000 fighters and three Mirage F10CR reconnaissance planes in the
Saudi airbase of al Kharg since the end of the Gulf War under the
"Southern Watch" operation imposing a no-fly zone south of the
33rd parallel.
</P>
<P>
French planes have never flown beyond 32nd parallel, because
France does not agree with a U.S. decision to extend the no-fly
zone to 33rd parallel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
