<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cheers Century Gold in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- With three days to go, China
celebrated its century gold through women long jumper Guan Yingnan
and stepped further to 102 with a golden goal in the women's
soccer and a martial art expert at the Bangkok Asian Games here on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
National champion Guan, winner in the Asian Championships last
year, awarded China its 100th gold medal by jumping to her winning
distance of 6.89 meters in the last attempt.
</P>
<P>
"I'm glad that I've beaten my anxiety by landing in the victory
distance in my last jump as my teammate Yu Yiqun surprised me with
her 6.77-meter last effort," said Guan.
</P>
<P>
To highlight China's feat in the Asian Games, Fan Yunjie scored
the golden goal from a left-wing pass off Zhang Ouying to award
China its 101st gold medal in the women's soccer final against the
Democratic People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese held a little advantage over their rivals in the
pitch but failed to convert chances into goals in regulation time.
</P>
<P>
Of the six athletics golds, China took one more through Li
Shaojie in the men's discus, who set an Asian Games mark of 64.58
meters, with the other four split by Kazakhstan, Japan, South
Korea and India.
</P>
<P>
South Korea reapt the most of eight golds out of a total of 40
golds at stake in the competitions of the day, taking both the
men's and women's team titles in archery, two from the wrestling,
and one apiece from the athletics, badminton, cycling, fencing.
</P>
<P>
Asian record holder Lee Jin-Il of South Korea ran the fastest
in the men's 800 meters to retain his Asiad's title in one mintue
46.56 seconds after a break of three years, banned for doping
test.
</P>
<P>
Thailand had its best day of five golds, taking half of the six
boxing gold medals on its clear home advantages, winning its
strong sport of sepak takraw and a surprising victory in the men's
tennis doubles.
</P>
<P>
Three Thai boxers were involved in the day's finals with all
beating their respective rivals by points, raising concerns for
the refereeing system of amateur boxing as neither of the losers
willingly acknowledged their defeats.
</P>
<P>
In the track cycling, Japan, South Korea and China, the East
Asian countries, continued their dominance by taking five out of
the seven golds at stake in the Bangkok Asian Games, with the
other two went to Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The men's sprint remains as the domain for Japan as Yoichiro
Kamiyama becomes the first professional cyclist with an Asian
Games gold, South Korea becomes the winner in the men's team
pursuit and China proves its strength by taking all the golds and
silvers in the women's events.
</P>
<P>
The day's medal tally also ushered in a new champion of origin
as Myanmar outbeat Vietnam in the women's sepak takraw final, and
both Macao and Brunei won their first medal of a silver and a
bronze respectively.
</P>
<P>
Thailand overtook Kazakhstan and Chinese Taipei to rank in a
distant fourth with 18 golds, only behind of China, South Korea
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
South Korea increased its margin to contend for the second
overall place with 57 golds against 49 for Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
