<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1,500 DRC Fishermen Flee Into Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Some 1,500 refugees
from the war-torn Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), mostly
fishermen, have fled into Tanzania with the fall of Moba Town
into the hand of rebels in mid-November.
</P>
<P>
The refugees, from Fizi zone and South Kivu Province, have
been entering Tanzania through Rukwa Region in southwest Tanzania
and are settling in villages along the southern shores of the
Lake Tanganyika, Vincent Parker, a senior external relations
officer of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
(UNHCR) said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the influx in Rukwa Region, UNHCR immediately
hired boats in late November to collect the new arrivals
initially estimated at 1,500 by local government authorities,
Parker told a press conference at UNHCR's branch office in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
From November 23 to December 13, he said, a total of 621 new
arrivals were picked up with Mv Mwongozo and Mv Liemba from
southern lakeshore villages in the region and brought to the
Kibirizi Port in Kigoma Region which lies to the north of Rukwa.
</P>
<P>
"The new arrivals picked up from Rukwa Region are
predominantly of fishing background, some of whom had fled with
their fishing boats," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is alleged that many of the refugees in the villages are
reluctant to go to refugee camps because of the perceived that
camp life is hard," he added.
</P>
<P>
UNHCR does not currently have permanent presence in Rukwa
Region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since rebels in the DRC took up arms against the government of
President Laurent Kabila, more than 17,300 DRC refugees had fled
into Tanzania, he said, adding that the number still keeps rising
day by day.
</P>
<P>
He said most of the refugees had entered Tanzania from the
Kigoma Region and are accomodated at the Nyarugusu Camp, some 160
kilometers northwest of the Kigoma Town on Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
The refugees have been in good conditions, he later told
Xinhua. "They are better than Burundian refugees."
</P>
<P>
He said the civil war in Burundi since 1993 has forced more
than 270,000 refugees from the country to flow into Tanzania,
although 11,259 had returned by the end of November.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania plays host to refugees primarily from Burundi, DRC,
Somalia and Rwanda. By November 30, he said, the assisted refugee
population in Tanzania stood at 336,826, compared with 346,000 at
the beginning of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
