<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Condemns U.S. Attack on Iraq (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United States and Britain launched air strikes code named
"Operation Desert Fox" at 05:49 (Beijing time) today. Early
reports indicated that the raids either killed or injured a number
of Iraqi civilians, including children.
</P>
<P>
China issued an immediate response condemning the strikes, and
the Chinese media promptly commenced coverage of the latest
developments. Media reports included diversified responses from
international organizations and countries throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Various local international affairs observers considered the
air strikes an "inevitable" U.S. strategy to use military force to
settle international disputes and advance both hegemonism and
power politics. "Military action was also designed to offset the
seriousness of the impeachment crisis," according to one expert.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Qipeng, director of the International Relations Research
Institute at the Foreign Affairs College, said the international
community, including China, has made unremiting efforts to
peacefully settle the issue. However, according to Zhou, the
U.S. choice of military action against other nations is determined
by nothing more that its foreign policy strategies and so-called
"national interests."
</P>
<P>
Tang Wenzhao, deputy director of Institute of U.S. Studies
under the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), pointed out
that the constraint factor offered by the the international
community, particularly the opposition Security Council members
China and Russia, successfully quelled the U.S. and Britain's two
previous attempts. However, they are "determined to strike Iraq
and eventually oust the Saddam administration," according to Tang.
</P>
<P>
Beijingers intently watched TV reports throughout the day, with
soaring newspaper sales for covers related to Iraq and the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
The local media urged the U.S. and Britain to immediately cease
their military action and expressed full anticipation that China
and the international community work together in an attempt to
settle the Iraq weapons inspection crisis politically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
