<HEADLINE> Egypt Regrets U.S. Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Thursday expressed
regret at the overnight air strikes against Iraq by the United
States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
An official statement issued in the day called for necessary
steps taken by the concerned parties to contain the crisis and
avert further deterioration of the situation to secure regional
stability.
</P>
<P>
Egypt urged the protection of the Iraqi people against further
sufferings.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the eruption of the Iraqi crisis in February, Egypt
has been calling for efforts to find a peace solution to the
crisis, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, meanwhile, has also called on Baghdad to abide by the
United Nations Security Council resolutions to safeguard the
country and its people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced to halt partial or full cooperation with the
U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, in February, August and
November this year. It eventually rescinded its decisions through
international mediations.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched missile attacks on Iraqi military
and security targets most of the night Wednesday to contain what
U.S. President Bill Clinton said President Saddam Hussein's threat
to its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The attacks came after UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler accused
Baghdad of not fully cooperating with U.N. weapons inspections, as
it promised about one month ago to avert an imminent strike.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM is responsible for overseeing the elimination of Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction, a must for the U.N. Security Council
to lift the crippling economic sanctions imposed on Iraq after its
1990 invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
