<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Palestinians Injured in Protest Against U.S. Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- At least five Palestinians
were injured in clashes with Israeli soldiers in the West Bank in
protest against the U.S. air strike against Iraq Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Clashes erupted in Hebron, Bethlehem, Ramallah and other West
Bank towns as Palestinian protesters threw stones at Israeli
soldiers who fired rubber bullets in return, Jerusalem Media and
Communications Center, a Palestinian news service, reported.
</P>
<P>
It said five Palestinians, including a local crewman for a
U.S. television network, were injured in violent clashes in
Ramallah.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians were protesting against the surprise missile
attack on Baghdad launched by U.S. and Britain at around
midnight Wednesday. They burnt U.S., British and Israeli flags.
</P>
<P>
The air strike came only hours after U.N. chief inspector
Richard Butler submitted a report over the weapons inspections in
Iraq to the U.N. Security Council, accusing Iraq of failing to
cooperate with the U.N. Special Commission, or known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
Senior Palestinian officials said they do not support the
air strike, stressing that dispute can only be resolved by
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We don't condone the use of force by the United States.
We believe solutions should come from peaceful means," Saeb
Erekat, senior Palestinian negotiator with Israel, said in a
televised speech. "This is a sad day for us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, adviser to Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat, said the U.S. military action will not
solve problems but only increase suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"We, as the Palestinians, feel solidarity with the Iraqi
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
These reactions were less strong compared with those during
the 1991 Gulf War, sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990, when the Palestine Liberation Organization expressed its
support for Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and staged large-scale
demonstrations against the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The PNA has kept a low-profile in recent confrontations
between the U.S. and Iraq, refraining from condemning Washington,
the major mediator in its peace-making with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
