<HEADLINE> Thailand Take Half Boxing Golds on Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Hosts Thailand enjoyed an
obvious home ground advantage to take half of the six gold medals
on offer at the Asian boxing tournament on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Three Thai boxers were involved in Thursday's finals and they
all had no problems in beating their respective rivals by points.
</P>
<P>
The refreeing system of amateur boxing again showed its
controversial side as nither of the losers in the bouts against
Thai boxers were satisfying with the score.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese boxing official made it simple: "If the competitions
were held in China, the winner should be Chinese boxer."
</P>
<P>
Yang Xiangzhong of China fought a even five-round bout against
Suban Punnon of Thailand in the 48kg class final but the score
turned to be 14-1 in favor of the Thai boxer.
</P>
<P>
According to the scores, Thai boxers also enjoyed one-sided
victories in the 60kg class and 67kg category.
</P>
<P>
Pongsit Wiangwesas beat Temur Suleymanov of Uzbekistan in the
60kg class final to give Thailang a second gold medal in Asiad
boxing tournament while Parkpoom Jangphonak out-punched Nurzhan
Smanov of Kazakhstan in the 67kg final.
</P>
<P>
The remaining three golds were taken by Kazakhstan, India and
Uzbekistan respectively.
</P>
<P>
Ng-Pingko Singh of India won the 54kg class after beating Timur
Tulyakov of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The 75kg class gold medal was taken by Vyacheslav Burba
Kazakhstan, who defeated Dilshod Yarbekov of Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
After three failed attempts at the title in the lighter
categories, Uzbekistan finally won a gold in the 91kg class as
Ruslan Chagaev dominated the bout to beat Muzaffar Mirza of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The finals of other six classes at the Asiad boxing tournament
will be held on Friday. 
</P>
