<HEADLINE> Roundup: China Condemns U.S. Attack On Iraq (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China has condemned air
strikes the United States and Britain launched in Iraq without
U.N. Security Council authorization, and called for an immediate
halt to military action against Iraq and the resumption of talks
to reach a political settlement concerning weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin urged the United States and
Britain to halt air strikes against Iraq in order to "create
conditions enabling all concerned parties to seek solutions
through dialog."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the military action will seriously
complicate the situation in the Gulf Region and have dire
consequences in terms of international relations. "China is highly
concerned about the situation," said Jiang.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president exchanged views earlied today on the
crisis with Russian President Boris Yeltsin and U.S. President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We were deeply shocked by the news", said Chinese Foreign
Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi, adding that China has always opposed
the use of force and advocate peaceful settlement of international
disputes.
</P>
<P>
The actions taken by the United States and Britain violated the
UN Charter and norms on international relations, said Sun.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's Permanent Representative to the UN, said
violations of international law and practices present "a serious
threat to world peace and security."
</P>
<P>
He accused that the UN Special Commission (UNSCOM) on Weapons
Inspections, led by Chief Inspector Richard Butler, of playing a
role in "instigating" the crisis. He also noted that Butler's
report to UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan was "biased and devoid
of fact."
</P>
<P>
Qin attended today's UN Security Council meeting and said that
Butler bears "grave responsibility" for the current crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
