<HEADLINE> UN Special Envoy on Afghanistan to Visit Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Special Envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi will arrive here Friday for talks with
Pakistani and Taliban leaders on the Afghan issue.
</P>
<P>
"Brahimi will exchange views with Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz and other officials on his talks with Iranian
leaders," a U.N. official requesting anonymity said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The special envoy, currently in Tehran, held talks with Iranian
leaders on the murder of Iranian diplomats and a journalist by
Taliban fighters in Mazar-e-Sharif in August.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Brahimi is also likely to meet Taliban
leaders during his stay here.
</P>
<P>
"We have invited the Taliban for the talks and are hopeful that
a team of Taliban officials will come from Kandahar," he said.
</P>
<P>
It will his second visit to the region in three months. He
visited Pakistan, Iran, Afghanistan and some Central Asian
countries in October this year.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. official, one of the topics of Brahimi's
talks with Pakistani leaders would be the proposed meeting of the
Six Plus Two group in Tashkent, Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
Uzbek Foreign Minister Abdul Aziz Kamilov, during his visit to
Pakistan in November, invited the Taliban to participate in the
Tashkent meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan militia, however, had set a condition that they
should be invited as a government rather than a group.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi's forthcoming visit comes after a resolution by the
U.N. Security Council this month, threatening the Taliban with
sanctions if the militia did not agree to the establishment of a
broad-based government.
</P>
<P>
The Russia-sponsored resolution urged both the warring sides in
Afghanistan to end fighting and peacefully resolve the crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
