<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Meeting on Conflicts Opens in Ouagadougou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- About 18 African leaders
Thursday gathered in Ouagadougou, the capital of Burkina Faso, to
try to find ways to end conflicts on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting of the fourth ordinary session of the
Central Organ of the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution at
the summit level is expected to consider the report of an OAU
high level delegation which visited Ethiopia and Eritrea earlier
to mediate in the Ethio-Eritrean border dispute.
</P>
<P>
The summit is also to consider the report by OAU
Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim on the crisis in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Other issues on the agenda include conflicts in Burundi,
Angola, Guinea Bissau and Comoros.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of all the countries involved in the conflicts as well
as those of member countries of the Central Organ were present at
the summit.
</P>
<P>
Both DRC President Laurent Kabila and the rebel
representatives are now in Ouagadougou, but Kabila refused to
hold direct talks with the rebels, as it has always been his
position.
</P>
<P>
While answering Xinhua reporter's question, Salim said he is
certainly expecting a breakthrough on the DRC issue, but all
depends on the result of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He also ruled out the invitation of the rebels from DRC to the
meeting, because it is a meeting of heads of state and
government.
</P>
<P>
In his report to be delivered to the summit, Salim suggested
for a two-phase solution to the DRC crisis.
</P>
<P>
The first phase will aim at the attainment of a cease-fire,
withdrawal of foreign troops and deployment of a peace-keeping
force.
</P>
<P>
The second phase would involve political dialog aimed at a
peaceful solution to the crisis, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
