<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers Thursday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton on Wednesday launched the largest
military operation of his two terms in office, putting U.S. and
British forces against Iraq in what he called a "strong sustained"
attack from the air against the sources of President Saddam
Hussein's military power.
</P>
<P>
-- Returning to Washington poised to impeach President Bill
Clinton, House Republicans Wednesday night postponed Thursday
morning's climatic floor session after vigorous debate about
whether delay would play into the hands of a White House on the
verge of defeat.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The joint American-British attack, which is expected to last
at least until this weekend, began with a wave of more than 200
Tomahawk cruise missiles, most of them launched against facilities
believed to be used by the Iraqis for the manufacture of storage
of weapons of mass destruction. The United States will likely be
force to leave a large force in the region for several more years.
</P>
<P>
-- Republicans in Congress were bitterly divided over the
airstrikes against Iraq, and the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott, fiercely attacked President Bill Clinton's policy.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- President Bill Clinton went on TV to say he ordered the
attack after a U.N. report said recent arms inspections had been
blocked. U.S.-British attacks are expected to last two to four
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
