<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Horrible Memory for Iraqi Teenager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- For Ali Suleiman, a
15-year-old Iraqi boy, the dawn of December 17 has been etched in
his mind when a tragic incident occurred in his neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
A cruise missile streaked across the sky and slammed into the
main street of most populous Karrada District at 1:15 a.m. (2330
GMT). Ali was injured on his left arm by a shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
The boy later recalled that he was standing with his two
brothers on a lane next to the Karrada main street when he saw a
15-meter-long missile whistled by over his head with a frightening
white light.
</P>
<P>
Then came the deafening explosion, irritating white smoke
billowed up and the air was filled by a smell of sulphur. "I was
shocked to my roots," Ali said.
</P>
<P>
When the day broke, more aftermath of the strike exposed to the
light: a two-meter-deep, six-meter-wide pit left by the missile
explosion in the middle of the street, shattered windows in
destroyed buildings nearby and branches of hit trees littering the
road.
</P>
<P>
The explosion also broke water pipes and water filled up the
large pit. Mud is everywhere.
</P>
<P>
A witness said the blast waves have caused the bricks on the
walls to fly in different directions, hitting passerbys.
</P>
<P>
Usually, the Karrada main street was the most busy place in
Baghdad. But on Thursday morning, traffic was blocked and the
street was crowded with civil defense workers and traffic police
to clear up the site and rescue the injured.
</P>
<P>
The missile which fell on Karrada district was one of the about
200 Tomahark missiles fired by the U.S. and British forces on
Iraqi targets.
</P>
<P>
The strike took place at around midnight local time Thursday
and U.S. President Bill Clinton said the raid was a retaliation
for Iraq's defiance of the U.N. Special Commission, which oversees
Iraq's disarming of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The attack, which has killed at least two Iraqis and wounded 30
others, was launched to destroy Iraq's military capability, Clinton
added.
</P>
<P>
The surprise strike came just hours following a report by UNSCOM
chief Richard Butler, who accused Iraq of refusing to hand over
weapon-related documents demanded by UNSCOM and failing to grant
weapons inspectors unfettered access to suspected sites.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 led to the 1991 Gulf War, and
the weapons inspections in Iraq to ensure it clears off all
weapons of mass destruction. But Iraq has run into several
standoffs with the U.N. over weapons inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
