<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Long-jumper Guan Wins 100th Gold for China in Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Guan Yingnan awarded China its
100th gold medal from the women's long jump finals here on
Thursday when the Asian Games is close to an end with three days
to go.
</P>
<P>
Guan, winner in the last Chinese National Games and in the
Asian Championships last year in Japan, scored her winning
distance of 6.89 meters in her last attempt.
</P>
<P>
Her teammate Yu Yiqun won the silver in 6.77, also from her
sixth jump. Yelena Pershina of Kazakhstan ranked third in 6.55
who failed to score four times in six attempts.
</P>
<P>
Pershina was crowned twice in the 1993 Asian Championships in
Jakarta, Indonesia and in the East Asia Games last year in Pusan,
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Today's top three placings were just a repeat in the Asian
Championships last July in Japan, where Guan took the gold in 6.83
with Yu second in 6.74 and Pershina third in 6.50.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Li Shaojie won the men's discus title with an Asian
Games record of 64.58 meters in his fifth attempt as the Asian
record-holder of 65.16 meters met no challenge from the other nine
rivals. He surpassed the 60 meters with all his six attempts.
</P>
<P>
India's Anil Kumar finished second in 58.43 and Chinese Zhang
Cunbiao third in 57.28.
</P>
<P>
Li, gold medalist in the Chinese National Games in 1993 and
1997, also triumphed in the Pusan East Asia Games and the last
Asian Championships.
</P>
<P>
Asian record holder Lee Jin-Il of South Korea ran the fastest
in the men's 800 meters to retain his Asiad's title in one mintue
46.56 seconds, far behind his record 1:44.14 clocked in Seoul in
1994.
</P>
<P>
The 25-year-old South Korean was banned for three years for
banned drugs in 1994 and returned to the track only last year.
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to win the gold because this is the first
international meet I participated since the ban was lifted last
year," Lee said.
</P>
<P>
"I was not guilty of doping," he said. "I just took some
medicine for my headache and cough."
</P>
<P>
His compatriot Kim Soon-Hyung finished second in 1:46.61 and
Qatar's Abdul Abdulla third in 1:47.10.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 400m hurdle, 30-year-old Natalya Torshina of
Kazakhstan claimed the title in 55.33 seconds, chased by Hsu
Pei-Chin of Chinese Taipei in 55.71 and Li Yulian of China in
55.93.
</P>
<P>
Torshina, silver medalist in the Asian Championships, led the
first 200 meters and was overtaken by Hsu in in the third bend.
She regained the lead in the last 30 meters to finish first.
</P>
<P>
Hsu, bronze medalist in the last Asian Games, won the second
medal of any kind for Chinese Taipei from the track and field.
</P>
<P>
Li Rui, winner in the Asian championships, appeared in a slump
form to finish in fourth.
</P>
<P>
The women's 800m gold went to Idia's Jyotirmoy Sikdhar, who
clocked 2:01.00.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 200m heats, double gold medalist Koji Ito of Japan
stormed into the finals with a time of 20.84 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Koji, who holds the Asian 200m record of 21.06 seconds, led all
the way in the first round, slowing down his pace in the last 20
meters.
</P>
<P>
The 28-year-old, who set an Asian record of 10 seconds in the
100m semifinals, said his main goal is to win the 200m gold medal,
saying "I have always taken 200m as my event actually."
</P>
<P>
In the women's 200m qualifying round, Damayanthi Darsha of Sri
Lanka, gold medalist in the women's 400 meters, beat 100m champion
Li Xuemei in the semifinals as the latter slowed down her pace.
</P>
<P>
Darsha clocked 23.16 seconds against Li's 23.35, which was far
behind her Asian record of 22.01 set up in the Chinese Naitonal
Games last year.
</P>
<P>
With the top three in each two groups qualifying for Friday's
finals, India's legendary P.T. Usha finished fourth in the second
group in 24.27.
</P>
<P>
The Indian veteran, who crashed in the 100m and 4X100m relay,
has only one event of 4X400m relay left in her fifth Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"She is not in a good shape since she has an injury to her
leg," India's track coach Hargovind Singh said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
