<HEADLINE> East Asians Continue to Dominate Asiad Track Cycling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- After the Beijing and
Hiroshima meets, East Asian teams continued to dominate the Asian
Games track cycling events, taking five out of the seven golds at
stake at the Hua Mark Velodrome here in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, winning the other two golds, is the only central
Asian country which could challenge the powerhouses like Japan,
South Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
Men's sprint is still Japan's domain, with Keirin racers
Yoichiro Kamiyama and Nariaki Mabuchi completing a one-two finish.
</P>
<P>
But the victories have the historical significance as Kamiyama
becomes the first professional cyclist grabbing an Asian Games
gold.
</P>
<P>
However, Japan lost the men's 1-km time trial to South Korean
Ji Sung-Hwan.
</P>
<P>
South Korea became the winners again in the team pursuit event,
beating old rival Kazakhstan in the final to repeat its victory in
Hiroshima four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the central Asian state is still unbeatable in the
individual longer distance races, as Vadim Kravchenko kept his
4-km pursuit title and his compatriot Sergey Lavrenenko excelled
in the heatly contested 40-km points race.
</P>
<P>
China proved its strength in the women's events by claiming all
the golds and silvers.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qingzhi successfully retained her 3-km individual pursuit
title in her last Asiad competition and Wang Yan battled against a
fatal disease to triumph in the sprint.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei emerged as the potential title contender in the
next Games as it won three bronzes here.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the team, who came empty-handed from Hiroshima,
attributed the progress to shifting focus from long distance
events to shorter ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
