<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Rate Hits 5.5 Percent in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The provisional seasonally
adjusted unemployment rate for the period September-November 1998
was 5.5 percent, and the provisional underemployment rate was 2.9
percent, according to the latest labor force statistics released
Thursday by the Census and Statistics Department of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
For the period August-October 1998, the seasonally adjusted
unemployment rate was revised marginally downwards, from the
earlier provisional figure of 5.3 percent to 5.2 percent, while
the underemployment rate remained the same as the earlier
provisional figure of 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the period September-November 1998 with
August-October 1998, the increase in the unemployment rate occurred
mainly in the decoration and maintenance, manufacturing, business
services, import/export trades and transport sectors.
</P>
<P>
As to the underemployment rate, increases were scored in the
manufacturing, decoration and maintenance and retail sectors. The
unemployment and underemployment rates in the other major sectors
remained relatively stable.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the latest figures, Government economist K Y Tang
 said that both the seasonally adjusted unemployment rate and the
underemployment rate showed a further rise in September-November,
as the downward adjustment in the economy continued along with
reduced business volumes and further down-sizing in the corporate
sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that on current indications, and having regard to the
fact that both are lagged indicators of economic activity, the
unemployment and underemployment rates were likely to stay high in
the short term.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Education and Manpower Joseph W P Wong reaffirmed
the Government's commitment to do its utmost to help the
unemployed return to the workforce as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is undergoing a major economic adjustment brought on
largely by repercussions of the regional financial turmoil.
Unemployment will remain on the high side for some time as a
result of corporate down- sizing and layoffs during this process.
</P>
<P>
"However, several positive developments have emerged in the
most recent period. These include declining local interest rates,
moderating inflation and a rebound in asset prices, which have
helped to improve sentiments in the local market.
</P>
<P>
"These, together with the inherent flexibility of our economy,
should enable Hong Kong to emerge more robust and competitive in
the longer term," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Absorb Foreign Investment: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China will continue to give
priority to attracting more foreign investment, An Min, assistant
minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon after the Fifth Chinese Mainland, Taiwan
and Hong Kong Trade and Economic Forum opened here, An Min listed
the major measures China is adopting to absorb more foreign
investment as the following:
</P>
<P>
-- further optimizing the industrial structure of foreign
investment. Foreign investment is mainly encouraged in such
sectors as agriculture, industries-based high and new
technologies, basic industries, infrastructure, environmental
protection industry, and export-oriented industry;
</P>
<P>
-- Continuing to enlarge areas for foreign investment in
petrochemical industry, construction sector, service trade, the
exploration and development of mineral and tourism resources and
water transportation. More liberalization will be adopted for
foreign investment in service industries such as accounting, legal
and consulting services, air transport and freight forwarding
business;
</P>
<P>
-- Further improving the geographic pattern of foreign
investment. The state continues to support the eastern area in its
efforts to develop capital- and technology-intensive industries
and export-oriented industries, and gives priority to central and
 western areas in the arrangement of a group of projects of
agriculture, water conservation, communications, energy, raw
materials and environmental protection for attracting foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
Foreign invested enterprises in the eastern region are
encouraged to reinvest in the western and central regions, and
when foreign investment ratio is over 25 percent in such projects,
they will be deemed as enterprises with foreign investment,
eligible for relevant treatment;
</P>
<P>
-- Absorbing foreign investment through multiple channels and
ways. Efforts will be continuously made to absorb investments from
Hong Kong, Macao, Taiwan, and Southeast Asian nations. Efforts
will be intensified to attract investments from Japan and North
American and European Union countries;
</P>
<P>
-- And actively guiding the investments by multinational
corporations, and improving the investment environment.
</P>
<P>
On Hong Kong investments in the mainland, An said that Hong
Kong has always been the single largest source of overseas
investment for the mainland, with the number of investment
projects and realized value of foreign direct investment both
accounting for over half of its total stocks.
</P>
<P>
With Hong Kong's many advantages in financing, information,
market development, management and cultural intermediary, and the
mainland's fairly strong manufacturing base, abundant technical
personnel and relatively low labor cost, the two sides can
complement each other in many fields, especially in the field of
scientific and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said the 21st century will be an era of knowledge-based
economy. Cooperation between the two sides in the areas of science
and high technology and their related industries can certainly
become a new economic growth point for both sides.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that by the end of October this year,
China has cumulatively approved 321,034 foreign investment
projects with a contractual value of 560.675 billion U.S. dollars,
of which 257.778 billion U.S. dollars have already been brought
in. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
