<HEADLINE> Turkey to Withdraw Diplomats From Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem said Thursday that most officials in the Turkish
Embassy in Iraq are preparing to leave the country.
</P>
<P>
The upcoming pullout of diplomats was decided on after the
U.S. air strike against Iraq, Cem said at a press conference, but
he did not give a specific time of the pullout.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain launched air raids on Iraq Wednesday night,
killing at least two Iraqis and wounding 30 others.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said that the raids was staged in
retaliation for Iraq's defiance of the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM), which monitors Iraq's disarming of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
Cem said that Turkish Ambassador to Baghdad Selim Karaosmanoglu
and several embassy officials will stay behind "upon their own
will."
</P>
<P>
He also said that Turkey attaches great importance to the
protection of territorial integrity and political unity of
Iraq. But Iraq should fully abide by the U.N. Security Council
resolutions, he added.
</P>
<P>
The council imposed sanctions on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990 and maintains that the sanctions will not be lifted
until UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has cleared off all its banned
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Turkey believes that Iraq, which is an important member of the
international society, should gain its place again and the
sanctions on Iraq should end, Cem stressed.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey also requests the end of the pain and sufferings of
the Iraqi people who pay the heaviest price in the crisis," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
