<HEADLINE> U.N. Hosts Talks to Settle Conflict in Georgia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Talks aimed at bringing peace
to Abkhazia, Georgia began here Thursday at the sponsorship of the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The Georgian delegation is led by State Minister of Georgia
Vazha Lordkipanidze while the Abkhaz delegation is led by de facto
Prime Minister Sergei Bagapsh, said the United Nations Office at
Geneva (UNOG).
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting was opened by the Special Representative of
the U.N. Secretary-General for Georgia Liviu Bota.
</P>
<P>
In his opening statement, Bota noted that the Coordinating
Council of the Georgian and Abkhaz sides, in accordance with its
statute, met alternatively between Tbilisi and Sukhumi.
</P>
<P>
As an exception, this session was being held in Geneva but it
should not be considered as a precedent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The draft agenda for the meeting includes issues related to the
lasting non-resumption of hostilities and to security problems,
refugees and internally displaced persons, and economic and social
problems.
</P>
<P>
Bota stressed that the fate of the refugees was a matter of
utmost importance and their return was a humanitarian priority in
itself.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth session of the Coordinating Council of the
Georgian and Abkhaz Sides, part of the Geneva peace process for
the settlement of the war in Abkhaz, Georgia, which broke out in
1993.
</P>
<P>
Since the fifth session held last September, the council has
been convened at the level of heads of government, said the UNOG.
</P>
</TEXT>
