<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Give Advice on Chinese Future Agricultural Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 60 world well-known
agricultural scientists offered their advice on Chinese future
agricultural development in a book, "Agriculture in China
1949--2030", which was published today.
</P>
<P>
In the 400,000-character book, Chinese and foreign experts
elaborated their views on how to feed Chinese population due to
reach its peak in 2030.
</P>
<P>
The book summarizes Chinese agricultural achievement since 1949
and covers various pressing issues in agricultural development
including planting, animal husbandry, analysis to agricultural
resources and utilization, agricultural production, technologies
and economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Chinese population is expected to peak at 1.6 billion in 2030
and its food demand is estimated to reach 640 million tons at that
time.
</P>
<P>
China should develop its agriculture to full capacity in
accordance to its natural resources and ecological conditions to
support the well-being of its people, said Doctor Tian Chich Tso,
a famous Chinese American scientist and one of the main authors of
the book.
</P>
<P>
Writing in the book, experts adviced the Chinese government to
select officers responsible for agriculture based on true
understanding and knowledge of agricultural science and
technology, and the ability to initiate and promote international
agricultural cooperation and exchange.
</P>
<P>
They recommend that Chinese agricultural teaching, research,
and extension systems be united to serve the farmers. And China
should greatly increase investment in agricultural research.
</P>
<P>
They also advice China to increase water-usage efficiency and
find new water resources and control environmental
pollution. China should establish a sound, credible and timely
information and statistical system for scientific long-term
projection and policy decisions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
