<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Reunification Mode Inapplicable for China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
United Nations Resolution No.2758 expelled the representative
of the Taiwan authorities from the United Nations and its
subordinate organizations in October, 1971. The government of the
PRC thereafter resumed its UN membership, while East and West
Germanys were both UN members in 1973.
</P>
<P>
Tao said more than 160 nations recognize the government of the
PRC as the sole legitimate government representing China, with
only 20-odd countries maintaining official ties with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
While not a single country maintains diplomatic ties with both
sides across the Taiwan Straits, East and West Germanys
simultaneously maintained diplomatic relations with third
countries, according to Tao.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that East and West Germanys recognized each other
and maintain formal ties, while Chinese people and the PRC
government have always opposed "two Chinas" or "one China, one
Taiwan."
</P>
<P>
Tao pointed out that Taiwan authorities are simply trying to
use the German mode of reunification as a tool to replace the
mainland's socialist system with capitalism, or to indefinitely
maintain separation across the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
The German mode proposed by Taiwan authorities is also designed
to counter the "one country, two systems" principle, said Tao.
</P>
<P>
He said the smooth return of Hong Kong to the motherland
convinced an increasing number of Taiwan compatriots of the
mainland's sincerity in realizing reunification and enabled them
to better understand the "one country, two systems" principle.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Germany achieved reunification after four decades
separation, Tao expressed hope that Taiwan authorities will comply
with contemporary trends and take practical steps under the "one
China" principle to ensure the early reunification of the
motherland.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
