<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Warns of Risk of TB Transmission in Air Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has given a caution to the world's 1.4 billion air
passengers that they should take proper measures to minimize risk
of infection of tuberculosis (TB).
</P>
<P>
"We want to make air travel safer, reduce the risk of TB
transmission and increase passengers' confidence that they are
adequately protected from risk of infection when they travel,"
said Dr Mario Raviglione of WHO's Communicable Disease Operational
and Epidemiological Research unit here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said this when launching a booklet entitled "Tuberculosis
and Air Travel: Guidelines for Prevention and Control."
</P>
<P>
These guidelines would serve as a substantial aid to air
passengers. While stressing the risk is low, WHO said that TB
transmission during air travel has been documented.
</P>
<P>
Within the next decade, the International Civil Aviation
Organization (ICAO) expects that more than 2 billion passengers
per year will travel by plane.
</P>
<P>
"Long-haul flights combined with the confined space of a
passenger cabin and the close proximity to co-passengers from the
entire world may facilitate the spread of contagious diseases,"
said Dr Claus Curdt-Christiansen of the ICAO.
</P>
<P>
"It is to be hoped that WHO's guidelines will be studied by all
doctors related to the airline industry and its regulatory
agencies and that the recommendations given will be implemented
without delay by health authorities and airline companies
worldwide," said Curdt-Christiansen.
</P>
<P>
In the guidelines, WHO suggested that maximum efficiency air
filters be installed and properly maintained on all aircraft and
ground delays kept to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
It advised anyone with infectious TB to postpone travel until
they become non-infectious, adding that "boarding can and should
be denied to persons known to have infectious TB." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
