<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grizzly Discovery Made in Nanjing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The dismembered remains of
Chinese victims who had died as a result of bacteriological
experiments carried out by invading Japanese troops during the War
of Resistance Against Japanese Aggression (1937-45) were
discovered earlies this year in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
The remains were discovered last August at a construction site
in the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province. Autopsies and
extensive research of documents proved that victims died as a
result of related experiments, according to an official with the
Nanjing Information Press Office.
</P>
<P>
The discovery included the decapitated heads of 29 victims,
including one female. The victims were between 17 and 38 years of
age. The heads were found in wooden boxes, with some boxes holding
several heads, and others containing skeletal remains.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Military pathologists collected samples of bones, boxes
and dirt at the excavation site and determined that the samples
contained traces of cholera toxins resulting from microbial
separation tests. The pathologists also confirmed that the victims
died as a result of bacterial experiments conducted by members of
the japanese Unit No.1644.
</P>
<P>
Historical documents indicate that the Japanese
Bacterialoglical Experimentation Unit No.731 was stationed in
Harbin, capital of northeast China's Heilongjiang Province, in
1933. Unit No.1644 was stationed in Nanjing, with other units
formed in Beijing and Guangzhou around 1939. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
