<HEADLINE> S. African FM: Using Force Is No Answer to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa did not
believe that using force would resolve the dispute over Iraq's
non-compliance with United Nations resolutions, Foreign Minister
Alfred Nzo said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the air strikes launched overnight by the United
States and Britain on Iraq, Nzo said in a statement South Africa
fully supported all U.N. Security Council resolutions on the need
for Iraq to comply.
</P>
<P>
However, South Africa did not believe force would resolve the
issues relating to the activities of the UN special commission
and the International Atomic Energy Agency in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Nzo expressed his "deep concern" about the surprise air
strikes against Iraq during a meeting with the deputy chief of
mission of the United States embassy in Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
The lack of unanimity by the members of the U.N. Security
Council on the decision to strike was of concern to the South
African government, he said.
</P>
<P>
These actions would inevitably lead to greater human suffering
for the people of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Nzo again called on all sides to seek a negotiated settlement
and to avoid any further actions which would aggravate tensions
in the region.  
</P>
