<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Land Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Li Yuang, vice minister of
the Land and Natural Resources Ministry, said today that
China will further improve enforcement of land protection.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the new Land Law, effective January 1, 1999, will
give land departments under the State Council greater power to
investigate and adjudicate land cases.
</P>
<P>
Land departments at higher levels will have the power to deal
directly with land cases beyond the scope of lower level
departments and punish officials for inappropriate actions in
accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
Li stressed the need to seriously implement the general land
use plan and strictly control land used for urban construction.
</P>
<P>
"Directors of land bureaus at all levels will be responsible
for protecting cultivated land in their administrative
regions," according to Li.
</P>
<P>
He added that China will form a powerful enforcement system and
will strictly deal with illegal land occupation cases.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has handled 30-odd land cases during 1998, with a
number of city, county and township leaders receiving various
levels of punishment and a number of local land bureau directors
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
Ren Yao, former director of the Yanta District Land Bureau in
the northwest China city Xi'an is currently the subject of a
judicial investigation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
