<HEADLINE> Malaysian Senate Condemns U.S., Britain for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Dewan Negara
(Senate) Thursday unanimously approved a motion condemning the
United States and Britain for launching air strikes against Iraq,
the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The Upper House has resolved to convey the resolution to the
U.S. Embassy and British High Commission in Kuala Lumpur, and the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Tabling the motion, Senator Mohd Zuki Kamaluddin described the
attacks as a blatant violation of Iraqi sovereignty and the human
rights of its people.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the U.S. and Britain do not respect the
sensitivities of Muslims who will be welcoming the fasting month,
especially the people of Iraq who are living in fear and sadness,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mohd Zuki said the military action showed that the United
Nations Security Council had failed to prevent the U.S. and
Britain from continuing to bully Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He urged the U.N. to lift its economic sanction on Iraq as it
has caused the deaths of almost 1.5 million Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
In debating the motion, six senators strongly condemned the
attacks, and urged the U.N. Security Council to immediately stop
the air strikes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
