<HEADLINE> Jordan Regrets at U.S. Air Raids on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordan on Thursday expressed
regrets over the U.S.- Britain air strikes on Iraq and called on
the world community to take into considerations the Iraqi people
and its long time sufferings.
</P>
<P>
At an emergency meeting of the Supreme Council of Defense after
the air raids on Iraq, Prime Minister Fayez Tarawneh called for
measures to be taken to prevent any destabilization efforts
against Jordan from both inside or outside the Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordan closed its border with Iraq early Thursday morning to
prevent a sudden influx of Iraqi refugees into the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Tarawaneh said that foreign minster Abdul Itah Khatib is in
contacts with ambassadors from the five permanent members of
the U.N. Security Council to get acquainted with the latest
developments of the Iraqi crises.
</P>
<P>
He said Jordan is following the Iraqi crises with extreme
concern and utmost seriousness.
</P>
<P>
Khatib said Wednesday that resorting to military action will
not solve the crises arsing from the inspection of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said in a statement that "the best means
to resolve the crisis would be to adhere to international
legitimacy to arrive at a comprehensive review with the objective
of ending the sufferings of the brotherly Iraqi people". 
</P>
</TEXT>
