<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korea's Top Businesses' Unveil Agreements on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Four of South Korea's top five
family-own conglomerates, or chaebols, unveiled their agreements
with major creditors on improvement of their financial situation.
</P>
<P>
They are Hyundai, Samsung, LG and SK. The exception is Daewoo.
</P>
<P>
Under an commitment on financial improvement signed with Korean
Exchange Bank, Hyundai will lower the debt ratio from 508.1
percent at the end of last June to 199.7 percent by the end of
next year and to 177.6 percent by 2000 and reduce its number of
subsidiaries to 30 from 63 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai will raise 5.892 billion U.S. dollars of foreign
capital by the end of this year and 4.565 billion U.S. dollars
next year through sell-off of its subsidiaries, joint ventures and
issuance of convertible bonds.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hyundai will focus on the industries of automobile,
electronics, construction, heavy and chemicals, and finance and
services as long-run strategy.
</P>
<P>
The LG Group will slash the debt ratio from the current 364
percent to 199.8 percent by the end of next year and to 186.4
percent by the year of 2000.
</P>
<P>
In an agreement signed with its major creditor, Commercial Bank
of Korea, LG will reduce the number of its subsidiaries from
current 53 to 32 by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
LG will foster key businesses in chemicals and energy,
electronics and communications, service and finance.
</P>
<P>
It will raise 17 trillion won through issuance of shares, sale
of assets and attraction of foreign capital by the year 2002 and
raise 6.5 billion U.S. dollars through sell-off of business units
or foreign equity participation.
</P>
<P>
LG also said that it will make efforts to have the integrated
corporation of its semiconductor sector with Hyundai decided by
December 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
Samsung also signed a treaty with Hanil Bank Thursday while SK
signed a pact with Korea First Bank. They promised to improve
their finance by cutting their debt ratios and ailing subsidiaries
and focusing on core businesses within next tow years.
</P>
<P>
Daewoo and its major creditor Korea First Bank is expected to
sign a similar accord Friday.
</P>
<P>
The five business groups will face suspension of bank credit
and recall of loans already extended unless they implement the
commitment as pledged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
