<HEADLINE> Sydney Backs Changes to Bidding Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Australian Olympic officials
welcomed a proposal to change the way Olympic sites are chosen
amid allegations that the existing bidding process has been
corrupted by bribes, reports from Sydney said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
John Coates, Australian Olympic Committee president, said that
he supported a move by International Olympic Committee (IOC)
president Juan Antonio Samaranch to restrict voting on the
cities, limiting it to the IOC executive board.
</P>
<P>
Coates said that in 1994 the IOC members had rejected a
proposal to change the bidding process but he said it was
unlikely they would do that again in the current climate.
</P>
<P>
Under the IOC's current laws the venues for Olympic Games are
decided by a vote of all 114 IOC members.
</P>
<P>
But Samaranch said the IOC should think of studying another
way of electing the Olympic cities, possibly by restricting the
vote to the 11 executive board members.
</P>
<P>
His proposal came just a day after the IOC announced that it
was investigating allegations over payments made in Salt Lake
City's successful bid to stage the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
Sydney Olympic officials have distanced themselves from
allegations of bribery and corruption although senior officials
believe they have been tarred by the same brush.  Ednitem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
