<HEADLINE> DPRK, Hyundai Agree to Set Up Industrial Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Hyundai Group founder Chung
Ju-yung said Thursday that Hyundai and the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to create a special
industrial zone for South Korean companies in DPRK's western coast.
</P>
<P>
Chung told a press conference that the Hyundai Group agreed
with Kim Yong-sun, chairman of the DPRK Asia-Pacific Peace
Committee, to establish a 20 million-pyong (66 million square
meters) industrial complex on DPRK's western coast for South
Korean companies.
</P>
<P>
Chung gave the press conference Thursday upon returning to
South Korea through the truce village of Panmunjom after a
three-day visit to the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai hopes the industrial zone could be established around
DPRK's western port city of Haeju for South Korean small and
medium-sized companies to further inter-Korean economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"We decided to discuss the exact location of the industrial
complex" during the next visit to DPRK next February, Chung said.
</P>
<P>
The business tycoon said that he has invited Kim Yong-sun,
regarded as DPRK leader Kim Jong-il's right-hand man, to visit
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
"Chairman Kim told us that he had no reason to hesitate to make
a trip to South Korea," he said.
</P>
<P>
Chung's latest visit was his fourth to the DPRK this year.
When he visited Pyongyang on October 30, DPRK leader Kim Jong-il
met him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
