<HEADLINE> Yonekura Wins Women's Badminton Singles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Kanako Yonekura kept
her giant-killing run by beating China's world No. 3 Gong Zhichao
in the women's singles final of the Asian Games badminton
competition on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 47th-ranked Japanese, who upset world No. 1 Ye Zhaoying of
China earlier, won Japan's first Asian Games badminton gold in 28
years with 1-11, 11-5, 11-6 victory over Gong.
</P>
<P>
A tearful Yonekura said after the final that she had been
"ready to play to the death" to end Japan's gold drought.
</P>
<P>
China might have found solace in the men's singles final when
Dong Jiong outlasted world No. 5 H. Hendrawan of Indonesia 17-14,
10-15, 15-8.
</P>
<P>
Gong Zhichao was in control in the first game but Yonekura
changed tactics in the second and waited for the Chinese to make
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
In the decider, they traded points until 5-5 when the Japanese
pulled away with a string of winning drop shots and smashes.
</P>
<P>
The world and Olympic champion combination of Gei Fei and Gu
Jun won China's second gold in the day with a 12-15, 15-9, 15-11
victory over Elysa Nathanael and Deyana Lomban of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia struck gold in the men's doubles as Olympic champions
Ricky Subagdja and Rexy Mainaky retained their title with a 15-5,
15-10 win over Pramote Teerawiwatana and Siripong Siripool of
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The all South Korean mixed doubles final was won by Kim
Dong-Moon and La Kyung-Min who defeated Lee Dong-Soo and Yim
Kyung-Jin 15-6, 15-8.  
</P>
</TEXT>
