<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Reunification Mode Inapplicable for China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The German mode of
reunification is inapplicable for China and the purpose of related
claims made by Taiwan authorities is to hinder cross-Straits
reunification and split China in perpetuity, according to a
Chinese law specialist.
</P>
<P>
An article by Tao Zhenghua, a research fellow with the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences (CASS), points out that the German mode
of reunification centered on a historical process of separation
due to special factors.
</P>
<P>
Germany realized reunification on October 3, 1990, with the
federation's basic law entering effect following an amendment
process, according to Tao.
</P>
<P>
He said the essence of recent calls Taiwan authorities made to
reunify China in accordance with German mode center on "ruling the
country separately first" in advance of "reunification."
</P>
<P>
Tao said China and Germany have completely different histories
and legal backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
Germany's separation resulted from World War II, which is
recognized by international treaties, said Tao, adding that
China's separation resulted from civil war and U.S. armed
occupation of Taiwan to prevent the Chinese people from liberating
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The governments of East and West Germanys were established with
the support of the former Soviet Union and the United States,
while the People's Republic of China (PRC) was resulted from
victory in the Chinese People's Revolution. Taiwan authorities are
simply the remnants of the overthrown government, said Tao.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan has always been a part of China in terms of both
territory and population, while East and West Germanys represented
a completely different situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
