<HEADLINE> Egyptian Students Protest Against US Attacks on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Egyptian university
students held demonstrations Thursday to protest against the
overnight air strikes on Iraq by the United States and Britain,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
About 3,000 students of Cairo University marched into the
streets upon hearing the news of the strike, shouting slogans of
solidarity with the Iraqi people, security officials said.
</P>
<P>
"We would sacrifice our souls and blood to you Iraq," the
students shouted. They dispersed peacefully two hours later.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ministry of Interior has tightened security measures
around the U.S., British and Israeli embassies in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain fired hundreds of missiles at Iraq through
the night for what U.S. President Bill Clinton said a retaliation
for Iraq's defiance of the United Nations Special Commission
(UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM oversees the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction, a must for the U.N. Security Council to lift the
economic sanctions imposed on Iraq after its 1990 invasion of
Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
