<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary: EU Committed to Comprehensive Engagment With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Relations between the European
Union (EU) and China "have never been so close as now", according
to diplomatic envoys from the EU Troika countries.
</P>
<P>
In a recent press conference here, Josef Mullner, Charge
D'affairs Ad Interim of the Austrian Embassy to China, said that
the EU has put its relations with China on a par with those of the
United States and other powers.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, China has become an increasingly important partner with
the EU. Since the beginning of this year, the EU has adopted a
series of policies and measures, including suspending the tabling
of proposals against China to the annual Human Rights Conference
of the United Nations and listing China amongst "non-market
economy countries". Moreover, the EU endorsed a policy document
entitled "Building a Comprehensive Partnership with China" to push
ahead EU-China ties.
</P>
<P>
These EU's initiatives have met with positive responses from
China. Chinese leaders Li Peng and Zhu Rongji visited Holland,
Britain, France and other EU nations this year, while the
president of the European Commission Jacques Santer,
vice-president Leon Brittan and the prime ministers of five EU
nations, including Britain and France, paid official visits to
China.
</P>
<P>
German chancellor Gerhard Schroeder hopes to visit China next
May, when he is expected to attend the second EU-China meeting
when his country holds the annual presidency of the EU. German
Ambassador to China Konrad Seitz revealed this today but details
of the visit are still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
The growth of EU-China relations has benefited both sides. The
trade volume between China and the EU has witnessed a noticeable
expansion while China's trade volume with its neighboring Asian
countries decreased this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Chinese customs statistics, the trade volume
between China and the EU reached 33.89 billion U.S. dollars in the
first three quarters of 1998, an increase of 16.6 percent compared
with the same period last year. China's imports from the EU
accounts for 13 percent of its total imports and China has become
the third largest non-European trading partner of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The EU's comprehensive engagement with China represents not
only economic considerations, but also the EU's ambitious strategy
to enjoy a bigger role in global affairs. China's rapid economic
growth and its increasingly important world status explains the
basic reason why the EU has adopted a more positive China policy.
</P>
<P>
In a world that is moving towards multi-polarization, a closer
EU-China relationship would certainly benefit both sides, and the
world at large.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
