<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electronic Parking Devices to Cover Whole of HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Following a successful
trial, the second phase of a new electronic parking devices (EPDs)
conversion program will cover all but one districts of Hong Kong
by March next year, it was announced here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference on the launch of the second
phase of the program, Principal Transport Officer Management Peter
Luk said that all districts, except "New Territories" East, will
be equipped with the new parking system.
</P>
<P>
The Transport Department official said that in the initial
phase of the program, about one-quarter of the 14,000 mechanical
parking meters in Hong Kong have been replaced by EPDs. Almost all
the rest -- about 10,000 within most of Hong Kong's districts --
will be converted to new devices in the second phase, which begins
on December 27 and ends next March.
</P>
<P>
In phase one of the conversion program which began in April
this year, a total of 3,500 mechanical meters in some districts on
Hong Kong Island and in Kowloon have been changed into EPDs within
two months.
</P>
<P>
In the second phase, the mechanical meters will be replaced by
9,000 electronic parking meters (EPMs) and 50 pay-and-display
machines (PDMs), with the conversion first implemented in
districts on Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
A few mechanical meters in "New Territories" East and some
remote areas will be replaced by EPDs at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
Both EPMs and PDMs are operated by a common smart card and
e-Park Card issued by the Transport Department, with the number of
sales outlets for e-Park Cards to be doubled to 500 in the second
phase.
</P>
<P>
The new parking system has been well received by motorists. The
first phase performed satisfactorily in key aspects including
operation, maintenance and in managing and retrieving relevant
information and data.
</P>
<P>
On average, the utilization of EPMs has increased by 16 percent
compared to the rate drawn by mechanical parking meters before
their replacement while the number of complaints has dropped by 84
per cent.
</P>
<P>
Luk promised to closely monitor the operation of the new
devices and introduce improvements if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
