<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Foreign Debt Goes Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's foreign debt went
down to 84.7 billion U.S. dollars as of December 10, a decline of
10 billion dollars from July last year when the baht began to be
floated.
</P>
<P>
Thai central bank officials said on Thursday that existing debt
levels include 12 billion baht (330 million dollars) in loans from
the International Monetary Fund, which pointed to the sharp fall
in private-sector foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
Current foreign debt levels stood at about 60 percent of the
country's Gross National Product (GNP), well below the 80 percent
level considered dangerous.
</P>
<P>
The central bank predicted that foreign debt would fall to 48
percent of GNP within the next several years.
</P>
<P>
The terms of the obligation debt had also changed, with
short-term debt now accounting for just 26 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Thailand would have to begin repaying its loans to the IMF
within 18 months, according to the officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
