<HEADLINE> Greek Armed Forces Closely Watching Situation in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Greece's armed forces have been
since Wednesday closely monitoring the situation in Iraq following
air strikes launched overnight by the U.S. and Britain against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Greek National Defense General Staff's operations center
had been put on alert since Wednesday after the evacuation of
U.N. arms inspectors from Iraq, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) quoted sources close to the National Defense General
Staff (GEETHA) as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Greece had no involvement in the events, the sources said,
adding that 11 Greek U.N. observers, currently at the Iraqi border
with Kuwait and in northern Iraq, were facing no problems.
</P>
<P>
The Greek media on Thursday also expressed their opposition to
the air strikes, saying that President Bill Clinton had launched
the military attacks against Iraq in order to postpone the
impeachment vote by U.S. House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Greece has repeatedly said that it opposes the settlement of
Iraq's disputes with U.N. arms inspectors through military
actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
