<HEADLINE> Finland Deplores Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Finland Thursday expressed
deep regrets over the U.S.-British air strikes against Iraq and
hoped for an earliest possible end to the military actions.
</P>
<P>
Finnish Prime Minister Paavo Lipponen said that he totally
agreed with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan who described
Thursday as a "sad day" because the efforts to settle the Iraq
crisis through peaceful and diplomatic means suffered a setback.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Tarja Halonen also expressed regrets over the
deterioration of the situation, saying that although the
international community had made great efforts, Iraq and the
U.N. weapons inspectors failed to cooperate with each other.
</P>
<P>
She wished that the military strikes end Friday when the muslim
holy month of Ramadan begins.
</P>
<P>
Pertti Torstila, director of the political department of the
Finnish foreign ministry, said that the United States and Britain
should be responsible for their use of force in the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
Finland will closely follow the development of the situation,
Torstila added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
