<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Co-operation Between HK SAR, China's Mainland Police Brings Down Illegal Immigration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Excellent co-operation
between Police of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) and South China's Guangdong Province has brought down the
figures of illegal immigrants, according to deputy commissioner of
Hong Kong SAR's Police here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
An eight-member delegation of Hong Kong Police led by Wong
Tsan-kwong, the deputy commissioner, returned from Shantou of
South China's Guangdong Province Wednesday evening after a two-day
meeting with the Guangdong Border Defense Bureau (GDBDB).
</P>
<P>
"The meeting examined ways to further enhance liaison and the
efficiency in the handling of intelligence in combating illegal
immigration," a Police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"Both sides reviewed the anti-illegal immigration tactics and
explored various means to further strengthen enforcement action
which included the exchange of skills and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the encouraging results in the
anti-illegal immigration work brought about by the excellent
co-operation between Hong Kong Police and the GDBDB," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
During their visit to Shantou, Hong Kong Police delegation
viewed the illegal immigration and smuggling blackspots in the
city and the delegation was also briefed on GDBDB's measures to
fight against illegal immigration.
</P>
<P>
The GDBDB patrol vessels made a first ever visit to Hong Kong
SAR in June and the Hong Kong Marine Police made a reciprocal
visit to Guangdong in September.
</P>
<P>
By November this year, 13,201 illegal immigrants have been
arrested, which represented a 20 percent drop compared with 16,435
illegal immigrants netted during the corresponding period last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
