<HEADLINE> FIFA Sells Brazil 2002, 2006 World Cup TV Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- FIFA,the world soccer
governing body, has sold the 2002 and 2006 World Cups television
rights in Brazil to the country's dominant broadcaster Rede
Globo, according to FIFA's marketing partner Thursday.
</P>
<P>
ISL, which markets top events for many of the world's leading
international sports organisations, said the multi-million dollar
deal for Brazilian TV rights was the first to be signed for the
next two World Cup tournaments.
</P>
<P>
ISL spokesman Daniel Beauvois gave no value for the contract
but said FIFA was guaranteed to receive 2.8 billion Swiss francs
($2.09 billion) for TV rights to the 2002 and 2006 World Cups
from Europe, Latin America, Canada, Asia, the Middle East,
Oceania and Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 2002 World Cup will be co-hosted by Japan and South Korea.
Brazil is bidding for the 2006 World Cup along with Egypt,
England, Germany, Ghana, Morocco and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
