<HEADLINE> Malaysian FM Condemns Military Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign
Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi Thursday condemned the unilateral
military strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"This violates the principle of peaceful settlement of disputes
and the Charter of the United Nations," he said in a statement
released by the Foreign Ministry here.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the unilateral action on Iraq has set a
dangerous precedent and Malaysia urged member countries of the
Non-Aligned Movement (NAM) and the Organization of Islamic
Conference (OIC) to oppose in the strongest manner this action by
the U.S.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia counsels dialogue and consultation which is essential
to maintain the credibility of the United Nations process to
monitor Iraq's disarmament program. Malaysia sees no justification
for the military action which constitutes an aggression against
Iraq and which has also undermined the mandate of the U.N.
Security Council," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that an emergency session of the U.N. Security Council
should be convened immediately to discuss the situation and to
bring a stop to the military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said: "Iraq on its part must also ensure full
compliance with U.N. Security Council resolutions. The
eight-year-old sanctions have already exacted an excessive toll on
Iraq and its people and, in this regard, the latest U.S. military
strikes are totally ill-conceived. They only further undermine
peace and security in the region."
</P>
<P>
"Force cannot be used as a means to deal with international
disputes except where aggression has been committed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Thursday in Hanoi, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad also condemned the U.S.-led air strikes on Iraq, saying
"We don't think that there should be any use of force." 
</P>
</TEXT>
