<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Cabinet Discusses Precautions After </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti cabinet held
an extraordinary meeting Thursday morning to discuss necessary
precautions after the U.S. launched military strikes against Iraq
overnight.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Al-Dekheel, the deputy prime minister and minister of
state for cabinet affairs, said the meeting reviewed the situation
after the air raid which took place at about midnight local time
(2200 GMT) Wednesday, the official news agency Kuna reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also listened to a number of reports by ministers on
defensive and security preparations to maintain the country's
sovereignty and stability, Al-Dekheel said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed the need to secure basic services and
requirements for citizens and residents, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990 triggered the 1991 Gulf War
and led to the U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq designed to ensure
that Baghdad clears off all its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Disputes over weapons inspections between Iraq and the
U.N. Special Commission, which oversees Iraq's disarmament, have
erupted into several crises.
</P>
<P>
Al-Dekheel said the cabinet has entrusted all concerned bodies
to take measures to face various emergencies and urged all
citizens to give assistance.
</P>
<P>
He said the cabinet will follow up the Iraqi crisis, but
expressed hope that all reasons behind the escalation of tension
will be addressed and all the people in the region be able to live
in peace.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton announced in a televised national
speech Thursday morning that he ordered the strike in retaliation
for Baghdad's obstruction of international weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon has said that about 200 Tomahawk cruise missiles
were fired at targets in Southern and Northern Iraq, as well as in
Baghdad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
