<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Plant More autumn and Winter Crops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China's farmers planted more
crops in this year's autumn and winter season which will help
alleviate shortages due to the severe floods which devastated this
summer's grain harvest.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the floods, official estimates indicate that
the harvest fell to 113.1 billion kilograms, eleven percent less
than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But the National Bureau of Statistics (NBS) has revealed that
there has been a 2.2 percent increase in the late seasons'
plantings.
</P>
<P>
This followed a survey of 40,000 rural households in 700
counties which indicates that grain growing areas will actually be
down by 0.4 percent, to 29.8 million hectares, but that there will
be increased plantings of other crops.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ministry of Agriculture there were plans to
plant more than 30 million hectares of grain. However, the NBS
believes that because of comparatively lower returns on grain,
farmers are now more enthusiastic about growing high cash yield
crops.
</P>
<P>
For example, because of rising prices, farmers have increased
areas planted with oil-bearing crops and there will also be an
increase in the planting of vegetables and crops used for forage
this winter.
</P>
<P>
The NBS survey shows that the areas planted with wheat, a major
winter grain crop, will have decreased by 1.1 percent to 25.6 ha
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture noted that this season's planting
still faced some unfavorable conditions such as drought in the
northern part of the country, even though there has been unusually
high temperatures.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
