<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Highest Court to Reopen Debate Over Pinochet Immunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Law Lords decided on
Thursday to open a fresh hearing into the question of whether
former Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet has immunity from
extradition.
</P>
<P>
The House of Lords, the Highest Court in the United Kingdom, had
been asked by Pinochet's lawyers to set aside its previous rule
which said that he had no immunity.
</P>
<P>
The lawyers argued that one of the judges involved in the
previous decision was biased because of his close association with
the human rights group Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
After spending two days on listening to Pinochet's Lawyers'
arguments, a special panel agreed that a fresh hearing should be
held to decide whether the 83-year-old general should enjoy
immunity.
</P>
<P>
The new hearing is scheduled to be held in January. If
Pinochet wins, he will be free to leave Britain and will not face
trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet is being detained in Britain on a Spanish warrant
seeking his extradition to face charges of murder. A Spanish
judge accused him of responsibility to the deaths and
disappearances of 3,000 people during his 17-year rule which ended
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
On November 25, a panel of five Law Lords ruled by three to two
that he had no immunity from prosecution as a former head of state
and a current Chilean senator.
</P>
<P>
One of the three judges who ruled against Pinochet, Lord
Hoffmann, is chairman of Amnesty's charitable arm while his wife
was an administrative assistance in the human rights body.
</P>
<P>
"Lord Hoffmann, who did not disclose his links with Amnesty
International was disqualified from sitting," Lord
Browne-Wilkinson, who presided over the appeal, said. The other
four judges sitting with him said they agreed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
