<HEADLINE> Share Prices Seen Fall and Bounce on Singapore Bourse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Share prices were seen fall
and bounce on Singapore Stock Market Thursday following the
U.S.-led air raids on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark Straits Times Index (STI) inched up 5.54 points
to 1,364.64 at close, bouncing off the intra-day low of 1,324.62
points.
</P>
<P>
Share prices plummeted in the morning session following the
U.S.-led strike on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The bounce emerged in late morning as some investors came back
into the market hunting for value on hopes that the U.S.-led air
strike on Iraq would be short-lived.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said these investors held the view that the air raids
would not last beyond the weekend.
</P>
<P>
They said the entry into the market by bargain hunters turned
banks and blue chips from losers into gainers.
</P>
<P>
The total turnover increased to 200.37 million units worth
316.28 million Singapore dollars (about 191.86 million U.S.
dollars). Losers outstripped gainers by 189 to 61 with 169
counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
KepB w0006 remained at the top of the actives chart of the day
with a turnover of 12.58 million units. KepLand was the second
most heavily traded stock with a volume of 8.09 million units
done. Wing T was next with 7.74 million counters changing hands.
</P>
<P>
UOB F was the biggest gainer of the day as it gained 55 cents
to 10.50 Singapore dollars. OCBC F picked up 50 cents to close at
11.00 Singapore dollars. Elec&AMP;E rose by 29 cents to end at 15.05
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 led the descent of the day with a
loss of 100 cents to 25.50 Singapore dollars. SPH 100 was next
shedding 20 cents to close at 17.30 Singapore dollars. ANA Ho sank
15 cents to end at 1.25 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
