<HEADLINE> British Muslims, Peace Groups Protest Iraq Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- British Muslims and peace
groups on Thursday condemned U.S.-initiated and U.K.-supported air
strikes on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Muslim groups and peace activists organized protests outside
Downing Street, where Prime Minister Tony Blair announced the air
raids on Wednesday evening London time. Someone daubed graffiti
on Britain's Cenotaph war memorial near Blair's office.
</P>
<P>
"The attack is a panic reaction by a besieged president,
totally irresponsible and the work of a leader bent on saving his
presidency," Reuters quoted the leader of the self-styled Muslim
Parliament of Great Britain, Ghayasuddin Siddiqui, as saying in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Siddiqui said that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, "a creation
of the West allowed to survive the Gulf War, has once again been
used as a justification for maintaining a strong military presence
in the Arabian Peninsula," according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
The hardline Muslim group Al-Muhajiroun was organizing
demonstrations for midday Thursday outside Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
"This is a war against Allah," Al-Muhajiroun declared in a
statement. It said it was hypocritical of the West to use its
latest high-technology weapons to destroy Iraq's "weapons of mass
destruction."
</P>
<P>
"There is no justification for continuing the blockade against
the Muslims of Iraq, let alone renewing U.S. and British military
attacks," Al-Muhajiroun said.
</P>
<P>
Also, the National Peace Council planned a candlelit vigil for
Thursday evening outside Blair's office, including a left-wing
member of the prime minister's Labor party, Tony Benn, Reuters
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
