<HEADLINE> China's Consumer Index Edging Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December (Xinhua) -- China's Consumer Index, an
important indicator of the economic situation, edged down last
month, according to figures released by the National Bureau of
Statistics today.
</P>
<P>
The November Index of Consumer Expectations dropped by 0.9
points on the October base to 91.5 points, according to a survey
of 4,200 consumers conducted by the NBS's Economic Monitoring
Center.
</P>
<P>
Two other indices, related to current economic conditions and
actual consumers, also dropped by small margins.
</P>
<P>
The results indicated that China should pay more attention to
its consumer economic policy, which is a major springboard for
economic development, the bureau noted.
</P>
<P>
Only 38 percent of respondents agreed that the country will
maintain sustainable growth over the next five years. The ratio is
nine percentage points lower than in the previous month, noted the
bureau.
</P>
<P>
The Index of Current Economic Conditions, which indicates
consumer views on current economic conditions, has also dropped
0.9 point to reach 86.4 points.
</P>
<P>
The NBS suggests that the country needs to adopt measures to
help consumers understand more about current world and domestic
economic developments and to stimulate the consumer market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
