<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Launches Fight To Tackle Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Burning coal in the city
center was banned from today in China's capital of Beijing, just
one of 19 emergency measures that officials are taking to curb the
serious air pollution.
</P>
<P>
Beijing's vice-mayor Wang Guangtao said, "All boilers within
the city's third ring road should now use clean fuel such as
natural gas and liquefied petroleum gas."
</P>
<P>
He warned that no new coal-burning facilities should be
built.
</P>
<P>
Other measures introduced from today to clean up Beijing's
highly polluted atmosphere include enforcing strict regulations on
the scrapping of old automobiles and introducing new control
standards on car exhaust emissions, as well as expanding the
greenbelt.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government has also ordered all building firms
to wall off their sites to keep dust and debris from being
spread. It is estimated that Beijing's 5,000-plus construction
sites are responsible for nearly half of the city's air-borne dust
clouds.
</P>
<P>
Beijing has suffered from severe air pollution during recent
years, mostly because its residents burn 28 million tons of coal
every year. In winter, 90 percent of the sulphur dioxide, 50
percent of the nitrogen oxide and 40 percent of suspended
particles in the air are produced from such coal-burning.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the 1.4 million motor vehicles choking up the
city's roads and highways also add to the pollution
problem. Exhaust fumes have become a major air pollutant.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that by using tough measures the municipal government
plans to improve the city's environment by next year and even more
so by the year 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Up on Back of US Bombing of Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket
rocketed more than 1.5 percent higher Thursday after United
States-led bombing raids on Iraq ignited interest in oil, gold and
"defensive" stocks.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index finished 42.7 points up at
2,740.0, slightly off its intra-day peak of 2,741.0.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index surged 25.4 points or 2.71 percent to
961.8, while the all industrials index shot up 66.5 points to
4,915.9.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the market opened higher on the air strikes news,
with gains in the price of gold and oil overnight spurred on those
sectors.
</P>
<P>
"(The market) is very firm on the back of the Iraq situation,"
said Macquarie Nevitts client adviser Steve Mayne.
</P>
<P>
He said firmer commodities prices overnight fuelled gains among
resource stocks.
</P>
<P>
"The oil stocks were up because of a fear of an oil shortage
because of the attacks," Mayne said.
</P>
<P>
Gold stocks were buoyed because the precious metal was often
regarded as a safe haven investment during times of international
crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Among oil and gas stocks, Woodside Petroleum gained 15.8 cents,
Santos surged 18 and Novus Petroleum climbed nine.
</P>
<P>
The gold index rose 33.6 points to 1,134.7, with Lihir climbing
eight, Normandy adding three and Newcrest steady at 2.30
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The spot price of gold bullion in Sydney closed at 294.80 U.S.
dollars an ounce, up from Wednesday's close of 293.00.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the resources sector, diversified miners bounced
back after recent sell-downs, with Rio Tinto rising 38.3 cents,
WMC climbing 20.22 and MIM easing one cent.
</P>
<P>
BHP added 37 cents ahead of its half year profit results out
Friday.
</P>
<P>
It was a mixed day for banking stocks, with the industry
sub-index gaining 53.7 points to 6,271.0.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank was the only "Big Four" player to
lose ground, shedding one cent, despite chairman Mark Rayner
forecasting further growth in business and profitability over the
current year.
</P>
<P>
ANZ made the most ground, picking up 28 cents or 2.66 percent,
while Commonwealth added 24 and Westpac rose 15.
</P>
<P>
In the telecommunications sector, Telstra charged 22.9 cents
higher, AAPT jumped 16 cents on turnover of 1.4 million shares and
Cable &AMP; Wireless Optus firmed two cents.
</P>
<P>
Among other industrials, Lend Lease soared 67 cents, Coca-Cola
Amatil stacked on 32.1, Coles Myer firmed 18 and Amcor surged 30.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 332.80 million shares traded for 956.85
million Australian dollars (598.03 million U.S. dollars), with
rising stocks outnumbering falling stocks by 727 to 531 with 422
stocks remaining steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
