<HEADLINE> UK to Be Heavily Involved in Air Strikes: Cook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said on Thursday that Britain will be "heavily involved in
the next wave of air strikes against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, we'll be contributing about a fifth of the manned
aircraft raids," he said in an interview with BBC radio.
</P>
<P>
He said he had no reason to believe that the raids, which began
late Wednesday evening, were not successful.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary also confirmed that Wednesday night's
raids had been carries out with United States cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
Further strikes would go ahead with the aim of degrading Iraq's
chemical and biological weapons program and diminishing its war
machine, he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is not the end today," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
There are 12 British Air Force Tornado attack aircraft based in
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
"We have exhausted all other avenues," British Prime Minister
Tony Blair said in a statement delivered on Wednesday night less
than half an hour after the start of Operation Desert Fox around
2200 GMT.
</P>
<P>
Blair's announcement came about 35 minutes earlier than United
States President Bill Clinton's address.
</P>
<P>
"Our quarrel is with him (Saddam) alone," Blair said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
