<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Suggests Phased Solution to Congo (K) Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) Salim Ahmed Salim has
suggested a two-phase solution to the crisis in the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The suggestion is contained in a report Salim is expected to
deliver to the fourth ordinary session of the Central Organ of
the OAU Mechanism for Conflict Prevention, Management and
Resolution at summit level, scheduled to open Thursday in
Ouagadougou, capital of Burkina Faso.
</P>
<P>
The first phase should aim at the attainment of a cessation of
hostilities, the signing and actualization of a cease-fire, and
the deployment of an international peace-keeping force under the
auspices of the United Nations, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The second phase should see the initiation of broader
political dialog involving groups other than the armed rebellion
to negotiate and forge a political dispensation that will meet
the aspirations of all Congolese, it said.
</P>
<P>
The report regretted that though great efforts have been done
by individual African leaders, the OAU and the U.N. to solve the
DRC crisis, the result has been very frustrating, with the lack
of any significant breakthrough so far.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general warned that if the crisis in DRC is
allowed to continue and escalate, it will have catastrophic
consequences not just for the Great Lakes region, but the whole
African continent.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the report also noted that there is now a
consensus on basic principles to be observed, including the need
for an immediate cease-fire, respect for the sovereignty of the
DRC, the withdrawal of foreign troops and political dialog within
DRC.
</P>
<P>
Salim noted that a foundation for a peaceful solution has
already been laid by previous efforts, and what is left to be
done is for the OAU Central Organ to help the conflicting parties
to narrow their differences for the attainment of peace.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to OAU sources, both Congolese President
Laurent Kabila and the rebel representatives are now in
Ouagadougou, but by Wednesday night, it was still not clear if
the rebels would be invited to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Sources said Kabila has not changed his position and refuses
direct dialog with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
About 24 African leaders and 30 delegations are expected to
attend the two-day meeting, which is scheduled to discuss
conflicts in Angola, Burundi, Guinea Bissau, the Comoros as well
as the dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
