<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Condemns U.S. Air Strikes on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon Thursday strongly
condemned the air raids launched by the U.S. and Britain on Iraq,
demanding the two countries immediately stop the aggression.
</P>
<P>
"We condemned this assault and asked why only Israel in the
Middle East can be free of any punishment or pressure for its
occupation of Syrian, Lebanese and Palestinian lands and its
neglect of international laws," Prime Minister-Designate Salim
Hoss told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
After months of disputes over weapons inspections, U.S. and
British forces early Thursday launched the biggest air strikes
against Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War triggered by Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The attack came hours after a report by the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) chief Richard Butler, who accused Baghdad of
failing to fully cooperate with UNSCOM on disarming Iraq as
required in U.N. resolutions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Hoss said it seems that Iraqi people, especially children,
elderly and women, will suffer more than what the eight-year-old
U.N economic sanction has caused.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were imposed on Iraq following its invasion of
Kuwait and the Security Council maintains that the sanctions will
not be lifted until UNSCOM certifies that Iraq has eliminated all
its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Hoss also called on U.S. to stop the assault on Iraq and lift
the sanctions on it to respect Iraqi people's human rights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
