<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Computerize Primary Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government will
begin from the 1999 fiscal year the computerization of primary
schools in the country, Education Minister Sam Olaiya has said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking Wednesday at the opening ceremony of a two-day
workshop organized by the National Primary Education Commission
in capital Abuja, the minister said arrangements had been made
for the provision of computers for an effective information
management system.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the computerization of primary schools in the
most populous African country was part of the government's
Primary Education Project (PEP), according to a Vanguard report
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, the minister said, text and exercise books,
furniture, motorcycles, motorboats and other infrastructure had
been procured for primary schools.
</P>
<P>
The PEP is being financed by a World Bank facility.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, World Bank resident representative in
Nigeria Trevor Byre commended the Nigerian government for
strengthening primary education program in the country.
</P>
<P>
"It is really a pleasure for me today (Wednesday) to see the
result of not just the building of schools, rehabilitation of
schools but above all the provision of important softwares of
books for pupils and teachers," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
