<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani Senate Condemns U.S. Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Senate Thursday
unanimously passed a resolution condemning the U.S. air attack
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The resolution adopted by the Senate after a debate on the
issue termed the attack as one against the whole Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
It urged the international community and the U.N. Security
Council to take immediate measures to stop the attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Winding up the debate in the Senate, Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz called upon all parties concerned to resort to
dialogue as a mean to resolve the conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said progress towards this end can only be achieved by
adhering to the U.N. resolutions and respect for Iraq's
sovereignty and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
Aziz regretted that the use of force against Iraq comes at a
time when billions of Muslims are preparing for the holy month of
Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack had added to the miseries of the Iraqi
civilian population and imposed a threat to regional peace and
security.
</P>
<P>
The attack has sent a wave of concern and anguish throughout
the world particularly the Muslim world, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said Pakistan has consistently supported implementation
of all U.N. resolutions without selective application in true
letter and spirit.
</P>
<P>
While supporting the U.N. resolutions, Pakistan has
consistently opposed the use of force and wants peaceful
resolution of the conflict through diplomatic efforts, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan supports the statement made by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan Thursday morning expressing sadness
at the failure of the U.N. to prevent the attack.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has called for continuing cooperation between Iraq and
the U.N. weapons inspectors and a comprehensive review of Iraq's
compliance with the Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan feels that Iraq has complied substantially
with the resolutions and there was no immediate danger of any
non-compliance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
