<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Denounces U.S. Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) Thursday
denounced the overnight air strikes by the United States and
Britain on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The strike will "not help settle pending issues" between Iraq
and the U.N., AL chief Esmat Abdel-Meguid, who is on a visit to
Italy, said in a telephone interview with Egypt's Voice of Arab
radio Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British decision to strike Iraq was "a unilateral
one which did not garner the U.N. Security Council approval,"
Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of missiles rained down on Iraq at around midnight
local time (2200 GMT) Wednesday, killing two people and wounding
30 others.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said the raid was a retaliation for
Iraq's defiance of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM), which
oversees Iraq's disarming of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The airstrike came only hours after UNSCOM chief Richard Butler
reported to the U.N. that Iraq failed to fully cooperate with
UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
He accused Baghdad of refusing to hand over weapons-related
documents demanded by UNSCOM and obstruct the work of weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid said the attack was launched against an Arab state
which has been implementing and abiding by U.N. Security Council
resolutions, expressing concern that it "will only complicate
things."
</P>
<P>
The chief of the 22-nation pan-Arab organization also lashed
out at Butler, saying he was "not objective" in dealing with the
U.N. arms inspections in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
