<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Says Peso Unlikely to Appreciate Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso is unlikely
to appreciate further as "an excessively strong peso is just as
unsustainable and destabilizing as an excessively weak peso,"
Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of local exporters, Singson said that the
central bank would continue to allow the market to determine the
exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The market-determined exchange rate would be "supportive of our
external competitiveness," he said.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that the central bank always believes in achieving
an overall balance in market conditions.
</P>
<P>
However, the market sentiment Thursday drove again back the
peso to a closing rate of 39.45 to the U.S. dollar although it
reached an intra-day high of 39.44 to the dollar and intra-day low
of 39.59.
</P>
<P>
Bank treasurers initially expected the peso to appreciate in
the last remaining days of the month following dollar inflows from
some investors, loan proceeds and returning overseas contract
workers.
</P>
<P>
While there was initial optimism that the peso could strengthen
to 37 to the dollar, market sentiment has kept the currency at 39
pesos against the greenback.  
</P>
</TEXT>
