<HEADLINE> Iraq Crisis Adds Spark to Australian Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.-led air strikes on
Iraq attracted offshore buyers to the "safe-haven" Australian
markets Thursday, boosting the Australian dollar and bond prices.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar found support from overseas buyers early,
reaching a high of 62.60 U.S. cents at midday.
</P>
<P>
However, local interests met the rally with afternoon selling,
pushing it back to finish flat and close to its lows for the day.
</P>
<P>
The local currency ended at 62.37 U.S. cents, steady with
Wednesday's close. It traded within a range of 62.20 and 62.60
during the day.
</P>
<P>
Steve Nitis, senior manager corporate foreign exchange at
Commonwealth Bank, said the drama in Iraq had led to the
Australian dollar being quite well bid by "quality names" from
offshore.
</P>
<P>
He said the offshore support had been predicated on an
improvement in fundamentals such as a firmer gold price and a
turn-up in the Commodities Research Bureau Index.
</P>
<P>
Nitis said the outlook remained bullish for the currency over
the next month and the next move would more likely be to 63 to 64
U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
The federal government's mid-year economic outlook, reported by
Treasurer Peter Costello, was overshadowed by events in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The government revised its forecasts for economic growth up to
3.25 percent, from the election-time estimate of 2.75 percent, for
1998/99.
</P>
<P>
Economists, reflecting on the upgrade, said it remained a
conservative estimate and growth could still rise further on the
upside.
</P>
<P>
Costello declared that the Australian economy was a solid rock
that was outperforming the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
At the close here Thursday the Australian dollar was buying
72.38 Japanese yen from 72.46 and 1.0398 German marks from 1.0339.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
