<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leaders Leave for Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A 35-member delegation led
by Ali Mahdi Mohamed left Somalia Thursday for Tripoli, Libya.
</P>
<P>
The delegation included senior officers from the recently
announced administration of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to Ali Mahdi Mohamed who briefed the journalists
before his departure, their unexpected journey to Libya is at the
official invitation of Colonel Muammar Gaddafi of Libya.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said he will meet Hussein Mohamed Aidid who is
currently in Cairo and will join the delegation to Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said the 3-5 days visit to Libya may pave the way
for a national reconciliation conference for all the Somalis and
called on the Somali politicians to get ready for helping the
establishment of a government of national unity in the near
future in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Such conference which was scheduled to be held in the town of
Baidoa was postponed for several times, and the last time was set
to meet on January 15 following a four-month delay announced by
the so-called national coordination committee co-chaired by Ali
Mahdi and Hussein Aidid.
</P>
<P>
The Libya visit by the top political leaders of Mogadishu is
also taking place at a time when Colonel Abdullahi Yussuf Ahmed,
the president of the recently established regional administration
of Northeastern Somalia known as Puntland, is also visiting
Libya.
</P>
<P>
Abdullahi Yussuf had been one of the two Darod clan leaders
who boycotted the Cairo peace deal late last year after accusing
Egypt of not being neutral in the political affairs of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The politicians now believe that Gaddafi is trying to mend the
disruption over all reconciliation process of the country, a very
difficult goal to be achieved since the Somali politicians never
or very rarely change or renounce their political views
concerning the power sharing of the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Mogadishu leaders are having their own
problems here back home where several leaders are firmly opposing
to their administration.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi said they are meeting Abdullahi Yussuf in Libya.
</P>
<P>
"Let's hope something positive will come out of that," he said
with some considerable doubt.
</P>
<P>
"Libya is one of those Arab countries given the mandate to
help sort out the problems of Somalia and restore the nation back
on its feet," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Since Mogadishu's administration was announced, Libya has been
helping Ali Mahdi and Hussein Aidid with all it can including
cash money for the payment of the encamped 3,000 police force of
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said Mohamed Hajji Ibrahim Egal, the president
of the break-away republic of Somaliland, was also invited to
visit Libya to attend the meeting by the Somali politicians.
</P>
<P>
However, sources close to Egal's office said he had declined
to accept the offer at this particular time. The sources said
Egal would only accept such a meeting when a unique
administration is founded for southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, faction leader Osman Ali Atto reportedly will not
attending the Libya meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
