<HEADLINE> Italy Hopes for Quick End to Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government hopes the
U.S.-led attacks on Iraq will end quickly and that events will go
in the direction of a political solution to the crisis within the
framework of the United Nations, Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Italian Senate, Dini said the Italian
government hopes that the military action launched late Wednesday
"will end as soon as possible and that initiatives necessary for a
political solution within the framework of the United Nations can
be started up."
</P>
<P>
He said he was following the developments in close contact with
Premier Massimo D'Alema and that he had conferred over the
telephone during the night with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
"The Italian government is following events unfolding in Iraq
and the American initiative to strike military objectives in Iraqi
territory with great concern," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
According to the Italian government, the crisis is caused by
Iraq's failure to comply with U.N. resolutions and repeated
failure to cooperate with weapons inspectors. This failure to
cooperate, said Dini, has "stopped the commission from carrying
out its duties of searching for and eliminating weapons of mass
destruction."
</P>
<P>
At this point, he said the government hopes the strikes will
end quickly to give way to a settlement within the
U.N. framework. 
</P>
