<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Throws Hundreds of Tomahawks on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The first waves of the
U.S. airstrikes against Iraq Wednesday will have sent 200-300
Tomahawk cruise missiles on Iraqi targets, senior U.S. defense
officials said.
</P>
<P>
As dawn broke over Iraq, U.S. spy satellites and U-2 spy planes
carried out overflight missions to assess the destruction wrought
by the first wave of strikes, the Associated Press said.
</P>
<P>
The attack started Wednesday at 5 p.m. EST -- midnight Iraqi
time -- with sea-launched cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
Primary targets for the Tomahawks were Iraqi military
communications nodes and facilities within several of Iraq's
sprawling presidential palaces, a senior defense official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
U.S. defense officials said that top-priority targets include
suspected biological and chemical weapon manufacturing and storage
sites, weapons delivery assets such as missile factories, and
facilities to manufacture and store mobile missile launchers.
</P>
<P>
The officials also said that with the arrival of the USS Carl
Vinson carrier battle group Friday, the U.S. Navy will be able to
launch upwards of 500 more cruise missiles at Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon used cruise missiles and radar-evading aircraft in
the first wave of strikes to avoid casualties. But following
phases of the airstrikes will involve conventional U.S. warplanes.
</P>
<P>
The United States is sending 1,500 Army troops to join 3,000
already in Kuwait. In addition, hundreds more will deploy with
Patriot missile defense batteries along with a special nuclear,
chemical and biological defense unit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Wednesday that the
"serious and sustained" strikes were not expected to eliminate
Iraq's arsenal or end the need for a massive U.S. military
presence in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to degrade (Saddam's) capacity to threaten his
neighbors with chemical, biological or nuclear weapons and the
means to deliver them," Cohen said at a Pentagon news conference.
"We're not seeking to eliminate it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
