<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Air Traffic Increase in U.K. Air Base in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- There is no increase in air
traffic in the British military air base of RAF Akrotiri in Cyprus
following the combined U.S.-U.K. air strikes on Iraq, the base's
spokesman Jon Brown said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Brown said, however, the base is ready to help out, if
and when necessary.
</P>
<P>
Normal air traffic at the British military air base RAF
Akrotiri, west of Cyprus' southern coastal town of Limassol,
consists of weekly flights to and from U.K. carrying personnel
and other flights as required.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the U.S. has not so far requested Britain's
permission to use the base.
</P>
<P>
He did acknowledge that when the equipment originally went
out to the Gulf, "some of it came via Akrotiri, some time
ago".
</P>
<P>
Asked if there are any contingency plans because of the current
situation in the Gulf, Brown said the bases as a military force
"always have contingency plans for all sorts of scenarios".
</P>
<P>
Brown said the U.S. has a detachment in Akrotiri, which
is the support flight for their Beirut embassy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
