<HEADLINE> Shanghai Unveils Record Breaking Buick Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The first Buick-New Century
car produced by Shanghai General Motors came off the assembly line
today and the company was immediately hailed for breaking new
records in auto production.
</P>
<P>
The factory was only set up 18 months ago and the chairman and
CEO of the General Motors in the U.S., who drove the white car
into the history books, praised the management and workforce for
their efforts.
</P>
<P>
Mr Smith's co-driver was Shanghai GM president Chen Xianglin
while Shanghai Communist Party chief Huang Ju was given the honor
of pressing the production line's start button.
</P>
<P>
Located in the Pudong New Area, Shanghai GM is the largest
motor vehicle joint venture in China. It was set up in June, 1997
by Shanghai Motor Vehicle Group and GM in the United States at a
cost of 1.52 billion U.S. dollars, invested in a 50:50 ratio.
</P>
<P>
It boasts the most advanced assembly line technologies in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The new model can use both leaded and lead-free petrol, which
is in line with China's efforts to protect the environment by
encouraging the use of lead-free fuel.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai GM plans to put two versions of the car - the New
Century and the Dynasty - into mass production in April, 1999,
with annual output targeted at 100,000.
</P>
<P>
This will increase the annual motor vehicle production
capacity of Shanghai, the country's largest auto manufacturing
center, to 400,000 and the joint venture plans to develop other
models from 2003.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has now designated the motor vehicle
industry as a pillar industry of its Ninth Five-Year-Plan
(1996-2000).  
</P>
</TEXT>
