<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Raises Forecast for Growth in 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
Thursday boosted its forecast for gross domestic product (GDP)
growth in 1998/99 to 3.25 percent despite the Asian economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
And it said the budget surplus in the current financial year
was estimated to be 3.3 billion Australian dollars (2.06 billion
U.S. dollars), 580 million Australian dollars (362.5 million U.S.
dollars) higher than previously estimated and more than double the
previous fiscal year's surplus.
</P>
<P>
"What the picture today shows is in the face of the Asian
financial fury with some parts of Asia contracting by as much as
10 percent, the Australian economy has been a solid rock, a strong
rock, outperforming the world," Treasurer Peter Costello told
reporters while releasing the government's mid-year outlook.
</P>
<P>
The Mid-Year Economic and Fiscal Outlook for 1998/99 boosted
growth for 1998/99 to 3.25 compared with 2.75 percent forecast in
the government's pre-election outlook.
</P>
<P>
However, GDP growth was seen slowing in 1999/2000 to 2.75
percent, in year average terms.
</P>
<P>
The document also boosted expected employment growth for
1998/99 to 2 percent, from 1.75 percent previously forecast, but
falling back to 1.25 percent in 1999/2000.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate was seen at a year average of 8 percent
this fiscal year - unchanged from earlier forecasts due to an
expected slowing in domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
Inflation was seen lower than previously expected, with the
consumer price index (CPI) expected to rise by 2 percent in
1998/99 compared with 2.5 percent in earlier forecasts.
</P>
<P>
In 1999/2000, inflation is expected to rise slightly to 2.5
percent but Costello pointed out that it would remain within the
monetary policy target band of 2-3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The mid-year review saw the Australian budget staying in
surplus into the outyears, although there was some impact from the
introduction of the federal government's tax package.
</P>
<P>
The mid-year review said the current account deficit was set to
widen to 32 billion Australian dollars (20 billion U.S. dollars)
in 1998/99, or 5.5 percent of GDP, reflecting the weaker
international environment.
</P>
<P>
Costello said the government remains committed to maintaining
its strong fiscal position, "and will be taking a highly
disciplined approach during the coming budget processes."
</P>
<P>
The current fiscal outlook is consistent with the maintenance
of surpluses while economic growth remains sound, and the
objective of halving Commonwealth General net debt remains on
track, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
