<HEADLINE> Former Vice-President Joins Nigeria's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's former Vice-President
Alex Ekwueme has formally declared his ambition to seek
nomination as flag-bearer of the People's Democratic Party (PDP)
in the February 27 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The former vice-president made the announcement Wednesday in
Kaduna, northern Nigeria, during a public lecture organized by
the Ahmed Bello University, the New Nigerian reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that he wanted to be president because he has a vision
of a great Nigeria where probity, accountability, integrity and
transparency are enthroned.
</P>
<P>
He has a vision of a Nigeria where free and compulsory
education is the norm, where agriculture is supported and food is
in abundance, where utilities work and industries are in
production, and where the health of the citizens is given its
priority, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ekwueme promised to work assiduously to restore the country as
a showcase for social justice, peace and prosperity, a country
expected to assume its formal role as the authentic leader of the
growing Africa Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
He restated his suggestion that the country should have three
vice-presidents in the next civilian government, saying that the
arrangement will instill a sense of belonging in governance among
the constituent units of the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Ekwueme, an Ibo from the eastern part of the country, was the
vice-president in the second republic of the Federal Government
headed by former President Shehu Shargari.
</P>
<P>
He maintained a low profile politically until a few months to
the end of General Sani Abacha's life in June when he emerged as
leader of the G-34 coalition of politicians to oppose Abacha's
plan to transform himself into a civilian president.
</P>
<P>
Ekwueme, an educated architect and businessman, has nurtured
the G-34 into a political party, the People's Democratic Party
which analysts have described as the most national of all the
political parties in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
During the December 5 local government elections, the PDP
scored five percent votes and above in all the 36 states and the
Federal Capital Territory in the country with 459 out of 774
chairmanship positions of the local governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
