<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Asset Sale in Thailand Fails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The largest asset sale of 56
closed financial firms in Thailand has proved to be a failure,
sources at the Financial Restructuring Authority (FRA) said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The FRA, set up to manage liquidation of the 56 financial
companies which closed last year, launched the auction on
Wednesday as the largest one-day sale in history.
</P>
<P>
Assets worth 371 billion baht (10.3 billion U.S. dollars) were
offered for sale. But bids for only nine of the 45 lots up for
sale were accepted by the FRA board. Six of the lots attracted no
bids, while the remaining 30 lots had bids under benchmark prices
set by the FRA.
</P>
<P>
Bids on the nine lots sold totaled 37 percent of the 371
billion baht in assets involved, fairly high considering that up
to 90 percent of the total loan portfolio offered by the FRA in
the auction is non-performing.
</P>
<P>
Proceeds from the auction will be split by creditors of the 56
companies next year, with the central bank, the largest creditor,
having a 90-percent share.
</P>
<P>
The FRA will negotiate with participating investors next week
on whether they would increase their bids or accept the
profit-sharing arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Under the profit-sharing, the FRA would allow investors to buy
assets below the benchmark prices. But future capital gains on the
assets would be shared with the government.
</P>
<P>
FRA chairman Amaret Sila-on said he was disappointed with the
auction results and deemed the auction "a failure."
</P>
<P>
He said failure to pass crucial legal reforms, particularly new
foreclosure and bankruptcy procedures, was a major factor for the
poor auction results, Amaret said.
</P>
<P>
Delays by parliament in implementing legal reforms had
increased risks for investors, he said, adding that Political
friction about the asset sale process, as well as social dissent,
had also discouraged some investors from participation.
</P>
<P>
Several opposition politicians, academics and businessmen have
attacked the auctions on nationalistic grounds, charging the
process would result in local assets being sold cheaply to
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Others have voiced concerns that investors were colluding with
borrowers of the 56 companies to buy back loans cheaply at the
expense of public taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
The FRA has said it will prosecute any investors found to have
colluded with borrowers, and maintains that the auction process
has been in line with the best international practices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
