<HEADLINE> French Military Chief Opposes Missile System in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The setup of a deterrent
missile system in the Gulf can only raise instability in the
region, said J.P.Kelche, visiting Chief of Staff of the French
Joint Forces on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with his counterpart Sheikh Mohammed Bin Zayed
Al-Nahyan of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Kelche said
U.S. recommendation to establish the defensive missile system in
the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) member countries to counter
nuclear proliferation in the region will further threaten regional
stability and security.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Oman, UAE, Kuwait, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Such an anti-ballistic missile system will not be "100 percent
proof," but encourage adversaries to build up their military
capabilities instead, said Kelche, who arrived here last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It can be interpreted by neighbors as a sign of mistrust and
fuel the arms race," he added.
</P>
<P>
Kelche said France considers that security can be achieved in
the region through peaceful solutions to state-to-state
disagreements, which means "the sincere pursuit of the peace
process between Israel and the Palestinians and the compliance by
all, including Iraq, with Security Council resolutions." 
</P>
</TEXT>
