<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Say Microelements Help Increase Rice Yields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese specialists have
found that most plants need microelements in addition to manure
and that a balanced supply of microelements may help increase
yields of the plant and improve the quality of the products.
</P>
<P>
Seven microelements, especially boron, molybdenum and zinc,
can effectively increase the yields of rice, according to
experiments made by local specialists.
</P>
<P>
The experiments show that the output of low-yielding rice
paddy applied with manure which contains boron, molybdenum and
zinc is up 21 percent compared with conventional fields.
</P>
<P>
Experts also said that different regions have different
specialities because of the variant structure of microelements in
the field. The famous Longjing green tea is produced only in the
areas around Hangzhou, capital of Zhejiang Province, because the
fields in the region have higher contents of silicon, potassium
and phosphorus and low contents of calcium, magnesium and
manganese.
</P>
<P>
The quality grapefruit produced in southern Zhejiang province
and the walnut in western Zhejiang are also attributed by experts
to the content of certain microelements in the field.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
