<HEADLINE> NATO Holds Saddam Responsible for Air Strikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- NATO Secretary General Javier
Solana on Thursday held Iraqi President Saddam Hussein responsible
for the U.S.-British air strikes.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement issued prior to the NATO defense ministers
council meeting, the NATO chief said that the Iraqi president
"alone is responsible for the grave situation and for the
consequences that his defiance of the will of the international
community has entailed."
</P>
<P>
Solana said that Iraq "must cooperate with the United Nations
and take immediate and concrete steps to comply fully with all its
resolutions."
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain, despite clear-cut opposition
from three of the five permanent members of the United Nations
Security Council, launched an air strike against Iraq with cruise
missiles in the early hours Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China and Russia strongly opposed the use of force while France
deplored the attack as an action without the mandate of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said that five Iraqi people were killed
and more than 30 injured in the initial attack against the Iraq
capital of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The United States is now reportedly reinforcing its military
buildup in the Gulf region, where it already has eight warships
that can launch Tomhawk cruise missiles. 
</P>
