<HEADLINE> Albright Defends U.S.-British Airstrikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright Wednesday night defended U.S.-British
airstrikes against Iraq despite strong opposition by other United
Nations Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
"We have decided to use force because other means simply have
not worked," Albright told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
"Showdowns last fall, last winter, last month were all
concluded without air strikes after Iraq promised to cooperate
fully with U.N. weapons inspectors. Throughout, we worked hard to
maintain Security Council unity by allowing time and then more
time for Iraq to live up to those promises," she said.
</P>
<P>
"As the United States' chief diplomat, I can tell you that we
exhausted every diplomatic approach and every possibility," she
said, adding that "Saddam Hussein blew it."
</P>
<P>
But the United States and Britain were alone when they began
the raids on Iraq at 21:49 GMT Wednesday and their military
action against Iraq aroused strong opposition from other United
Nations Security Council members.
</P>
<P>
Russia and China condemned the military action and said that
the airstrikes violated the U.N. Charter. The two countries
demanded immediate halt to the military attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
France, which fought alongside the United States and Britain in
the 1991 Gulf War, disassociated itself from the military action
and said it could have grave consequences on the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"The truth is they have no answers as to how to make (Iraq)
comply" with U.N. Security Council disarmament demands, Albright
said in dismissing the opposition.
</P>
<P>
"And the bottom line is that it would be very nice if those who
do not support our approach had an approach that worked," she said.
</P>
<P>
However, Albright said that she was satisfied with the support
from other countries for the U.S. approach and that the Pentagon
had the military cooperation it needed in the region to carry out
its mission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
