<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Oppose U.S. Air Strikes on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Senior Palestinian officials
said Thursday that they do not support the U.S. air strikes
against Iraq, stressing that dispute can be resolved only by
peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
"We don't condone the use of force by the United States. We
believe solutions should come from peaceful means," Saeb Erekat,
senior Palestinian negotiator with Israel, said in a televised
speech Thursday. "This is a sad day for us," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tibi, adviser to Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Chairman Yasser Arafat, said the U.S. military action will not
solve problems but only increase sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"We, as the Palestinians, feel solidarity with the Iraqi
people," he said.
</P>
<P>
The surprise missile attack on Baghdad launched by U.S. and
Britain came at around midnight Thursday only hours after
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) chief Richard Butler submitted a
report over the weapons inspections in Iraq to the U.N. Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
Butler accused Iraq of having failed to live up to its promise
to provide full cooperation to UNSCOM, which oversees Iraq's
disarming of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian reactions were less strong compared with those
in the 1991 Gulf War, sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in
1990, when the Palestine Liberation Organization expressed its
support for Iraqi President Saddam Hussein and staged large-scale
demonstrations against the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The PNA has kept a low-profile in the recent confrontations
between the U.S. and Iraq, refraining from condemning Washington,
the major mediator in its peace-making with Israel.
</P>
<P>
But hundreds of Palestinian youths in a refuge camp in the
Palestinian-ruled Bethlehem demonstrated Thursday morning to
protest against the U.S. strike. They burnt U.S. and Israeli
flags.
</P>
<P>
In another West Bank city of Ramallah, Palestinians marched on
the streets Thursday to show their solidarity with the Iraqi
people, Jerusalem Media and Communications Center, a Palestinian
news service, reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
