<HEADLINE> East Asians Continue to Dominate Asiad Track Events </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- After Beijing and Hiroshima,
East Asian teams continued to dominate the Asian Games track
cycling events, taking five out of seven golds at stake at the Hua
Mark Velodrome.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan, which wom the remaining two golds, is the only
central Asian country which could challenge powerhouses like
Japan, South Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
Men's sprint is still Japan's domain, with Keirin racers
Yoichiro Kamiyama and Nariaki Mabuchi completing a one-two finish.
</P>
<P>
But the victories have historical significance as Kamiyama is the
the first professional cyclist grabbing an Asian Games gold.
</P>
<P>
However, Japan lost to the men's 1-km time trial title to South
Korean Ji Sung-Hwan.
</P>
<P>
South Korea became the winner again in the team pursuit event,
beating old rival Kazakhstan in the final to repeat its victory in
Hiroshima four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the central Asian state is still unbeatable in the
longer individual distance races, as Vadim Kravchenko kept his
4-km pursuit title.
</P>
<P>
In the heatly contested 40-km points race, Kazakhstan's Sergey
Lavrenenko excelled.
</P>
<P>
China proved its strength in women's events by claiming all the
golds and silvers.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qingzhi retained her 3-km individual pursuit title won in
last Asiad competition and Wang Yan battled against a fatal
disease to triumph in the sprint.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei emerged as the possible title contender in the next
Games as they won three bronzes here.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the team, who came empty-handed from Hiroshima,
attributed the progress to shifting focus from long distance events to
shorter ones. 
</P>
