<HEADLINE> Compaq to Cut PC Prices by 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Compaq Computer Corp., the
world's largest maker of personal computers, said Wednesday it
will cut prices up to 7 percent on a new line of computers.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the company said the price cuts on its
Prosignia desktop personal computer line aim at a preemptive
strike against competing products from rival Dell Computer Corp.,
the world's leading direct computer systems company.
</P>
<P>
The price of mid-range Compaq Prosignia 330 with an Intel
Pentium II 350 megahertz processor and a moderate amount of
computer memory, was reduced 7 percent to 1,629 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company cuts the price of its top-of-the-line Prosignia
330, with a speedy 450 megahertz Pentium II chip and crammed with
computer memory, to 1,999 dollars, or by 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The price of low-end Compaq Prosignia 310, which is equipped
with an Intel Celeron 300a computer chip and a minimal amount of
computer memory, was cut to 1,249 U.S. dollars, or 2 percent off
its previous price of 1,279 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The prices of the three categories include a 17-inch computer
monitor, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
