<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Takes Measures to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has taken a series of
measures to develop its tourism industry and has made encouraging
progresses in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian country has seen an upward trend in foreign
tourist arrivals and foreign exchange earnings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, tourist arrivals in the country were 140,112. The
figure rose to 156,231 in 1995, 165,887 in 1996, and 186,000 in
1997, an increase of 11.5 percent, 6.18 percent, and 12 percent
respectively, according to the Bangladesh Parjatan Corporation
(BPC), the national tourism organization.
</P>
<P>
Foreign exchange earnings, which were only 759.4 million taka
(15.7 million U.S. dollars) in 1994, increased to 955.2 million
taka (19.7 million dollars) in 1995 and 1.175 billion taka (24.2
million dollars) in 1996, a growth rate of 26 percent and 22
percent respectively. Earnings in 1997 recorded a remarkable
53-percent increase to 1.8 billion taka (37.1 million dollars)
from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry has been blessed by the country's rich
natural and tourism resources, such as its beaches, hills,
forests, wildlife, tribe villages, archaeological and historical
sites and cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
The government has been giving high priority and importance to
the tourism sector in efforts to develop the national economy and
promote the country's image abroad, especially in
tourist-generating countries like the United States, Japan and
those in Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
To formulate a united policy for rapid development of the
tourism sector, the government has formed the National Tourism
Council with Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina as its head. Meanwhile,
tourism has been declared as an industry with policy incentives
for investment in the sector.
</P>
<P>
The government encourages foreign investment in the sector
either through joint ventures or on a 100-percent foreign
ownership basis.
</P>
<P>
The government has also announced a number of incentives for
both local and foreign investors who are interested in this field,
including tax exemption on royalties, foreign loan interests and
capital gains from transfer of shares, avoidance of double
taxation on foreign investors on the basis of bilateral
agreements, and exemption of income tax on salaries for up to
three years for foreign technicians.
</P>
<P>
Under the national policy of development and promotion of
tourism, the BPC has established various tourism facilities in the
country, including hotels, motels, youth hostels, restaurants,
picnic spots, and land and water transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
Duty-free shops and recreational facilities have also been
built up in tourism-potential areas of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Human resources development in the field of tourism is also
getting due attention. The National Hotel and Tourism Training
Institute supported by the United Nations Development Program
(UNDP) and the International Labor Organization (ILO) has been
expanding training facilities and trained about 16,000 people in
hotel and tourism.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the World Tourism Organization has prepared a
tourism master plan for Bangladesh with financial assistance from
the UNDP.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is now implementing the recommendations of the
master plan in phases within the framework of the country's
national five-year plan (1997-2002). A five-year plan for the
development of tourism has also been formulated and received an
allocation of 3 billion taka (61.9 million dollars) for the public
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
