<HEADLINE> Angola Calls for Repulsing UNITA Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Angola's Defense Ministry
Thursday called on all armed forces to fight courageously and
repulse the attacks by the National Union for Total Independence
of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
"Armed UNITA forces led by Jonas Savimbi have once again
plunged the country into the abyss of war. Their intention is to
overthrow the existing democratic system and to realize their
dream of seizing state power by armed force," said a statement of
the ministry issued on the eve of the Army Day which falls on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Large scale clashes between the Angolan government army and
UNITA forces broke out since mid-November. The UNITA which
should have been demilitarized under the U.N. inspection turned
out allegedly with dozens of tanks and long-range cannons and
downed several government fighter planes with ground-to-air
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the government army has suffered
great setbacks while the UNITA occupied the most parts of Huambo
and Bie provinces and besieged their capitals.
</P>
<P>
A great number of refugees are currently fleeing from the
fighting zones whereas international humanitarian organizations
and government officials are also withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
Taking this into account, the Angolan government denounced
UNITA for cheating the United Nations and international
community. One the other hand, it accused the U.N. observer
mission of incompetence and negligence and asked the U.N. to
withdraw its peace-keepers from this southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Issa Diallo, the U.N. special envoy to Angola, said here
Wednesday that despite the current emergency situation in the
country, he still believed there would be a "positive ending" to
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
