<HEADLINE> India Strongly Deplores Air Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- India Thursday strongly
deplored the air strike on Iraq by the United States and Britain
and called for an immediate halt to the military action.
</P>
<P>
"It is particularly regrettable that this unilateral step has
been taken at the very time when the U.N. Security Council is in
session to discuss the development there," Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee told parliament in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This attack raises serious questions regarding the functioning
of the collective and consultative procedures of the U.N. Security
Council. It also undermines the ability of the council to verify
Iraq's compliance with the relevant Council resolutions," Vajpayee
said.
</P>
<P>
It has been India's view that the use of force in this
situation would be counter-productive, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-British air attack on Iraq was strongly condemned
Thursday in both houses of parliament here with members charging
U.S. President Bill Clinton with trying to divert international
attention from his possible impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The leader of the opposition in the Lower House, Sharad Pawar,
said the manner in which the U.S. carried out the attack on Iraq
needs to be strongly condemned. The opposition leader in the Upper
House of Parliament, Manmohan Singh, said the unilateral action of
the U.S. was uncalled for. 
</P>
