<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, December 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The U.S. and British missiles pounded the Iraqi
capital of Baghdad early on Thursday, killing at least two people
and injuring more than 30 others so far.
</P>
<P>
The first blast were heard at 00:49 a.m. local time (2149 GMT
Wednesday) and were followed by a series of explosions. Washington
and London immediately announced that the air strikes, code-named
Operation Desert Fox, had begun.
</P>
<P>
The air raids sirens sounded briefly over the Iraqi capital at
00:20 a.m. local time. Half an hour later, anti-aircraft guns
opened up in downtown and fired off two more sustained volleys.
(Iraq-Strikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin strongly condemned
the U.S. and British air strikes against Iraq on Thursday, and
called for an immediate end to the military action.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said in a statement that such a development of the
situation, to which Russia is decisively opposed, evokes the most
serious concern, a feeling of dismay and deep alarm. The
U.S.-U.K. strikes, which has caused casualties and serious
material damage, crudely violated the U.N. Charter, generally
accepted principles of international law and the norms and rules
of responsible behaviour of states on the world arena.
(Russia-Iraq-Yeltsin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council ended its night
session on Wednesday with members China and Russia condemning the
U.K.-U.S. military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"My position is that we are for the resolution of any crisis
through diplomatic means through the Council," the president of
the 15-member Security Council for the month of December, Jessim
Buallay, of Bahrain, said outside the Council chamber. The
Security Council is expected to meet again on the issue within a
few days, Russian permanent representative to the United Nations
Sergev Lavrov told reporters. (Security Council-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. airstrikes on Iraq Wednesday prompted
House Republican leaders to delay a vote set for Thursday but were
unlikely to affect the support for impeaching President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We are not anticipating taking that action tomorrow
(Thursday)," Republican House speaker-elect Robert Livingston
told reporters after a closed-door party meeting on Wednesday. He
said lawmakers were to "pass a resolution in support of our
troops," adding that the impeachment vote could come Friday or
Saturday. (US-Clinton-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- China's admission to the World Trade Organization
(WTO) should be sped up, Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Shi
Guangsheng and U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky
agreed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shi and Barshefsky were meeting in advance of the 12th session
of the Sino-U.S. Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade (JCCT) to
be convened Thursday and Friday. The two committed themselves to
step up efforts to push forward China's membership of the WTO, a
Chinese diplomat said. (US-China-WTO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China condemned the U.S. airstrikes against Iraq and
urged the U.S. to halt all its military actions immediately, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
China's official response came after the UN Security Council's
emergency consultations on Iraq adjourned and shortly after the
U.S. began airstrikes against Iraq at 0:49 a.m. local time (21:49
GMT) on Thursday. Sun Yuxi, the newly-installed spokesman, said,
"We feel shocked at the U.S. military strikes against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. of having no authorization by the
U.N. Security Council and unilaterally using force against Iraq,
saying, "This has violated the UN Charter and the international
norms." (China-Iraq Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- "This is a sad day for the United Nations and
for the world," U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
"This is also a sad day for me personally," said Annan, who has
undertaken pains-taking efforts to seek peaceful solution to the
Iraqi crisis. This is the first response from Annan following the
U.S. military action against Iraq. (UN-Annan-Statement) 
</P>
</TEXT>
