<HEADLINE> S. Africa May Recognize Palestine State: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is likely
to be among the first countries to recognize the new state of
Palestine if it is declared next May, Business Day newspaper said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
As leader of the Non-Aligned Movement (NAM), South Africa has
taken a high profile on the Middle East in recent weeks, it said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has repeatedly said he will
declare statehood if there is not sufficient progress on the
land-for-peace deal with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Arafat gained the support of the NAM of 113 developing
countries at its Durban summit in September, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting resolved to recognize an independent Palestinian
state with east Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who faces a
right-wing no-confidence motion in parliament, warned he would
freeze all troops redeployments if Arafat continued with plans to
a declaration of independence.
</P>
<P>
United States President Bill Clinton, who left the Middle East
Tuesday, has failed to persuade Israel to carry out troops
withdrawal from occupied territories scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
Should the Palestinian state be proclaimed on May 4, the South
Africa Foreign Ministry can be expected to apply the Montevideo
requirements, an internationally recognized sovereignty test, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
It also quoted diplomatic sources as saying that most European
Union countries can be expected to joint the majority of
non-aligned countries in recognizing Palestinian independence.
</P>
<P>
The paper said Clinton's visit to Palestinian-controlled
territory, the first by a sitting U.S. president, was seen by
Palestinians and many Israelis as implicit U.S. recognition of
Palestinian independence aspirations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
