<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official With Tibetan Buddhist Origins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Waldain, a Living Buddha, is
no longer simply a senior monk at a temple, but a local official
as well.
</P>
<P>
The 48-year-old Waldain is deputy director of the culture
bureau in the Aba Autonomous Prefecture of southwest China's
Sichuan Province. In spite of his age, he still wants to learn
more to help the economic development in his prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Waldain was deputy magistrate of Changqing County in Shandong
Province as part of an exchange program from 1996 to 1998. He was
a kind of envoy between the Han and Tibetan people for years. In
Shandong, he made a lot of Han friends and helped form a
poverty-alleviation partnership between about 130 Han households
in the east and ethnic minorities in the west. Although most of
the Han families were not rich, they sent family member to the
Southwest at their own expense and offered financial aid to
Tibetan and Qiang children for their education.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jiamian, a Chinese sociologist, calls the sending of
ethnic minority officials to prosperous coastal areas to learn
about developing the economy a significant move. The program helps
broaden the scope of ethnic minorities and narrow the gap between
eastern and western parts of China, he says.
</P>
<P>
Waldain was identified as the spiritual descendent of the
Living Buddha of Caodeng Temple in Barkam County in Sichuan and
began to study Tibetan classic scriptures at the age of three.
</P>
<P>
When China resumed the practice of the college entrance exam
system in the late 1970s, Waldain entered the Art Department of
the Central Institute for National Minorities and became a Living
Buddha with a college degree.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
