<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baghdad Rocked by U.S., British Missiles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and British missiles
pounded Baghdad early on Thursday, the heaviest missile attack on
Iraq since the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The first blast were heard at 00:49 a.m. local time (2149 GMT
Wednesday) and were followed by a series of explosions. The
explosions shook the building of Xinhua's Baghdad Bureau in
Mansur, Adrus District where electricity had been cut off.
</P>
<P>
Washington and London immediately announced that the air
strikes, code-named Operation Desert Fox, had begun.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua correspondents in Baghdad saw clouds of smoke drifted
across some parts of the city and the acrid smell of smoke hung
around the city center.
</P>
<P>
The air raids sirens sounded briefly over the Iraqi capital at
00:20 a.m. local time. Half an hour later, anti-aircraft guns
opened up in downtown and fired off two more sustained volleys.
</P>
<P>
Sporadic bursts of fire continued. Eyewitnesses said the
missiles landed around one of the palaces of Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein in central Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
At 02:00 a.m. local time, Xinhua correspondents, on the way to
the Information Center, saw the capital, with a population of four
million, became silent at the intervals of the explosions and
there were few visible signs of panic. At some intersections,
military policemen were checking the passing cars. Some ambulances
were running on the streets, indicating casualties.
</P>
<P>
Initial reports from one Baghdad hospital said at least two
people have been killed and 30 others injured during the attacks.
</P>
<P>
At a teaching hospital in Baghdad's Yarmouk District, hospital
wards were filled with patients suffering from burns. Some moaned
with pain.
</P>
<P>
Culture and Information Ministry officials said a U.S. missile
landed in a residential area, injuring four people and causing
damages to civilian property. The officials said it had caused
damage to a drinking water network. A two kilometer stretch of the
street was flooded.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein admitted on Thursday that
several targets were hit in Iraq and he called on the Iraqi people
to stand up to face "the new round of U.S.-British aggression."
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation, Saddam said on December 16 and
17, the U.S. and Britain which he called "evils", as they have
done in the past eight years, launched strikes against Iraqi
targets.
</P>
<P>
"Fight the enemies of God, the Arab nation and humanity. God
willing, you will be the victors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sirens sounded the all-clear in Baghdad after the raids lasted
about six hours. Residents heard the sirens signaling the end of
five rounds of attack at about 6:40 a.m. local time (0340 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The strikes came shortly after chief U.N. weapons inspector
Richard Butler issued a report on Tuesday, saying Iraq was not
cooperating fully with U.N. weapons inspectors who evacuated from
Baghdad on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Coffee Output Expected at 45,000 tons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 17 (Xinhua) - Tanzania's coffee
production in the 1998/99 crop year is expected to reach 45,000
tons, surpassing an earlier official estimate of 43,000 tons,
local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Harvesting of the arabica and robusta coffee crop in the
southern regions has so far yielded about some 20,000 and 13,000
tons of coffee respectively, while unwashed varieties were put at
3,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
A bumper harvest of the arabica coffee crop in the northern
regions, which is usually between May and March, is also
expected, trading officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
With a currently coffee price for arabica at about 175 U.S.
Dollars per 50-kg bag at export auctions, coffee export this year
is expected to earn Tanzania some 158 million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The coffee production was recorded at 37,000 tons in 1997/98
season due to bad weather.
</P>
<P>
As Tanzania's leading cash crop, coffee accounts for nearly 20
per cent of the total foreign exchange earnings estimated at
about 700 million US Dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has made an ambitious plan to increase its coffee
output to between 80,000 and 100,000 tons by the year 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
