<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The following is the summary of the international reactions to the U.S. air strikes against Iraq: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHINA:
</P>
<P>
-- China is opposed to the use of force against Iraq, China's
Permanent Representative to the United Nations Qin Huasun said in
the United Nations on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the use of force will not only have serious
consequences for the implementation of the Security Council
resolutions, but also pose a threat to international peace as well
as regional security.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the disagreement between UNSCOM and Iraq could be
resolved through dialogue and consultations.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no excuse or pretext to use force against
Iraq", he stressed.
</P>
<P>
RUSSIA:
</P>
<P>
-- Russian President Boris Yeltsin said Thursday he was filled
with indignation and great anxiety at the U.S. and British strikes
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin accused Washington and London of violating the
U.N. charter and international law and endangering world security.
</P>
<P>
He called for the attacks to be halted immediately, saying the
Iraqi crisis can only be settled through political means.
</P>
<P>
FRANCE:
</P>
<P>
-- France expressed its regret over what it called the
"spiral" which has led to the military strikes by the United
States against Iraq Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry communique said that France also
regrets the serious consequences the strikes would inflict on the
Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
"France regrets that the Iraqi leaders have not shown enough
proof of the spirit of full cooperation which was demanded by the
memorandum of agreement of February 23, 1998, between the U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan and Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tarek
Aziz," said the communique.
</P>
<P>
GERMANY:
</P>
<P>
-- The German government expressed the hope that the
U.S. strikes against Iraq will end quickly as soon as possibly.
</P>
<P>
A German government spokesman, Uwe-Karsten Heye said in Bonn
Thursday the federal government regretted that it had come to use
military measures.
</P>
<P>
Heye said that the international community have repeatedly
called on Iraq to comply fully with the resolutions of the
U.N.Security Council.
</P>
<P>
JAPAN:
</P>
<P>
-- Japan Thursday expressed support for air strikes against
Iraq launched by the United States and Britain Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Japan supports this action by the United States and Britain,"
Japanese Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka told a press
conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
