<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Outraged by U.S.-U.K. Airstrikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Thursday reacted
strongly against the airstrikes against Iraq, demanding an
immediate end to the use of force against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin said the actions, launched by the
United States and Britain "flagrantly violated the United Nations
Charter" and norms of international law.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev has canceled a visit to Brussels
on Yeltsin's instructions, Itar-Tass reported. He was scheduled
to attend a meeting of the Russia-NATO Joint Permanent Council.
</P>
<P>
In Madrid, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the airstrikes
would not only complicate the situation in the Gulf, but also
sustain more grave and profound aftermath.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin is meeting with Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov,
Security Council Secretary Nikolai Bordyuzha and General Staff
Chief Anatoly Kvashnin presumably on the airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
Speakers of Russia's two houses of parliament also condemned
the missile strikes.
</P>
<P>
Yegor Stroyev, chairman of the Federation Council, or upper
house of parliament, said the strike would d make it more
complicated for the Russian parliament to ratify START II, the
Russia-U.S. treaty on reduction of strategic nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
At the State Duma, or lower house of parliament, lawmakers set
aside their planned agenda and started discussing the Iraq crisis.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Zyuganov, leader of the Communist party, the largest
Duma faction, described the use of force against Iraq as "an act
of international terrorism with most far-reaching consequences".
</P>
<P>
Local media reports said that Yeltsin has ordered Ivanov to
cut short the visit and return to Moscow immediately.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long been an opponent to the use of force against
Baghdad. Only Wednesday night, Yeltsin telephoned French President
Jacques Chirac, calling for a political solution to the Iraq
crisis over weapons inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
