<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian President Condemns U.S.-U.K. Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
strongly condemned the U.S. and British air strikes against Iraq
on Thursday, and called for an immediate end to the military
action.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said in a statement that such a development of the
situation, to which Russia is decisively opposed, evokes the most
serious concern, a feeling of dismay and deep alarm.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-U.K. strikes, which has caused casualties and serious
material damage, crudely violated the U.N. Charter, generally
accepted principles of international law and the norms and rules
of responsible behaviour of states on the world arena, he said.
</P>
<P>
The strike was carried out at precisely the moment when the
U.N. Security Council was discussing the Iraq problem, he said,
adding that the resolutions on Iraq taken by the Security Council
provide no basis whatsoever for such action.
</P>
<P>
The strike is a blow to the whole system of international
security, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Russia has been undertaking consistent and intensive efforts to
solve the Iraq problem quickly, the president said.
</P>
<P>
"We are still convinced the potential of a political-diplomatic
settlement of the Iraq crisis has not been exhausted, which was
confirmed on the whole by the normal process of cooperation
between Iraq and the United Nations recently," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
It is possible to settle the Iraq problem only by
political-diplomatic means on the basis of observing resolutions
of the United Nations Security Council and international law, he
added.
</P>
<P>
However, the military strikes have seriously damaged the great
work of recent years on the post-crisis settlement in the Gulf and
on dismantling the potential of Iraqi weapons of mass destruction
and their means of delivery, Yeltsin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0340 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel On Alert Though Chances of Being Attacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Although defense officials
said the chances of being attacked by Iraq is "minimum," Israeli
military was on high alert and civilians were urged to update
their gas mask kits Thursday following U.S. air strike against
Iraq at midnight.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has been holding
consultations with senior officials since the U.S. launched the
strikes over alleged Iraq's non-cooperation with U.N. weapons
inspectors, and they will meet again later Thursday, Israel Radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The defense ministry has ordered the troops to be on alert with
radar systems redeployed to detect any coming missiles, and the
officials said Patriotic missile systems and other U.S. defense
equipment are available.
</P>
<P>
During the standoff between Iraq and the U.S.-led forces in the
1991 Gulf War sparked by Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990,
Baghdad fired 39 Scud missiles armed with conventional warheads
at Israel, the closest ally of the U.S. in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The attacks killed one Israeli and wounded scores of others and
caused extensive property damage in the Tel Aviv area.
</P>
<P>
On the heel of the Gulf War, the U.N. Security Council adopted
resolutions to authorize the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) to
oversee Iraq's disarming of weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM have repeatedly run into standoffs with Iraq during the
weapons inspections, which several times drew the U.S. on the
verge of using force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
But as in the latest crisis over the weapons inspection last
month, Israeli officials have stressed that Israel is "outside the
conflict" and that the chances of being attacked by Iraq in
retaliation are very low.
</P>
<P>
A local daily, the Jerusalem Post, reported Thursday that
U.S. President Bill Clinton spoke of the possibility of an attack
on Iraq with Netanyahu Tuesday just before his departure from a
three-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian areas.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu was then quoted as still saying: "Israel is outside
the conflict, and in any case will know how to protect itself if
there is a need to do so."
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also said Netanyahu was informed by the White
House of the attack several minutes before it took place at around
midnight.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai called a meeting of his
senior staff after reports of anti-aircraft fire emerged from
Baghdad. "Preparations are being made," a ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Gas mask distribution centers were opened and citizens were
urged to make sure their gas mask kits are updated and they have
plastic sheeting and tape on hand to seal the doors and windows
if Iraq launched an missile attack.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the panic during the Gulf crisis when people
formed long lines outside the mask distribution centers, life on
the streets is normal and people are calm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0341 </DOCNO>
