<HEADLINE> 2 killed, 30 wounded in U.S. Air Strikes, Report Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- At least two people have been
reportedly killed and another 30 wounded in U.S. air strikes on
the Iraqi capital of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The wounded have been taken to hospitals, according to doctors
of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
However, a precise number of casualties is not immediately known
because the victims scattered in the different sites which were
hit by U.S. missiles.
</P>
<P>
Despite the ongoing air strikes, Baghdad residents went to the
streets as usual and many vehicles were seen in the downtown of
the city as well.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the Iraqi people might have become
accustomed to air strikes as they have experienced them on several
occasions in the past.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the U.S. launched air strikes, Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein called on the Iraqi people to "fight the enemies of
God, enemies of the nation and enemies of humanity."
</P>
<P>
In a related development, at a U.N. Security Council meeting,
Iraq's U.N. envoy Nizar Hamdoon accused chief weapons inspector
Richard Butler of producing a biased report Tuesday which
concluded that Baghdad had not fully cooperated with the
U.N. monitors and triggered the air strikes. 
</P>
