<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maize Output Falls in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The output of maize harvested
this year in Zambia dropped by 30 percent to only 650,000 tons
compared with about 960,000 tons harvested in 1997, according to
Standard Chartered Bank.
</P>
<P>
The production of maize, staple food for Zambians, is less
than half of the maize output of the 1996 harvest year, when the
maize production was as high as 1,410,000 tons, the bank said in
its latest publication available here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
This year's output is the lowest since 1991, necessitating
substantial imports in the final quarter this year and early next
year that will have adverse implications for both inflation and
exchange rate of the country's currency.
</P>
<P>
The production of soya, rice, sorghum and sunflower also fell
but there were important gains in cotton with an increase of 47
percent to 110,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The non-traditional exports have declined by five percent
because of the conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo,
according to the bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
