<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imbalance in Rural Development Draws Attention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- While some residents in Huaxi
Village in east China's Jiangsu Province are enjoying their luxury
houses and cars, needy villagers in a number of northwestern
mountain areas are depending to some extent on government aid to
survive.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old reform and opening-up drive has brought about
great changes for China's countryside as a whole, but due to
climatic, geographic and historical differences, rural development
has been uneven.
</P>
<P>
Economists have called for greater government concern for the
growing economic imbalance among rural people living in different
areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xinmin, an expert with the Rural Investigation Team of
the State Statistical Bureau, has studied this imbalance in
eastern, central and western parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
Rural people in developed eastern provinces, mainly coastal
ones, have benefited from the booming township and village-run
industries, which are mostly export-oriented, and in 1997 their
exports amounted to 621.9 billion yuan (75 billion US dollars),
91.1 percent of the total exports made by all of China's rural
industries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers in resource-rich central areas are making a
good living from mining and farming. But for those living in
western China, rural development has been greatly hampered by
poorer climate and transportation facilities, and a lack of
resources.
</P>
<P>
The statistician also attributes the imbalance to differences
in policies, investment levels and the preparedness of local
villagers.
</P>
<P>
This imbalance has caused notable gaps in both economic
development and individual income, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the gross national product (GNP) in the eastern,
central and western regions stood at 6.346 trillion yuan, 2.467
trillion yuan, and 1.17 trillion yuan respectively, while
per-capita income ranged from 2,746 yuan, 1,931 yuan and 1,404
yuan in these three regions.
</P>
<P>
This phenomenon has worried some local economists. Well-known
Chinese economist Hu An'gang has repeatedly said that if the
problem of regional developmental imbalance is not properly
addressed, the growing gaps among areas may lead to catastrophic
social problems and directly damage the country's political
stability.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese experts have urged the government to ensure
coordinated growth in these three sections of the country and
speed up the development of underdeveloped provinces by adopting
effective policies and measures, especially increasing investment
in the underdeveloped western areas and encouraging cooperation
between developed and underdeveloped regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stance on Entering WTO Reaffirmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China's trade minister has
said that China's policy on entering the World Trade Organization
(WTO) remains firm, according to today's People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
China has always held a positive attitude about entering the
WTO, said Minister Shi Guangsheng of Foreign Trade and Economic
Cooperation, just before he left for the United States to attend
the Sino-U.S. Joint Commission of Commerce and Trade.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations for China's entry into the WTO still continue
after 12 years of efforts on our part, Shi added, because the
resolution of this issue is not only up to China, but also
requires flexibility on the part of other parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
As a developing nation, China must open its markets step by
step, and we cannot accept excessive demands, he reiterated.
</P>
<P>
However, he denied pessimistic views against China's entry
efforts held by some members of the international community,
saying that these views are groundless.
</P>
<P>
China wants to enter the WTO, and is making every effort to
achieve this goal, Shi stressed.
</P>
<P>
China will still be able to solve existing problems after
entering the WTO, if they cannot be solved at present, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
