<HEADLINE> AIDS Orphans in Africa Set to Double: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- More than eight million
children under the age of 15 have lost their mother or both
parents to the Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (AIDS) in
Africa, a report by the U.N. Population Fund said.
</P>
<P>
The report, quoted by the Daily Nation newspaper Thursday,
said the number of AIDS orphans in the 23 countries studied is
projected to double in the next two years.
</P>
<P>
The report said AIDS orphans will reach 40 million by the year
2010, which would be 16 percent of children of the same age.
</P>
<P>
The report is a culmination of a study carried by the United
States Agency for International Development.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS epidemic is more extensive than was previously
thought, particularly in the Sub-Saharan region, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
About 5.8 million people, nearly 16,000 per day, became
infected in 1997, including 2.1 million women and 500,000
children under 15 years old, the reported noted.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, more than 100,000 adults succumb to the scourge with
Nyanza Province recording more than 70,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
The report proposed the improvement of primary health systems
and elimination of "harmful" traditional practices to combat the
epidemic and get it under control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0362 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
