<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks to Provide Euro-Related Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The China Industrial and
Commercial Bank (CICB) is to provide a series of Euro-related
banking services starting on the same day that the new single
currency Euro is launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the CICB said today that those services will
include the opening of Euro accounts, settlements, remittance and
collection business as well as letters of credit, all in the new
Euro. It will also report on the exchange rate of the Euro in
relation to the renminbi and the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
He explained, however, that during the transition period from
January 1, 1999 to December 31, 2001, the use of the Euro will be
limited to the payment of spot exchange transfer accounts. During
this period, customers can conduct business in spot exchange
loans, capital security and guarantees via Euro spot exchange
accounts.
</P>
<P>
He added that the CICB has made considerable preparation for
what is hoped will be next year's smooth launch of Euro banking
services. So far the bank has accomplished the installment and
trial operation of software for clearing facilities in a dozen of
its branches, and has adjusted its foreign exchange computer
accounting software.
</P>
<P>
According to sources in banking circles, the CICB is the first
Chinese bank to announce details of its Euro banking services.
</P>
</TEXT>
