<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Inflation Set to Peak Below 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's inflation
looks set to peak below 10 percent, with consumer inflation
ticking up to 9.4 percent in November from 9.0 percent in
October, Business Day newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the Statistics South Africa figures released
Tuesday suggested inflation was at or near a peak and South
Africa could begin looking forward to sharply lowered inflation
next year.
</P>
<P>
Month on month, the consumer price index did not rise at all,
helped by a fall in the housing component of the index as a
result of a cut in mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
Core inflation, which excluded interest rates and certain
volatile food prices, remained unchanged at 7.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank's monetary policy is usually based on core
inflation instead of headline inflation.
</P>
<P>
Economists said South Africa's inflation performance suggested
interest rates could decline early in the new year unless the
balance of payment put a spoke in the wheel.
</P>
<P>
Business Day quoted Standard Bank's economics division as
saying that if 9.4 percent was inflation's peak, it would be
below the previous upper turning point of 9.9 percent in April
last year.
</P>
<P>
As mortgage rates fall next year, headline inflation will fall
rapidly, reaching about three percent by September.
</P>
<P>
The inflation forecast for next year is six percent, compared
with an estimated average of 6.9 percent for this year.
</P>
<P>
The banks said if inflation remained subdued next year and
there was not too much pressure on the exchange rate, the repo
rate could reach 15 percent by the end of next year, compared
with 19.4 percent at the moment.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate is the rate at which the Reserve Bank lends to
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the balance of payments, not inflation, is
the key factor for interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0367 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fast Investment Growth In Southwestern China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- While Southeast Asian
countries are still struggling with the financial crisis and lack
of investment, decreasing production, and falling exports, the
Chinese province of Yunnan just across the border has had some of
the fastest investment growth in China.
</P>
<P>
The Provincial Statistics Bureau reported today that the
province has started construction of more than 3,000 new projects
this year and investment in fixed assets is expected to reach 68
billion yuan, an increase 14 percentage points higher than the
nation's average.
</P>
<P>
Financial support from the Central government for Yunnan
amounted to 6.2 billion yuan, an increase that is just behind that
for the cities of Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Yunnan borders Laos, Viet Nam and Myanmar and is not far from
Thailand. Half its exports go to Southeast Asia, which provides
half Yunnan's overseas tourists.
</P>
<P>
Companies from the Republic of Korea (ROK), Thailand, and Japan
account for 80 percent of the province's overseas investors. But,
the financial crisis caused big decreases in Yunnan's border and
processing trade from January to June, and caused the number of
tourists from Southeast Asia to drop to a fifth what it was in the
same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The province's GDP from January to June grew around 7 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
