<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Nation and Party Stronger, More Mature: People's Daily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Twenty years of reform and
opening has made China an economically strong country, and the
Communist Party of China has become more mature, with more
coherent force and authority among the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
This statement is made in a commentator's article signed by Ren
Zhongping in today's People's Daily, China's leading official
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the reforms from 1979 to the present, the article
cited a string of figures illustrating the economic achievements
China has made over the past 20 years, and quoted a World Bank
official as saying that the country needed only one generation to
accomplish what other countries took centuries to do.
</P>
<P>
This period saw three major events: the political turmoil in
China and Eastern Europe in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the
financial turmoil that has swept Asia since last year, and the
exceeding massive flooding that hit many parts of China this year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's successful handling of these events
proves that China has stood up and become strong and mature enough
to tackle political and economic problems, and fight against
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
"Our strides marching forward can never be stopped by whatever
evil or hostile forces, be they political, economic or natural,"
the article proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
It underlined that building socialism in China does not require
copying any foreign model, but only requires complying with
China's specific national conditions "to learn from, absorb and
apply the advanced fruits of capitalism on the one hand and to
keep to socialism on the other."
</P>
<P>
"The political turmoil in 1989 and other world crises tells us
that reforms carried out in socialist countries must adhere to
the direction of socialism, while the Asian financial turbulence
serves as a caution that attention must be given to economic
safety in the process of opening up to the outside," the article
said.
</P>
<P>
While calling for continued efforts for reform and opening up
and tapping the country's potentials, the article urged the public
to maintain vigilance against negative political and spiritual
influences from other countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commentator's article urged unswerving efforts
to fight against corruption, as clean, upright and incorruptible
officials are a must for the success of the socialist cause, and a
decisive factor for the very survival of the Communist Party and
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
