<HEADLINE> Air Attacks on Iraq Arouse Controversial Responses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Air strikes against Iraq by
the United States and Britain have aroused controversial responses
in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Prime Minister Jenny Shipley expressed her
Government's support for the action and took Saddam Hussein
responsible for the strikes. But at the same time she showed New
Zealand's regrets over the air strikes, saying innocent civilians
will be "inevitable casualties".
</P>
<P>
According to the Evening Post, Prime Minister Shipley told the
Parliament that the attacks on Iraq came after Saddam Hussein had
been given "repeated opportunities to comply with UN weapons
inspectors".
</P>
<P>
"Once more we are seeing Iraq's promises are proving extremely
hollow," she said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Shipley said she hopes this will be "a shortlived attack",
but clearly it is "necessary to bring Iraq into compliance".
</P>
<P>
Helen Clark, leader of the Labor Party, said in Parliament
while Iraq had flouted UN requirements, the military action
should have been "authorized by the UN Security Council, not by
two members of the council".
</P>
<P>
She said she was concerned that the bombing would "only maim
and kill innocent civilians, not the guilty".
</P>
<P>
Jim Anderton, leader of the New Zealand Alliance, criticized
the bombing and said it would achieve "exactly the opposite" of
what the U.S. intends.
</P>
<P>
"Bombing kills in discriminately. It also does not work. I am
quite certain in my own mind it's not going to work in Iraq," he
said. 
</P>
