<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Politicians, Public React to U.S. Strikes on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. politicians and the
public Wednesday made swift reactions to President Bill
Clinton's order to launch air strikes against Iraq for what he
called its defiance to U.N. weapons inspection resolutions.
</P>
<P>
While lawmakers generally endorsed the president's decision for
the air strikes against Iraq, Senate Majority leader Trent Lott
and some other Republicans questioned the timing, which came on
the eve of a planned House impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
But top Democrats said they fully supported the military
action.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the president acted correctly and responsibly,"
House Minority leader Richard Gephardt, and Senate Minority
leader Tom Daschle, said in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
Lott, who in the past has criticized Clinton for not acting
more aggressively in dealing with Iraqi President Saddam
Hussein, said: "Both the timing and the policy are subject to
question."
</P>
<P>
"While I have been assured by administration officials that
there is no connection with the impeachment process in the House
of Representatives, I cannot support this military action in the
Persian Gulf at this time," Lott said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Many Republicans expressed their fury and they didn't wait
for the bombs to drop to accuse Clinton of manufacturing the
showdown to boost his political standing at the brink of
Thursday's House vote on impeachment, which was now postponed
because of the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
"it's certainly rather suspicious timing," said Republican
Representative Tillie Fowler. "I think the president is
shameless in what he would do to stay in office."
</P>
<P>
Republican Representative Ron Paul denounced the military
action, accusing Clinton of using U.S. troops as pawns to avoid
impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
"How many American soldiers and innocent Iraqi children will
die so that this president can hide from justice?" Paul asked.
"This attack has no basis in protecting our national security
and only increases the danger to our people."
</P>
<P>
Republican Representative John Porter said: "I get the
impression that the president considers himself above the law,"
indicating he has switched his position after earlier announcing
he would oppose impeachment on the floor of the House.
</P>
<P>
"Never underestimate a desperate president," warned Republican
Representative Gerald Solomon. "This time he means business.
What option is left for getting impeachment off the front page
and maybe even postponed?"
</P>
<P>
Democrats were outraged that Clinton's motives were being
questioned.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Senator Robert Torricelli, called the Republican
reaction to strikes against Iraq "as close to a betrayal of the
interests of the United States as I've ever witnessed in the
United States Congress. It's unforgivable and reprehensible."
</P>
<P>
The public also was suspicious of the presidential decision
to order the air strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"That's ridiculous" said Marcia Shockey, a worker at the
Oklahoma Capitol. "Why would anyone go to war to divert
attention?"
</P>
<P>
David Peterson, manager of a Hooters Restaurant in Phoenix,
said Clinton's decision "looks like a good way to stop his
impeachment." Matt Mallec, a 26-year-old bartender in Downtown
Phoenix, was also suspicious of Clinton's motives.
</P>
<P>
"It's ironic how once again, here he is in hot water and that
gets pushed aside and he comes out looking like a hero again,"
he said as he sat in a booth, watching Clinton on CNN.
</P>
<P>
The bombing of Iraq provoked an immediate reaction both in
Washington and New York.
</P>
<P>
Protesters near the White House shouted for stop of the
bombing. They were soon dispersed by police. In New York some
100 demonstrators gathered at Times Square, shouting: "No blood
for oil!" and "Let Iraq live!" 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
