<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Nigeria in 1998: A Year of Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since Abubakar took office, a national reconciliation
process had been in progress in Nigeria, with the gradual release
of all political detainees in the country.
</P>
<P>
Among those freed is former head of state, General Olusegun
Obasanjo, who was detained in 1995 for alleged involvement in a
coup plot against Sani Abacha, and many other opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
It is unfortunate that the reconciliation drive failed to save
the life of Moshoode Abiola, the widely expected winner in the
1993 annulled presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
On July 7, Abiola, who had been in detention since 1994,
suddenly collapsed while he was discussing his release with
Abubakar and visiting U.S. Under-Secretary of State for Political
Affairs, Thomas Pickering. All efforts to save his life failed.
</P>
<P>
The death of Abiola is surely a national tragedy for Nigeria,
but it might prove a blessing for the Abubakar government, which
was saved from a possible confrontation with the pro-Abiola force
triggered by the death of Abiola.
</P>
<P>
Ever since Abacha's death, there had been strong calls for a
national unity government headed by Abiola, though Abiola himself
later reportedly renounced his presidential ambitions after a
meeting with visiting United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan
shortly before his death.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar refused the idea, saying that it poses dangers
unacceptable to his government.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, with the domestic and international support,
Abubakar secured through reconciliation, and quickly embarked on
a new transition to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
After extensive consultations on both national and
international scale, Abubakar announced scrapping of the
transition structure of Abacha, including the disbandment of the
five political parties and the annulment of all the elections
conducted under the National Electoral Commission installed
during the Abacha's regime.
</P>
<P>
In his address to the nation on July 20, which sets out his
political and economic plans, Abubarkar announced that a
presidential election would be held in the first quarter of 1999,
while the newly elected civilian president would take office on
May 29.
</P>
<P>
To make preparations for the 1999 general elections, a new
Independent Electoral Commission has been established, nine new
political parties were registered and fresh voters' registration
was held.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar has made it clear from the beginning that he will not
seek to transform himself into a civilian president.
</P>
<P>
While addressing his first international press conference in
Abuja on September 7, he announced that he will retire from the
armed forces after the hand-over of power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
