<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali King Favors Special Session of Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra
Thursday decided to summon a special session of parliament on
December 24 as petitioned by 62 members of parliament, said a
notice issued by the king's Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The move ended a week-long political uncertainty arising from a
ruling partner's withdrawal last Thursday from the government.
</P>
<P>
Now Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, whose recommendation
for dissolution of parliament for fresh polls was turned down,
will face a no-confidence motion planned by his former ruling
partner and other parties.
</P>
<P>
After sharing power with the Nepali Congress (NC) for three and
a half months, the Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-ML) pulled out, alleging that the NC had failed to implement
the agreements reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Prime Minister and NC President Koirala made a
recommendation to the Royal Palace for dissolution of parliament
for general elections on March 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Hours later, the CPN-ML and its supporters made a submission to
the palace, calling for a special parliament session to discuss a
no-confidence motion they were planning against the government.
</P>
<P>
After returning home Monday from a medical check-up and
treatment in London, King Birendra began the consultation process.
</P>
<P>
The major parties, including the main opposition Communist
Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML), agreed that
elections were the only way out. But they asked Prime Minister
Koirala to step down to make way for a new coalition government
comprising all the major parties for free, fair and impartial
elections.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, King Birendra, on the advice of the
Supreme Court, accepted the submission by 96 MPs to call a special
parliament session, turning down Prime Minister Surya Bahadur
Thapa's recommendation for dissolution of parliament for fresh
polls.
</P>
<P>
The Himalayan kingdom has witnessed five governments since the
mid-term polls in November 1994, which produced a hung parliament
where no single party holds a majority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
