<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0390 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Nigeria in 1998: A Year of Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Along with the political reform process, the present Nigerian
government also started bold and long-awaited economic reforms
by, among others, ordering the merger of the fixed official
exchange rate of one U.S. Dollar to 22 Naira with the Autonomous
Foreign Exchange Market exchange rate by the year end.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation of the dual exchange rates, which have for a
long time been accused of providing a hot-bed for massive
corruption, also paved the way for improved relations between
Nigeria and the international financial agencies such as the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
To combat persistent fuel shortage in the oil-producing
country, Abubakar ordered the repair of major oil refineries and
renounced the state monopoly of fuel import, allowing foreign oil
companies to operate in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
And more importantly, Abubakar announced an ambitious
privatization program that virtually involves all major
state-owned firms, including the National Telephone Firm, the
National Electrical Power Firm and major automobile and steel
plants and dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the reform is to attract foreign and private
investment and allow private investors to manage these enterprices
that have become a bottomless hole of huge state funds due to bad
management and corruption.
</P>
<P>
In launching a national war on corruption, Abubarkar ordered
senior government officials to declare their assets and started
investigations into the Abacha government officials, which have
led to the recovery of more than 700 million U.S. Dollars so far.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's new policies have produced an instant diplomatic
success. In the later half of the year, Nigeria received more
foreign visitors than it did in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Since early July, General Abubarkar has met with a long list
of senior officials from Britain, France, the U.S., the
Commonwealth, the U.N., the Organization of African Unity, the
World Bank and some African countries.
</P>
<P>
At these meetings, Abubakar managed to convince the
above-mentioned countries and organizations to support his
democratization process and requested them to lift the sanctions
against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Nigeria was slammed on with international sanctions
and even temporarily expelled from the Commonwealth for the
execution of writer Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni
minority activists.
</P>
<P>
All the diplomatic shuffles have paid off, as both the
European Union and the U.S. have announced the partial lifting of
their sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group established in 1995
to monitor Nigeria's human rights situation also recommended the
lifting of sanctions against Nigeria during a meeting in London
in October.
</P>
<P>
In a relatively short period of time, Abubakar has won the
hail of most Nigerians for his courage and decisive reforms. But
as the honeymoon is slipping by, Abubarkar, and indeed, the whole
nation will have to prove themselves to be sincere in dealing
with the much tougher challenges they are facing, the ailing
economy, the spreading poverty, and most of all, the finalizatin
of a lasting civil democracy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0391 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
