<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Scientists: Green Tea Can Kill Tumor Cells </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists reported
Wednesday that the result of their study shows green tea contains
substances that can kill tumor cells.
</P>
<P>
"Our research shows that green tea leaves are rich in anti-cancer
compound," said Dorothy Morre, a professor of foods and nutrition at
Purdue University, at a meeting of the American Society of Cell
Biology in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
Dorothy Morre and her husband James Morre, a chemist and
pharmacologist also at Purdue University, said that, before they began
their study on green tea, they had heard reports of green tea's
purported effects. These reports, they added, led them to set out to
see if there was a mechanism.
</P>
<P>
The husband-and-wife team found green tea contains substances
called epigallocatechin gallate, or EGCg for short, which
interfered with tumor-associated activity, but not interfered with
normal activity.
</P>
<P>
The EGCg limits the acitivity of breast cancer tumor cells grown in
the laboratory, but does not seem to affect normal, healthy breast
cells, the Morres reported.
</P>
<P>
They said green tea and black tea both come from the same bush in
the camellia family, but green tea is much richer in EGCg than other
black tea because the latter has been allowed to ferment, a process
which may interfere with compounds such as EGCg.
</P>
<P>
They said this is one of the first studies to directly link the
EGCg in green tea to anti-cancer activity. More tests are needed to
see if EGCg is active in the bodies of people who drink green tea,
they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0393 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
