<HEADLINE> OAU Meeting Ready in Ouagadougou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OUAGADOUGOU, December 17 (Xinhua) -- About 24 heads of state
and 30 delegations from African countries will meet Thursday in
Ouagadougou, capital of Burkina Faso, to discuss conflicts in the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, dubbed the fourth ordinary session of the Central
Organ of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) Mechanism for
Conflict Prevention, Management and Resolution at summit level,
marks a major collective effort to find solutions to crises in
several African countries that tend to threaten the peace of the
African continent.
</P>
<P>
According to a draft agenda made available to Xinhua, the
two-day meeting is going to discuss the conflicts in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Burundi, Guinea Bissau, the
Comoros and the dispute between Ethiopia and Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
By late Wednesday evening, a ministerial meeting was still
going on to deliberate further on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
According to an OAU official, both Congolese President Laurent
Kabila and the rebels are now in Ouagadougou but it is not
decided yet if they would be allowed to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A source from the Foreign Ministry of Burkina Faso said there
is no change of position on the side of Kabila, who refuses
face-to-face talks with the rebels.
</P>
<P>
OAU Secretary-General Salim Ahmed Salim, who was seen at
Wednesday night's ministerial meeting, is expected to deliver
reports on the above-mentioned five issues.
</P>
<P>
The reports, made available to Xinhua, said the foundation for
a peaceful solution to the Congo crisis have already been laid by
previous initiatives launched in and outside Africa.
</P>
<P>
Salim expressed the hope that the meeting will assist the
Congolese parties to conflict "in narrowing the differences and
bridging the gap on positions relating to a cessation of
hostilities, a standstill of the forces and the establishment of
a cease-fire, including, the modalities of its signing."
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Anjouan, the OAU chief said consultations
are still going on to respond quickly to the Comoran government's
request to assist in restoring peace, security and stability
there.
</P>
<P>
Recent conflicts between factions of Anjouan separatists since
December 5 have claimed more than 60 lives and forced local
residents to flee the Island.
</P>
<P>
On December 11, an OAU military delegation ended its
investigation in Anjouan and is believed to have reported its
findings to Salim.
</P>
<P>
According to an earlier report, the meeting will debate on the
report and discuss the possibility of employing a peace-keeping
force in Anjouan.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Guinea Bissau, the Secretary-General
appealed to both OAU member countries and the international
community to provide logistic and other assistance to enable the
agreed interposition force to be deployed by the target date of
mid-December.
</P>
<P>
The interposition force is agreed on by both the government
and opposition forces in the Nigerian capital Abuja in November.
The parties also agreed to establish a unity government, but
there is still differences about the composition of such a
government, although an opposition member has been appointed as
the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Salim's report also blamed the National Union of Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) for the current stalemate in the
peace process of Angola and urged UNITA to comply with its
obligations under various agreements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
