<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Raps at U.K.-U.S. Military Action Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China on Wednesday
night condemned the U.K.-U.S. military action against Iraq as a
violation of the U.N. Charter and international law.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, Chinese permanent representative to the United
Nations, told a night session of the Security Council, "We were
deeply shocked by this act and condemn it."
</P>
<P>
The military action came as Iraq, with the joint effort by
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the international community,
had resumed its cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and
progress had also been made in arms verification, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Against this backdrop, the two countries' unprovoked military
action is totally unjustified," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are against acts of power politics of unilateral resort to
the use of or threat of force in international relations, we
believed that such acts contravening the international law and the
norms guiding international relations are in themselves a serious
threat to international peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
"China has always strongly advocated the peaceful settlement
of international disputes and is against the use of or threat of
force in international relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
The differences between Iraq and UNSCOM could be properly
solved through dialogue and consultation, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The use of force is far from helping with the settlement and
may bring about serious consequences for the implementation of
relevant Security Council resolutions, for the relations between
Iraq and the United Nations, and for the peace and stability in
the region and in other parts of the world," said Qin.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Chinese envoy called on London and Washington to
immediately stop military strikes, to avoid any act that may
worsen the situation and to return to dialogue and consultation.
</P>
<P>
On UNSCOM's report on the alleged Iraqi failure to fully
cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors, Qin said, "The leader of
UNSCOM has played a dishonorable role in this crisis, and this
report is one-sided and evasive of the facts."
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM leader, Richard Butler, should be held responsible
for the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia joined China in condemning the military action against
Iraq. Other Security Council members, including Brazil, Kenya and
Sweden, said that only the 15-member Security Council was obliged
to deal with the crucial issue of peace and war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
