<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Losing Appeal with Foreign Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's appeal as a
destination for international investment has deteriorated in the
past three years, according to a recent survey commissioned by the
American Chamber of Commerce in New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
Questionnaires sent to 400 companies in New Zealand by Waikato
University drew 48 responses from a cross section of industries
who are identified as being overseas-based investors by the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
More than half say they have considered selling or relocating
away from New Zealand in the past three years, with Australia
being the most attractive alternative.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, political instability in the country
is the No.1 problem in attracting investors. This is followed by
Australia as an alternative for investment, rising compliance
costs, slow growth and excessive regulations.
</P>
<P>
A United Nations world investment report published recently
shows New Zealand as the most highly dependent of all developed
countries on foreign direct investment (FDI).
</P>
<P>
From 1986 to 1991, FDI as a percentage of gross fixed capital
formation was 19.2 percent in New Zealand. By 1996 it had risen to
26.7 percent. Percentages of other developed countries have
hovered around 2.6 percent to four percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
