<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Behind U.S. Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
ordered military strikes on suspected Iraqi military and security
targets Wednesday, claiming that Baghdad must be punished for
refusing to cooperate with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. strikes came shortly after Chief U.N. weapons
inspector Richard Butler's Tuesday report on Iraq's non-compliance
with U.S. resolutions, analysts pointed out that there are other
covert reasons for the U.S. being so eager to launch a military
strike against long-time trouble-maker Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of 1998, the U.S. has been thrown into
passivity more than once on the Iraqi weapons inspection issue. It
was prepared previously to launch two air strikes against Iraq,
but had called them off at the last minute amid strong worldwide
opposition and mediation.
</P>
<P>
The two aborted strikes gave some the impression that
U.S. influence could be wanning, and that it had been led by the
nose by Iraq. Hard-liners at home also began to criticize the
Clinton administration for being too weak in handling the Iraq
issue.
</P>
<P>
To demonstrate its determination and to regain initiative on
the Iraqi issue, the Clinton administration views the strikes as a
last chance before year's end to give a heavy blow to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
To overthrow the Saddam administration is another reason behind
the strikes. In the November weapons inspection crisis, the
U.S. had already made clear its intention to support opposition
forces to unseat Saddam from inside.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally televised address on Wednesday, Clinton
reiterated the intention of replacing the Saddam regime with a new
one. Besides offering financial support, Washington believes it is
necessary to support Saddam's opponents morally. Launching an air
strike seems to be a good way to achieve that goal.
</P>
<P>
The strikes were also thoughtfully timed in light of the
current situation in Washington. Analysts believed that to some
extent domestic considerations are an even more important factor
behind the strikes.
</P>
<P>
In the face of a possible impeachment stemming from the Monica
Lewinsky affair, the White House these days is going all out to
win republicans in the Senate from voting for impeaching Clinton.
</P>
<P>
So far, most of the republicans in the House of Commons have
said they would vote for an impeachment, which makes the prospect
of a house impeachment vote, which is set for Thursday, dim for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
To prolong the interval before the voting and win support from
those republicans who have not yet made up their mind on the
impeachment issue, as well as to distract public attention from
the Lewinsky case, a military strike against Iraq seems to be a
much-desired option for Washington. Indeed, the house vote has
been postponed because of the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
The strikes are also widely believed to be an effort for the
U.S. to strengthen its profile as a middle east peace maker. The
U.S. role in the Middle East has been weakened by its repeated
failure to bring the Middle east peace process on a set track.
</P>
<P>
Since the Israel government is adhering to its hard-line stand,
the implementation of the Wye Peace Accord, which was signed in
October between Israel and Palestine, has been deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
Washington now needs to do something in another front in the
Middle east to prove its leading role in the region, and ensure
that its Mideast strategy remains intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0407 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
