<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prison Population Rockets in New Zealand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The number of people in
prison in New Zealand has jumped by more than 70 percent and the
prisoners are serving longer sentences for more violent crimes
than they did a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
Quoting a latest prison census, which was taken on November 20,
1997, the Dominion reported Thursday that the census shows there
were 4,935 sentenced prisoners in New Zealand, a country with a
population of less than 3.8 million. The 4,935 prisoners included
4,728 male and 207 female.
</P>
<P>
The number of sentenced male prisoners was up 77.6 percent from
2,662 in 1987 when the first prison census was taken. Sentenced
female prisoners increased 72.5 percent from 120 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
In the foreword to the census report, Justice Secretary Colin
Keating said the rise in the prison population was mainly caused
by a big increase in convictions for violent and serious offenses,
leading to more prisoners serving longer sentences, the
Wellington-based newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
There was a disproportionate number of Maoris in prison. Maoris
 comprise 14 percent of the general population, but make up 43.8
percent of the male prison population and 42 percent of the
female.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Corrections Minister Nick Smith was quoted as
saying that the census is a "sad commentary" on the level of
offending, particularly violence, in society.
</P>
<P>
"Society is becoming a more violent place and we have got to be
more innovative if we are going to prevent a similar increase in
the next decade," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0409 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year-Ender: Nigeria in 1998: A Year of Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The year of 1998, which
witnessed the most dramatic and drastic changes ever happened in
a single year, will go down in the history of Nigeria as a year
of rekindled hope.
</P>
<P>
Nigerians entered 1998 with high expectations and keen
anxiousness for a general election, which if it took place in
August as scheduled, would have turned the country into civil
rule after almost 15 years of military rule.
</P>
<P>
The country, which has seen only three civilian rulers since
its independence from British Colonial rule in 1960, had been a
condemned member of the international society.
</P>
<P>
From June 1994 to June 1995, late military leader Sani Abacha
summoned a constitutional conference which produced a new
constitution for the country, but he never published it until his
sudden death in June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The constitutional conference asked Abacha to hand over power
to a civilian government but provided no date for him to do so.
In Nigerians' words, it gave him a blank check for him to fill.
</P>
<P>
Ever since Abacha announced a three-year transition program in
October 1995, Nigerians had been waiting for the coming civilian
presidency.
</P>
<P>
But Abacha never took action.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he claimed that it was not new either in Africa or in
other parts of the world for a military general to run for
civilian presidency.
</P>
<P>
As a result, numerous organizations mushroomed in Nigeria to
campaign for Abacha's presidency. The most prominent of them is
an orginization called Youth Earnestly Ask for Abacha, or YEAA.
</P>
<P>
In early March, YEAA launched a mass rally in capital Abuja in
support of Abacha's presidency.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day mass rally, government offices were closed,
police were mobilized to keep order, and various artists groups
were employed for entertainment, even the National Football Team
was called in to boost the morale.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the anti-Abacha rallies organized by
pro-democracy groups were dispersed by police using tear gases.
Some people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
When it seemed that a civilian Abacha presidency was only a
matter of time, Abacha suddenly died of heart attack on the early
morning of June 8, and hence the election went up in smoke. And
Abacha's death triggered off various speculations about the
circumstances of his death, some even suggested a foul play, but
with no proof.
</P>
<P>
On June 9, the Provisional Ruling Council recommended the then
Chief of Defense Staff, Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar to be
successor to Abacha and he was sworn in as the head of state and
commander in chief of the armed forces at the same day.
</P>
<P>
Sine then, Abdulsalam Abubakar, a 56-year-old career
officer unknown to most world leaders until June 9, has emerged
as the man on whom most hopes rest to rescue Africa's most
populous nation from its collapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0410 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
