<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, China Oppose U.S.-led Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia, China and Greece
Thursday expressed their strong opposition to the U.S.-led air
strikes against Iraq while France, Germany and Italy expressed
regret over it.
</P>
<P>
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said in Madrid that Russia
condemns the U.S. airstrikes and calls for an immediate halt to
the military operation.
</P>
<P>
The strikes "can not only complicate the situation in the Gulf
but also have more serious consequences, and over a wider area,"
Ivanov was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Permanent Representative to the United Nations Qin
Huasun said on Wednesday that China is opposed to the use of force
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the use of force will not only have serious
consequences for the implementation of the Security Council
resolutions, but also pose a threat to international peace as well
as regional security.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no excuse or pretext to use force against
Iraq," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
While condemning the U.S. airstrikes against Iraq, Chinese
Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi urged the United States to
halt all its military actions immediately.
</P>
<P>
Sun Yuxi said, "We feel shocked at the U.S. military strikes
against Iraq. "
</P>
<P>
The United States has no authorization by the UN Security
Council and "this has violated the UN Charter and the
international norms," Sun.
</P>
<P>
Greek Defense Secretary Dimitris Apostalakis said Thursday that
Greece opposes military actions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Apostalakis told reporters that Greece opposed "military
options of this kind" as the strikes would not help solve the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Greek media also expressed their opposition to the U.S. and
British military attacks on Iraq in editorial comments.
</P>
<P>
Nicaraguan President Arnoldo Aleman said Wednesday that he
deeply deplored the United State's attack against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"I deplore it, I believe there are democratic ways, a dialogue
or organizations like the United Nations where (problems) can be
resolved without bringing pain to any country," he said.
</P>
<P>
France regreted what it called the "spiral" which has led to
the military strikes by the United States against Iraq early
Thursday Baghdad time.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry statement said that France also
regrets the serious consequences the strikes would inflict on the
Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Thursday that Italy
deeply regretted the U.S.-led air strikes and demanded a rapid end
to them.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq crisis should be resolved through political means by
the United Nations, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Dini said he had phoned U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and British Foreign Minister Robin Cook Wednesday night
after the first round of air strikes at Baghdad early on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Germany called Thursday for a rapid end to military actions
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The German government hopes it will be possible to put a rapid
end to the military operations," said spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye.
</P>
<P>
He said that Bonn "deplored" the use of military measures in
the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also noted that the international community had
repeatedly called on Iraq to comply fully with the resolutions of
the U.N. Security Council. 
</P>
