<HEADLINE> Jordan Closes Border with Iraq to Prevent Refugee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordan closed its border with
Iraq earlier Thursday to prevent possible influx of refugees who
flee Iraq as a result of the ongoing United States air strike.
</P>
<P>
"We have closed our borders with Iraq, and we do not intend to
permit the entry of people coming from Iraq," the semi-official
Jordan Times Thursday quoted Interior Minister Nayef Al Qadi as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Jordan will not open its border with Iraq for refugees, but it
is willing to offer any possible assistance, if needed, on the
Iraqi side of the border, Qadi added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan's official news agency, the Petra, reported
that the situation remained calm and there was no influx of
refugees along the Jordanian-Iraqi border until 04:30 GMT Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of refugees fled Iraq and flooded Jordan
during the Gulf war (1990-1991), creating a severe burden for the
kingdom's economy in the following years. 
</P>
