<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Oil Industry Struggles Due to Price Slump </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Colombia's oil
exports in the first 10 months this year went down by 267 million
U.S. dollars due to a continuing world price slump.
</P>
<P>
The Mines and Energy Ministry said Wednesday that oil exports
totaled 1.8 billion dollars in the period as against 2.1 billion
dollars in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Oil output went up from 600,000 to 800,000 barrels a day in
October, prompting a 13 percent surge in exports in the first 10
months.
</P>
<P>
But the prices dropped to 13.29 dollars a barrel in October
from an average of 19.08 dollars in 1997 for the highest-priced
crude.
</P>
<P>
If prices fall below 10 dollars a barrel, the high-cost output
zones in the country may be closed. The production of the
country's crude costs four to five dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
If the slump continues, Colombia could lose 13 billion dollars
worth of oil revenues between 2001 and 2006, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Oil made up the bulk of export revenues for the country in
1997, but it could be surpassed by coffee this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
