<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China's admission to the
World Trade Organization (WTO) should be sped up, Chinese Foreign
Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng and U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky agreed here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shi and Barshefsky were meeting in advance of the 12th session
of the Sino-U.S. Joint Committee on Commerce and Trade (JCCT) to
be convened Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
The two committed themselves to step up efforts to push forward
China's membership of the WTO, a Chinese diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also agreed that significant progress has been
made concerning China's membership, but acknowledged that further
negotiations were needed on some important issues, the diplomat
told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
Shi told Barshefsky that any Sino-U.S. agreement on China's
membership in the WTO should be in the economic interests of both
sides.
</P>
<P>
The two also discussed other bilateral trade issues.
</P>
<P>
Shi, who arrived here on Tuesday, is to co-chair the JCCT
session with U.S. Commerce Secretary William Daley. The session is
the first high level economic and trade talks after the exchange
of visits by the presidents of China and the U.S. 
