<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Hit on Iraq Unlikely to Affect Clinton Impeachment Outcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. airstrikes on Iraq
Wednesday prompted House Republican leaders to delay a vote set
for Thursday but were unlikely to affect the support for
impeaching President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"We are not anticipating taking that action tomorrow
(Thursday)," Republican House speaker-elect Robert Livingston
told reporters after a closed-door party meeting on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said lawmakers were to "pass a resolution in support of our
troops," adding that the impeachment vote could come Friday or
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the Capitol Hill, there were indications that "Operation
Desert Fox" was enhancing Republican resolve to refer charges
against Clinton to the Senate for trial.
</P>
<P>
"The suspicion some people have about the President's motives
in this attack is itself a powerful argument for impeachment,"
Republican House majority leader Dick Armey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, another top House Republican, Gerald Solomon, had
denounced Clinton's action.
</P>
<P>
"We should not be handling the impeachment while the bombs are
in the air, and that's exactly the reason he's doing it," he told
CNN.
</P>
<P>
Republican Spencer Bachus said they are going to impeach
Clinton, adding that any delay would be momentary.
</P>
<P>
The attack "solidified support around impeaching the
president," said Bachus.
</P>
<P>
In a stunning move, Senate Republican leader Trent Lott said he
would not support U.S. air strikes against Iraq, hinting that he
suspected that impeachment had influenced Clinton's action.
</P>
<P>
"While I have been assured by administration officials that
there is no connection with the impeachment process ... I cannot
support this military action," Lott said in a statement, adding
"both the timing and the policy are subject to question."
</P>
<P>
"If, however, military action is taken, all Americans will
fully support our troops in battle," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 435-member House of Representatives was predicted to pass
at least one of the charges of perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
According to a poll Wednesday night by CNN, one third of
Americans believe Clinton ordered the attacks against Iraq to
divert attention from moves to impeach him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
