<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-Saving Irrigation Used Widely in E. China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
which produces one-tenth of the country's grain, has become the
largest user of water-saving irrigation facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
Currently, 2.11 million hectares of the province's 4.67 million
hectares of farmland have been covered with a water-saving
irrigation system, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Shang Mengping, an official with the provincial water
conservation department, said that this system has helped local
farmers cut their water consumption by at least 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to Shang, per-capita water resources in the
province stand at only 357 cubic meters, 20 cubic meters less than
even Israel. About 1.8 million hectares of local farmland have
been hit by droughts of varying severity over the past 48 years,
resulting in yearly losses of some 1.5 billion kilos of grain.
</P>
<P>
To offset the impact of droughts, the province experimented
with many water-saving methods, such as leveling the land and
reinforcing existing irrigation canals, in the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, Shandong has introduced advanced irrigation
technology and equipment, including spraying, seeping and dripping
methods from the United States, Israel, Australia, Italy and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 4.4 billion yuan has been used by the
province to create a water-saving irrigation network.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0436 </DOCNO>
