<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Replaces South as Leading Grain Supplier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The traditional practice of
"shipping surplus grain from south China to north China" is being
reversed, as north and northeast China have emerged as grain
giants in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the additional grain output of
the plain of the Yellow, Huaihe and Haihe rivers and the three
provinces in northeast China totaled 67.7 billion kilos in the
1984-96 period, accounting for 68 percent of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Northeast China, which embraces Jilin, Liaoning and
Heilongjiang provinces with an area of 1.24 million square
kilometers, is expected to become the country's largest grain base
early next century.
</P>
<P>
Jilin Province occupies only one-twentyfifth of China's
cultivated land, but produces one-tenth of the commercial grain
quota set by the state and one-half of the country's maize export,
annually.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Chinese Academy of Sciences predict that the
grain output of northeast China will climb to 99 billion kilos by
the year 2005, and the region is able to provide 45 billion kilos
of grain annually, which can feed 110 million people, or one-third
of China's future urban population.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, grain production in the country's southern
provinces is shrinking, as the output of land in the middle and
lower reaches of the Yangtze River has shown signs of decreasing
in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
