<HEADLINE> East China Province Expects Double-Digit Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province,
whose gross domestic product (GDP) ranks third in the country, is
expected to see its economy grow by around 11 percent this year,
exceeding the targeted nine percent, local analysts forecast.
</P>
<P>
This will help the country realize the national goal of eight
percent growth this year, they say.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the Provincial Statistics Bureau show that the
province generated 495 billion yuan in GDP for the first nine
months of the year, up 10.5 percent over the same 1997 period.
</P>
<P>
Although it has been hit hard by the Asian financial crisis,
with exports falling short of the year's growth target of ten
percent, Shandong has done been doing well in many other sectors,
thanks to a series of measures to stimulate domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The province secured a good harvest of major farm crops
including grain, cotton, oil seeds and fruit, with grain output
reaching 43 million tons, laying a sound foundation for
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sector also has been picking up, with added
value growing by 12.4 percent for the first ten months, and
experts predict a 12.5 percent rise for the entire year.
</P>
<P>
Added value in the service sector has been increasing at a 11.7
percent rate so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Local experts say that Shandong is capable of maintaining a
stable economy for years to come, and this has made them more
optimistic about the upward trend of the local economy.  
</P>
</TEXT>
