<HEADLINE> Ration Coupons Reflect China's History </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The old coupons and samples on
display in the Chinese capital of Beijing reflect the tremendous
changes that have taken place in the country over the past 40
years.
</P>
<P>
An unknown number of coupons were a necessity in the country
for buying a wide range of products, from grain to industrial
products for people's daily life, since the central government
issued the first set of coupons in 1953.
</P>
<P>
Organizers of the ongoing show put on display more than 1,000
kinds of coupons collected in Beijing alone. They had all been
abolished by 1993 and so was the case in other parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
An old bicycle-purchasing card tells the visitors that in 1973
there was only one such coupon for every 50 people, and another 30
industrial coupons were necessary if one wanted to buy a bike.
</P>
<P>
And it may be hard now to imagine that newly married couples at
that time had to get a coupon specially for couples if they wanted
to buy any furniture.
</P>
<P>
The first set of flour coupons was issued by the Beijing
municipal government in November 1953, when the first five-year
plan became effective in China.
</P>
<P>
Beijing issued rationing cards for edible oil on July 1, 1954,
and limited the supply of meat in 1957. And coupons were needed
when Beijingers bought shoes in 1960. There were altogether 102
kinds of goods that required coupons in 1962, 44.8 percent of all
the products then available.
</P>
<P>
"It was a really hard time, and the whole country was in
financial difficulties," said 82-year-old Mr. Bai.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing city government abolished coupons for eggs
and meat on December 1, 1992, and for edible oil on May
10, 1993, because of China's fast-changing economy.
</P>
<P>
However, many Beijingers have kept these coupons as souvenirs
of another time, and some collectors also exchange such items with
one another.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0444 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Make Report to Cope With Y2K Bug in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 17 (Xinhua) -- A Sri Lankan national task
force has compiled a report specifying recommendations to cope
with the Year 2000 Millennium Bug or Y2K issue, and submitted the
report to President Chandrika Bandaranaike Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
The report contains specific proposals on how to tackle the
information systems in key spheres such as power generation,
ports, airports, telecommunication, and health and aviation after
the year 2000, Professor Samaranayake told reporters at Temple
Trees, the presidential palace, Wednesday before submitting the
report to Kumaratunga.
</P>
<P>
The National Y2K Task Force, headed by Chairman of the Council
of Information Technology V.K. Samaranayake, comprises 20 eminent
professionals from both public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
Samaranayake said that the main problem with most computer
systems is that they use two digits to represent years, but when
it comes to the turn of the millennium the computers will show 00
for 2000, in the same manner as 98 for 1998.
</P>
<P>
"There are embedded chips and other integral parts of the
computer in which the corresponding changes should be made," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Samaranayake said that they had approached all key institutions
in the country and obtained vital information to resolve the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The public must also be kept informed that there is no need for
panic. There are 381 days left and we should make the best use of
that time, Samaranayake said.
</P>
<P>
He explained possible options in dealing with the situation
such as coding the computers from different years. In any event
all the information systems in the country need not be changed
before the turn of the millennium, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
