<HEADLINE> South Korea Retains Men's Team Pursuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea defeated a
Kazakshtan team hit by jinx in the final to retain the men's team
pursuit cycling title at the Asian Games here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mechanical problems made Valeriy Titov and Dmitriy Muravyev
fall only 100 meters into the race, causing the final to restart.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan was apparently deprived of the chance to revenge its
loss to the Koreans at the last Games in Hiroshima when the team
had to race without Titov, who suffered several bruises.
</P>
<P>
South Korea finally clocked four minutes 36.609 seconds, nearly
seven seconds faster than the central Asian team.
</P>
<P>
"We have trained for one whole year and today we finally get
the good result," said Ji Sung-Hwan, who won his second gold after
taking the 1-km time trial title here.
</P>
<P>
South Korean head coach Lee Young-Woo said he was not sure of
winning even when the Kazakhstan team was reduced to three.
</P>
<P>
"I could only say we had 49 percent chance and they got 51
percent. After two of their members fall our chance improved but
two of their riders are very very strong."
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan carried home the silver while China defeated Chinese
Taipei in the third place decider to win the bronze medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
