<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina, Chile Sign Border Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Argentine President
Carlos Menem and his Chilean counterpart Eduardo Frei Wednesday
signed a treaty on the limits of continental icefields, ending the
last border dispute between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony took place in the government house and was
attended by foreign ministers, high-ranking government officials
and congressional representatives from the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, President Menem said the pact was "a
new stage, a new history and a new path, which will lead to
strength and union between two peoples willing to solve pending
issues in a mature way."
</P>
<P>
Visiting President Frei said that with the signing of the
treaty, the two countries can build a future of integration, peace
and confidence.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, known as the "agreement between the Argentine and
Chilean republics to set the boundary from Mount Fitzroy to Daudet
Hill" establishes a borderline in the disputed icefields.
</P>
<P>
Since the signing of a peace treaty between Argentine and Chile
in 1984, the two governments have solved 23 of the 24 pending
zones, which left only the limits of the continental icefields to
be resolved.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Menem and Chilean President Patricio Aylwin signed a
treaty dividing the more than 2,300 square kilometer zone into
1,250 square kilometers for Argentina and 1,057 for Chile. The
pact was rejected by congressional members in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The treaty signed Wednesday has widespread support among
lawmakers in the two countries and is expected to be approved by
both congresses.
</P>
<P>
The pact is signed as good economic and political relations
prevail between the two countries. Recently, Argentina backed
Chile's stand that General Augusto Pinochet should be sent back to
his country.
</P>
<P>
In a statement signed on Tuesday, the Chilean government said
it fully supported Argentina's sovereignty over the Malvinas
(Falklands) Islands.
</P>
<P>
Argentina, a member of the Mercosur, and Chile, an associate
member of the trade bloc, have recorded growing commercial
exchanges of 600 million dollars in 1990 to 2.6 billion in
1997. Trade volume is expected to reach 3 billion dollars this
year.
</P>
<P>
Chilean investments in Argentina total 6 billion dollars and
Chile is one of Argentina' s most important trade and investment
partners.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the new border treaty is expected to further
boost bilateral relations, integration in the Mercosur union and
in Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0454 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Against Lifting Ocalan's Travel Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 16 (Xinhua) - - Turkey will file an appeal
against the decision to lift Abdullah Ocalan's travel
restrictions, said Augusto Sinagra, an Italian lawyer representing
Turkey on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under an Italian court ruling on Wednesday, Ocalan can move
freely within Italy, despite his lack of identification documents.
</P>
<P>
Sinagra called the court's decision "contradictory and
surprising as if a Turkish arrest warrant and extradition request
didn't exist".
</P>
<P>
The appeal will ask Italian authorities to take the "necessary
precautionary measures regarding Ocalan", he said.
</P>
<P>
The original restrictive measures imposed on the Kurdish
Worker's Party (PKK) leader, based on international warrant issued
by Germany, forbade him from leaving the Rome metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
But Germany said that it will not seek to extradite Ocalan to
Germany, because it feared disturbances among the country's
Kurdish community.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Almea said the appeals court
decision changed nothing in practical terms, saying that for
security reasons Italian authorities will continue to keep Ocalan
under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister designate Bulent Ecevit said Ocalan "was
already in fact a free man". Ecevit said that he still did not
know the scope of the ruling, but that since arriving in Italy,
Ocalan "has been able to talk with whoever he pleases and live
with all the comforts".
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz said the court
decision referred only to the German warrant, and thus Ocalan
should still be restricted based on Turkey's extradition request.
</P>
<P>
"If the Kurdish leader is released without any conditions, we
will appeal," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan is currently under house arrest in Rome, and Italy has
refused Turkey's extradition request because Italian law bars
extradition to countries where defendants could face the death
penalty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
