<HEADLINE> China Condemns U.S. Airstrikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China today condemned the
U.S. airstrikes against Iraq and urged the U.S. to halt all its
military actions immediately, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
today.
</P>
<P>
China's official response came after the UN Security Council's
emergency consultations on Iraq adjourned and shortly after the
U.S. began airstrikes against Iraq at 0:49 a.m. local time (21:49
GMT) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Sun Yuxi, the newly-installed spokesman, said, "We feel shocked
at the U.S. military strikes against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
He accused the U.S. of having no authorization by the UN Security
Council and unilaterally using force against Iraq, saying, "This
has violated the UN Charter and the international norms."
</P>
<P>
Sun stressed that China has always stood for peaceful means to
solve international disputes and is opposed to the use of force
in international relations.
</P>
<P>
EArlier, Qin Huasun, China's Permanent Representative to the
UN, said: "The use of force will not only have serious
consequences for the implementation of the Security Council
resolutions, but also pose a threat to international peace as well
as regional security."
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the U.S. air attack, involving
long-range cruise missiles, was made in response to Iraq's
continued defiance of U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Sources say that U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered the
airstrikes after reading the latest U.N. reports about
noncompliance by the Iraqis and consulting with his national
security staff. 
