<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of U.S. Strikes on Iraq Since Gulf War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States launched
airstrikes, codenamed "Operation Desert Fox," against Iraq on
Thursday following a U.N. report on Baghdad's lack of cooperation
with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The operation were set to be the heaviest since it led
"Operation Desert Storm" to oust Iraqi troops from Kuwait in the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The previous attacks were as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- January 17, 1993: The United States fired more than 40
Tomahawk cruise missiles at a factory near Baghdad suspected of
being linked to a secret nuclear arms program, after it acused
Iraq of establishing surface-to-air missile batteries in southern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
-- June 27, 1993: Two U.S. warships fired 24 Tomahawks at the
headquarters of Iraqi intelligence in reprisal for an alleged
plot to kill former U.S. president George Bush in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
-- July 24, 1993: After Iraqi radars locked on U.S. aircraft, a
U.S. warplane fired a missile at an anti-air positions in southern
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
-- October 7, 1994: The United States sent aircraft carriers,
warplanes and 54,000 troops to the Persian Gulf following Iraq's
large-scale troop movements to the Iraqi-Kuwaiti border. Iraq
withdrew its forces from the border in pressure of U.S. threat of
attacks.
</P>
<P>
-- September 3-4, 1996: In retaliation for an Iraqi army
incursion into Kurdish areas in northern Iraq, the United States
fired cruise missiles at air defence installations, including
radar posts, surface-to-air missile batteries, and anti-aircraft
command and control posts in southern Iraq. The missiles, fired
from warplanes and ships in the Gulf region, left five dead and 19
injured, Iraq said.
</P>
<P>
1997-98
</P>
<P>
After Iraqi President Saddam Hussein decided in October 1997 to
expel US arms inspectors working for the United Nations, the
United States built up an armada in the Gulf to strike Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The showdown was defused in February 1998 by U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan who clinched a last-minute deal in Baghdad
opening the gates of presidential sites to U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
But in October, Iraq broke off all cooperation with UNSCOM, and
only once U.S. bombers were in the air did Baghdad agree to
unconditional resumption of U.N. weapons inspections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0468 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Huge Diamond Trade Potential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Local and foreign sources have
forecast that China's annual diamond sales can be expected to
reach 20 billion yuan by 2000, making the country the world's
third largest diamond market, after the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The British De Beers, the world's renowned diamond supplier,
is singled out for making the forecast by the International
Business News published here.
</P>
<P>
This would mean a new diamond market with huge potential for
diamond suppliers worldwide, since China plans to open up its
diamond market, according to the British De Beers, the world's
renowned diamond supplier and experts.
</P>
<P>
With living standards improving rapidly, China has seen the
steady rise of its diamond trade, with domestic sales topping 3.75
billion yuan last year, up 13.6 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports of processed diamonds have increased to
some 100 million U.S. dollars at peak years.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, the country's leading commercial city, has over 90
local companies processing and marketing diamonds, compared with
only a handful five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government plans to exploit a broader overseas
market for local diamond products by aligning the industry
with international practice.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government plans to open a national
diamond exchange in Shanghai, which is now under construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
