<HEADLINE> Russian, German Dominate Biathlon World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Pavel Rostovtsev
clinched his first biathlon World Cup victory by winning a
20-kilometer race and German Uschi Disl won women's 15-km in
Osrblie, Slovakia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rostovtsev clocked 52 minutes, 25 seconds followed by Vesa
Hietalanti of Finland with a time of 52 minutes, 33.4 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Rene Cattarinussi of Italy finished third, 23.3 seconds behind
the winner.
</P>
<P>
Rostovtsev missed two shooting targets, while Hietalanti had
one and Cattarinussi had two.
</P>
<P>
Norway's Ole Einar Bjoerndalen, the Olympic champion and
overall World Cup winner, finished 77th.
</P>
<P>
In the World Cup standings, Rostovtsev had a five-point lead
over the Norwegian.
</P>
<P>
Disl won a 15-kilometer competition, taking her second
biathlon World Cup victory in a row.
</P>
<P>
She timed at 44 minutes, 34.2 seconds with one target missed.
Russian Albina Achatova took second place in 45:56.5. Magdalena
Forsberg of Sweden finished third in 46:14.0.
</P>
<P>
Forsberg led with 110 points, while Disl had 98 points.
</P>
