<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangxi Improves Transportation Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- People in Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, southwestern China, no longer frown at the
thought of having to travel somewhere with the improvement in
infrastructure construction especially in transportation in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
Liang Xianming, a regional government official, who often goes
on business trips, says that 10 years ago it took seven hours to
drive from the regional capital, Nanning, to Fangchenggang on the
South China Sea, and he had to stop for lunch along the way. But
now an expressway allows him to leave in the morning and return
home to Nanning for dinner.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has put 70 percent of the fixed assets
investment in transportation and telecommunications. From 1990 to
1997, the transportation sector got 16 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi shares a border with Viet Nam and has a long
coastline. River transport has a great deal of potential. Guangxi
has a 653-kilometer expressway under construction between major
cities like Guilin, Liuzhou, Nanning, Beihai, and Fangchenggang.
</P>
<P>
All counties and 99.3 percent of the villages in Guangxi are
linked by the highway network.
</P>
<P>
Guigang terminal is being built. When it is completed,
1,000-ton boats will be able to go from Nanning to Guangzhou,
southern China's economic center.
</P>
<P>
According to the Guangxi Transportation Department, its major
ports are now better connected to inland areas and the railway
runs to the ports of Fangchenggang, Qinzhou, and Beihai.
</P>
<P>
The present annual handling capacity of Qinzhou is 14.44
million tons, and Fangchenggang's was 6.5 million tons last year.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0482 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
