<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Orders Airstrikes on Iraqi Military Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Wednesday that airstrikes on Iraq was ordered on "military
and security" targets.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the attacks are aimed at Iraq's weapons programs
and its capacity to attack its neighbors. He said the military
strike is designed to protect the security of the United States,
and the interests of Americans and people around the world.
</P>
<P>
Saddam Hussein must not be allowed to threaten his neighbors
with weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he decided weeks ago to give Saddam Hussein one
last chance to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
But he said U.N. inspectors report that Iraq has failed to
cooperate and has in fact placed new restrictions on weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted the weapons inspectors weren't able to do their
job. He said even if they were to stay, it would be a "sham." As
he put it, they haven't disarmed Saddam. Instead, he has disarmed
them, through his deceptions.
</P>
<P>
And Clinton, addressing the nation from the Oval Office, said
the situation in Iraq poses a "clear and present danger" to the
stability of the Persian Gulf and to people everywhere.
</P>
<P>
He said he ordered a "strong, sustained" series of airstrikes
that would send "a powerful message to Saddam: If you act
recklessly, you will pay a heavy price."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Wednesday
he had ordered more U.S. air and ground forces in the Gulf to deal
with the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said there would be no time limits, the attack against Iraq
would be carried out for as long as needed.
</P>
<P>
"Any use of force, as the president has indicated, involves
risk. To limit the risk to our troops and our allies, I am
ordering a sharp increase in our forces in the Gulf," Cohen told a
news conference at the Pentagon soon after the airstrikes began.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Iraq should not misunderstand the U.S.
determination. "We have acted. We do not use force lightly and we
have not done so today."
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, General Henry
Shelton, said the operation employed U.S. Navy aircraft operating
from bases on land in the region and Tomahawk cruise missiles
launched from ships at sea.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was also deploying additional military forces to
Southwest Asia to bolster the already substantial military
presence in the Gulf region, the general said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright also said Wednesday
that the purpose of the military strikes against Iraqi targets is
to degrade the military capacity of the Iraqi regime.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the State Department, Albright said Iraqi President
Saddam Hussein's "capacity to develop and brandish such armaments
poses a threat to international security and peace that cannot be
ignored."
</P>
<P>
"One way or another, it must be countered. And degrading that
capacity is the purpose of the strikes on military targets in Iraq
that the president has ordered today," Albright told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
She indicated that "our quarrel is not with the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, we recognize that Iraqis have been the
primary victims of Saddam Hussein's failure to cooperate
internationally and his reign of terror domestically," she said.
</P>
<P>
"The United States took the lead in establishing a U.N. program
to meet the humanitarian needs of Iraqi civilians and supported
the expansion of that program earlier this year," she stressed.
</P>
<P>
She confirmed that she had consulted by phone with more than a
dozen of her counterparts of other countries.
</P>
<P>
Already deployed in the Gulf region are 24,100 U.S. military
soldiers; 22 ships, eight armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles; and
201 military aircraft, among them 15 Air Force B-52 bombers also
equipped with cruise missiles. The bombers are based on the Indian
Ocean island of Diego Garcia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0485 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
