<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mixed Reactions to U.S.-led Military Attacks on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.-led air strikes
against Iraq on Wednesday have drawn mixed reactions from the
international community with China, Russia and France condemning
the action.
</P>
<P>
In New York, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who has
undertaken pains-taking efforts to seek peaceful solution to the
Iraqi crisis, said: "This is a sad day for the United Nations and
for the world," and "also a sad day for me personally."
</P>
<P>
This is the first response from Annan following the U.S. and
Biritish military action against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Permanent Representative to the United Nations Qin
Huasun said on Wednesday that China is opposed to the use of force
against Iraq. He said the use of force will not only have serious
consequences for the implementation of the Security Council
resolutions, but also pose a threat to international peace as well
as regional security.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no excuse or pretext to use force against
Iraq," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
In Madrid, visiting Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said
his government would demand at the U.N. Security Council an
immediate halt to the U.S. and British military action against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack would not only worsen the Iraqi crisis but
would also have serious international consequences."
</P>
<P>
France also expressed its regret over what it called the
"spiral" which has led to the military strikes by the United
States against Iraq Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry communique said that France also
regrets the serious consequences the strikes would inflict on the
Iraqi civilians.
</P>
<P>
In Bonn, the German government expressed the hope that the
U.S. strikes against Iraq will end quickly as soon as possibly.
</P>
<P>
German government spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said Thursday the
federal government regretted that it had come to use military
measures.
</P>
<P>
Heye said that the international community have repeatedly
called on Iraq to comply fully with the resolutions of the
U.N.Security Council.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Wednesday evening that
Iraq must be degraded and diminished by military forces, after
U.S. and British forces attacked Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said his country
supports the U.S. and British air strikes on Iraq and urged
Baghdad to comply with U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Australian Prime Minister John Howard said the U.S. and British
attacks against Iraq was necessary due to "a total failure" by
Baghdad to honor its U.N. weapons inspections agreement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered the strikes Wednesday
morning after reading the latest U.N. reports about noncompliance
by the Iraqis and consulting with his national security staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
