<HEADLINE> Chinese Bank to Start Euro Trading in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai branch of the
Bank of Communications plans to start trading in the euro soon
after the new unified EU currency goes into circulation early next
year, branch director Xu Jiasheng announced recently.
</P>
<P>
By then, anyone who has an account with his branch will be able
to trade euros on any foreign exchange market through the bank, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Xu's branch is one of the first Chinese banks providing
individual foreign exchange trading services, beginning in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, foreign exchange turnover at the
branch has reached 2.4 billion U.S. dollars, of which 1.12 billion
dollars was transacted during the first 11 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
To meet the demands of the fledgling foreign exchange
activity, the branch recently increased its services, including
trading via the telephone and multimedia appliances. 
