<HEADLINE> China Condemns U.S. Airstrikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 17 (Xinhua) -- China today condemns the
U.S. airstrikes against Iraq and requests the U.S. to stop its
military action "immediately", said an official from the Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The response came after the UN Security Council's emergency
consultations on Iraq just adjourned and shortly after the
U.S. began airstrikes against Iraq at 0:49 a.m. local time (21:49
GMT) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The source, who asked not to be named, told Xinhua by telephone
that that Chinese government has time and again opposed the use of
force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Qin Huasun, China's Permanent Representative to the UN, said,
"The use of force will not only have serious consequences for the
implementation of the Security Council resolutions, but also pose
a threat to international peace as well as regional security."
</P>
<P>
Qin said the U.N. Special Commission in charge of dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction led by Richard Butler should
have consulted the council before it withdrew its arms inspectors
from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports claimed that the U.S. air attack, involving
long-range cruise missiles, was made in response to Iraq's
continued defiance of U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
U.S. White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said President Bill
Clinton ordered the strikes after reading the latest U.N. reports
about noncompliance by the Iraqis and consulting with his national
security staff. 
</P>
