<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0509 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Strikes May Lead to Humanitarian Disaster in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 17 (Xinhua) -- An Australian aid agency
warned Thursday of a potential humanitarian catastrophe in Iraq in
the wake of Thursday morning's air strikes by the United States
and Britain against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Robert Yallop, director of CARE Australia's overseas
operations, who has recently returned from Iraq, said the effect
of the bombings, coupled with existing damage to the country's
infrastructure, could see the humanitarian situation dramatically
exacerbated.
</P>
<P>
CARE Australia, a non-governmental aid agency, has a staff
around 15 aid workers operating in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Yallop, who set up CARE Australia's operation in Iraq shortly
after the Gulf War in 1991, said "it is clear the innocent will be
the ones most affected".
</P>
<P>
"I was in Iraq a few weeks ago and I saw with my own eyes the
continuing deterioration in the condition of the Iraqi people,"
Yallop said.
</P>
<P>
"I've seen babies that are born seriously underweight. I mean,
babies that have birth weights of a kilogram, children of three
and four years of age weighing anything from five to eight
kilograms."
</P>
<P>
"You actually wonder what the point of maintaining a sanctions
regime in that kind of context is."
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the day, those who will suffer as a result of
this military intervention are those who have suffered over the
past eight years from the impact of the 1991 war, the sanctions
and so on," he said.
</P>
<P>
United States and Britain announced earlier Thursday their air
strikes against Iraq over Iraq's alleged failure of cooperation
with United Nations Special Commission on Arms Inspections.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government has not yet made any comment on the
strikes, and is expected to declare its support for U.S. and
Britain's military action as it did before. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
