<HEADLINE> Canadian PM Expresses Support for Air Strikes Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien on Wednesday expressed support for U.S.-U.K. military
actions against iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein has brought this crisis on himself by following
deliberate strategy, at great cost to his country, of obstructing
the work of United Nations weapons inspectors in order to maintain
the basis of a weapons of mass destruction program," said Chretien
in a release.
</P>
<P>
"Canada had hoped that Iraq would live up to its commitments to
cooperate with UN inspectors, as it promised to do last month, "
he said.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, as UNSCOM's report to the Security Council on
December 15 stated, Iraq's conduct "ensured that no progress was
able to be made in either the fields of disarmament or accounting
for its prohibited weapons programs." he said.
</P>
<P>
It is "regrettable that Iraq chose not to live up to its
commitments," added the Prime Minister.
</P>
<P>
Chretien also noted that Canada will continue to support
U.N. and international humanitarian efforts, such as the Oil for
Food program, to help alleviate the hardships of the Iraqi
people. 
</P>
