<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urgent  Cohen Vows to Continue Sanctions Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said Wednesday that the UN sanctions against Iraq
should continue until the dismantlement of Baghdad's weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
At a Pentagon press conference, Cohen acknowledged that U.S.
military strikes against Iraq could affect the U.N. Special
Commission's ability to inspect Iraq's weapons programs, but said
sweeping sanctions would remain in place.
</P>
<P>
The original sanctions, which prohibited all Iraqi exports and
required United Nations approval for imports, were intended to
force Iraq to eliminate all of its weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
But after years of patchy cooperation from Iraqi authorities,
UNSCOM, the U.N. body supervising the arms controls, says it still
cannot certify banned weapons have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
"We have given (Iraqi President) Saddam Hussein every
opportunity to fully comply with the weapons regime," Cohen said.
"We do intend to keep the sanctions in place until there is full
compliance by the Iraqi government." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
