<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0521 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Continues Air Strike Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- After the first waves of
"substantial" U.S. air strikes against Iraqi targets, Baghdad
appeared calm in the orange glow of road lamps mingled with wisps
of smoke caused by explosions.
</P>
<P>
Cars and ambulances were seen speeding on the empty roads and
extra police patrols have been deployed on the main streets
leading to the city center of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
There was no report of casualties, nor was there any official
Iraqi reaction to the sudden attack. The official news agency INA,
however, said President Saddam Hussein is expected to make a
speech to the nation in about an hour.
</P>
<P>
Foreign reporters were gathering at the Press Center for any
official information. Armed solders in front of the gate checked
every person entering the building.
</P>
<P>
Washington said the air strikes were against military and
security targets to "deplete and diminish" Saddam's capability to
threaten his neighbors and the world.
</P>
<P>
Some windows of civilian houses in Western Baghdad had been
broken by blasts caused by huge and ear-deafening explosions.
Experts here said that the attack involves long-range cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
Missiles had been seen dropping in the direction of the one of
the presidential palace in Baghdad - the Radawaniya presidential
palace.
</P>
<P>
A huge smoke volume could be seen from the Mansur District in
the city center and flames also can be seen in the direction of
the Saddam International Airport.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, the White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart said that
U.S. President Bill Clinton had ordered the strikes Wednesday
morning after reading the latest U.N. report on the noncompliance
by the Iraqis and consulting with his national security staff.
</P>
<P>
"At the direction of the president, the U.S. military forces
have launched a substantial military strike against Iraq,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
There seemed a great deal of criticism of the timing of the
attack. Many believe the attack was launched at least partly to
save Clinton from an imminent impeachment in the House for
perjury, obstruction of justice and misuse of power.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military action has been immediately supported by
Britain. British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Wednesday night
that he had authorized British participation in an attack on Iraq
minutes before.
</P>
<P>
He said that "British involvement will be significant" in the
attack, codenamed "Operation Desert Fox."
</P>
<P>
Blair accused Iraq of "constant lies, prevarication and
breaching of agreed conditions."
</P>
<P>
The attack came just one day after the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq pulled out all its staff
from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler has accused Iraqi regime of not
cooperating with the commission in its inspections of suspected
sites as promised about one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Washington's swift action, without warning, appeared to be
designed to prevent Saddam from getting off the hook again.
</P>
<P>
On October 31, Baghdad announced suspension of all cooperation
with U.N. weapons inspectors in an attempt to bring about an early
lifting of U.N. sanctions, thus triggering a standoff with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. military threat, President Saddam Hussein backed off
at the last minute by pledging unconditional resumption of
cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors on November 14. The move
narrowly spared the country of a punishing U.S. air attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
