<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. Strikes Iraq to Degrade Its </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States launched
airstrikes against Iraq Wednesday to degrade the latter's ability
to make and to use weapons of mass destruction and to diminish its
ability to wage war against its neighbors, said U.S. Secretary of
Defense William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
"And we want to demonstrate the consequences of flouting
international obligations," Cohen said at the Pentagon Wednesday
evening soon after U.S. military forces began the attacks.
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein has been an outlaw for some time. In the
1980s, he used chemical weapons against Iran and against his own
Kurdish minority. In 1990 he invaded Kuwait. In 1991 he fired
Scud missiles at his neighbors," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
He said, at the end of the Gulf War, the United Nations
Security Council demanded that Iraq fully disclose and dismantle
its program to build deadly biological, chemical and nuclear
weapons and the missiles to deliver them. But Saddam has used a
combination of denials, deceptions and delays to evade Security
Council mandates.
</P>
<P>
"At nearly every turn, Iraq has chosen obstruction over
openness, and confrontation over cooperation," he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered the strikes Wednesday
morning after reading the latest U.N. reports about noncompliance
by the Iraqis and consulting with his national security staff.
</P>
<P>
"At the direction of the president, the United States military
forces have launched a substantial military strike against Iraq,"
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
The attack involved long-range cruise missiles, military
officials here said.
</P>
<P>
Later, Clinton said airstrikes on Iraq were ordered on "military
and security" targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0529 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updates With More Clinton's Remarks) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
said Wednesday that airstrikes on Iraq was ordered on "military
and security" targets.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the attacks are aimed at Iraq's weapons programs,
and its capacity to attack its neighbors. He said the military
strike is designed to protect the security of the United States,
and the interests of Americans and people around the world.
</P>
<P>
Saddam Hussein must not be allowed to threaten his neighbors
with weapons of mass destruction, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he decided weeks ago to give Saddam Hussein one
last chance to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
But he said U.N. inspectors report that Iraq has failed to
cooperate and has in fact placed new restrictions on weapons
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
Clinton noted the weapons inspectors weren't able to do their
job. He said even if they were to stay, it would be a "sham." As
he put it, they haven't disarmed Saddam. He has disarmed them,
through his deceptions.
</P>
<P>
And Clinton, in a nationally broadcast address from the Oval
Office, said the situation in Iraq poses a "clear and present
danger" to the stability of the Persian Gulf and to people
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
He said he ordered a "strong, sustained" series of airstrike
that would send "a powerful message to Saddam: If you act
recklessly, you will pay a heavy price."
</P>
<P>
Clinton twice emphasized that he had acted on the unanimous
advice of his advisers. 
</P>
