<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa Defeats Egypt in Mandela Challenge Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's national
soccer team, Bafana Bafana, beat Egypt 2-1 Wednesday to win the
Nelson Mandela Inauguration Challenge title in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Captain Hossam Hassan scored the first goal at the 34th
 minute with a perfect finish, only to be equalized by South
Africa's striker Benedict McCarthy six minutes later.
</P>
<P>
At the 74th minute, McCarthy scored his second goal with a
header when the South Africans got a freekick at the edge of the
box.
</P>
<P>
The match, which was seen as a revenge of Bafana on the
Pharoahs, also gave Trott Moloto his first win as new Bafana
coach.
</P>
<P>
Bafana was defeated by the Egyptians at the African Nations
Cup in Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso, earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Before the match, South Africa officially launched its bid to
the 2006 World Cup and unveiled its bid logo -- a football with a
sketch of Africa at the center.
</P>
<P>
South African Sports Minister Steve Tswete said: "We have the
infrastructure, we have the facilities, we have the technology,
we have the capacity and we have the will to do justice to the
biggest sports event on earth."
</P>
<P>
"FIFA (Federation of International Football Associations) can
be assured that a World Cup in South Africa will be a unique and
qualified success."
</P>
<P>
"Give us the World Cup, and we will surprise you to an even
greater degree," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
