<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0535 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen Orders More U.S. Forces to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen said on Wednesday he had ordered more U.S. air and
ground forces to the Gulf to help in the military strikes against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the attack would be carried out for as long as needed
and there would be no time limit.
</P>
<P>
"Any use of force, as the president has indicated, involves
risk. To limit the risk to our troops and our allies I am ordering
a sharp increase in our forces in the Gulf," Cohen said at the
Pentagon soon after the United State began air strikes against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said Iraq should not misunderstand the United States'
determination. "We have acted. We do not use force lightly and we
have not done so today."
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, General Henry
Shelton, said the operation employed U.S. Navy aircraft operating
from land bases in the region and Tomahawk cruise missiles
launched from ships at sea.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was also in the process of deploying additional
military forces to Southwest Asia to bolster the already
substantial military presence in the Gulf region, the general said.
</P>
<P>
Already in the Gulf region are: 24,100 U.S. military men and
women; 22 ships, eight armed with Tomahawk cruise missiles; and
201 military aircraft, among them 15 Air Force B-52 bombers also
equipped with cruise missiles. The bombers are based on the Indian
Ocean island of Diego Garcia.
</P>
<P>
One aircraft carrier battle group is in the Gulf and another is
on its way.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also said the purpose of the airstrikes against Iraq on
Wednesday was to degrade its ability to make and to use weapons of
mass destruction and to diminish its ability to wage war against
its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"And we want to demonstrate the consequences of flouting
international obligations," Cohen said at the Pentagon Wednesday
evening soon after U.S. military forces began the attacks.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered the strikes Wednesday
morning after reading the latest U.N. reports about noncompliance
by the Iraqis and consulting with his national security staff.
</P>
<P>
"At the direction of the president, the United States military
forces have launched a substantial military strike against Iraq,"
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
The attack involved long-range cruise missiles, military
officials here said.
</P>
<P>
Later, Clinton said airstrikes on Iraq were aimed at "military
and security" targets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0536 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Opposes Use of Force against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 16 (Xinhua) -- China is opposed to the
use of force against Iraq, Chinese Permanent Representative to the
United Nations Qin Huasun said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said the use of force will not only have serious
consequences for the implementation of the Security Council
resolutions, but also pose a threat to international peace as well
as regional security.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the disagreement between UNSCOM and Iraq could be
resolved through dialogue and consultations.
</P>
<P>
"There is absolutely no excuse or pretext to use force against
Iraq", he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Qin said the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in charge of
dismantling Iraq's weapons of mass destruction led by Richard
Butler should have consulted the council before it withdrew its
arms inspectors from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said council members were disappointed about the UNSCOM
report. "The report is apparently one-sided and does not reflect
the complete picture on the ground," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qin's remarks came after the council's emergency consultations
on Iraq have just adjourned and shortly after the United States
began airstrikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Butler reported late Tuesday that Iraq had failed to live up to
its promise to cooperate fully with the U.N. arms inspectors and
he ordered the inspectors to leave Baghdad immediately "for their
safety". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
