<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record Number of Americans to Travel in Christmas Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- A record 45.2 million
people in the United States expect to travel 100 miles or more
from home during the Christmas season, according to a survey
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
That figure represents a two percent growth over last year's
44.5 million travelers, said AAA, a non-profit federation of 93
clubs in the U.S. and Canada. Since 1990, Christmas-New Year
travel in the country has jumped 66 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to AAA's survey, approximately 35.5 million people
plan to go by auto this holiday, and another 9.7 million will
travel by airplane, train or bus.
</P>
<P>
AAA's holiday travel projections are based on a national
telephone survey of 1,500 adults.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that 38 percent of travelers plan to visit a
city while another 31 percent expect to go to a town or rural
areas. Other popular destinations include beach, mountains,
national parks, amusement parks and lakes.
</P>
<P>
The previous heaviest travel period was Christmas-New Year's
1996 when 42.3 million Americans took a trip, AAA said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0546 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Says Iraq Must be Diminished by Military Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) British Prime Minister Tony Blair
said Wednesday evening that Iraq must be degraded and diminished
by military forces, after U.S. and British forces attacked
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Making a statement outside his Downing Street residence, he
said every care will be taken to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"Earlier today, I gave authority for UK forces to be deployed
against Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
US and British forces launched a "substantial" attack on Iraq
on Wednesday, he confirmed, saying in a statement outside 10
Downing Street: "Operation Desert Fox was launched at 10pm London
time".
</P>
<P>
"We have no option but to act," Blair said, noting the strikes
were aimed at degrading Saddam's capability to build and use
weapons of mass destruction, and diminish the threat.
</P>
<P>
Attacking Saddam as a serial breaker of promises, Blair said
Britain had no quarrel with the Iraqi people and was taking every
possible care to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"Our military actions are clear: to degrade the capability to
build a newest weapons of mass destruction, and to diminish the
military threat he poses to his neighbor. The targets chosen,
therefore, are targets connected with his military capabilities,
his weapons of mass destruction capacity, and his ability to
threaten his neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking every possible care to avoid civilian
casualties...Our quarrel is not with the Iraqi people. It's never
had been...Our quarrel is with him alone, and the evil regime
which he represents," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no realistic alternative to military force. We are
taking this military action with real regret but also with real
determination. We have exhausted all other avenues. We act because
we must," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no greater responsibility upon a prime minister
than to ask British servicemen to risk their lives for the sake of
peace and stability in another part of the world and I feel that
responsibility, tonight, profoundly.
</P>
<P>
"British involvement will be significant," he said. The Prime
Minister had earlier spoken to the commander of British forces in
the Gulf, Group Captain Rich Jones, and thanked troops for their
"bravery and professionalism".
</P>
<P>
"Saddam Hussein has no intention of abiding by the agreements
he has made," he said. "Despite constant lies, prevarication and
breaching of the agreed conditions, the weapons inspectors carried
out their task, uncovering in the process vast evidence of weapons
of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
Blair said that last month, in calling off an air strike, the
UK and US had "made that last extra effort". After that, they had
warned there would be "no warnings, no wranglings" next time
Saddam Hussein broke his word: "We made the position crystal clear
to him and the entirety of the world community."
</P>
<P>
"Saddam has no intention whatever of keeping to his word. He is
a serial breaker of promises," he said. "The threat is now, and
it is threat to his neighbours, to his people and to the security
of the world."
</P>
<P>
Blair said that after more than a year of broken promises "we
have no option but to act". The military objectives were to
degrade the Iraqi leader's capability to build and use weapons of
mass destruction and to diminish the military threat he posed to
other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The targets chosen were connected with his military capability,
weapons of mass destruction capacity and his ability to threaten
his neighbours, Blair said.
</P>
<P>
Blair added: "There is no realistic alternative to military
force. We are taking military action with real regret but also
with real determination. We have exhausted all other avenues. We
act because we must."
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the government announced that MPs are to hold an
emergency Commons debate on Iraq on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Commons Leader Margaret Beckett told the House in a surprise
late-night statement on Wednesday that the scheduled business was
being changed in the light of representations over the worsening
crisis. Within an hour, the air strikes had begun. 
</P>
</TEXT>
