<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0549 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slower U.S. Economic Growth in 1999 Predicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 16 (Xinhua) -- As it enters its eighth
year of expansion, the U.S. economy will continue to grow in 1999,
although the pace will be slower than in recent years.
</P>
<P>
This prediction was made by a panel of noted economists
surveyed by the Bond Market Association which presents about 200
securities firms and banks in the United States. The Association's
Economic Advisory Committee also expects further easing by the
Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee and a 1999 unemployment
rate that remains below five percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
The Association said in a report Wednesday that the U.S. gross
domestic products will average a 2.1 percent growth rate in 1999,
as measured from the fourth quarter 1998 to the fourth quarter
1999. While that reflects a still growing economy, the Association
said, the rate is noticeably below the 3.4 percent GDP growth rate
the economists forecast for 1998.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, Merrill Lynch said Tuesday in a briefing that
its economists expects U.S. GDP growth to slow to 2 percent in
1999, down from 3.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
As for interest rates, the Association's Economic Advisory
Committee expects to see rates for the 30-year Treasury move down
to 4.75 percent by this time next year from the current monthly
average expected to close 1998 at 5.1 percent. The Federal Funds
will decline to 4.40 percent, down from the current monthly
average of 4.75 percent. Merrill Lynch, however, expects Fed funds
rates to be down to 4 percent by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
Inflation remains in check with the panel projecting the
Consumer Price Index will increase by 2.0 percent in 1999, the
Association said, although that rate is higher than the
economists' forecast of 1.6 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Association identifies the threat of deteriorating economic
conditions in Asia and Latin America as "a potentially serious
drag" on the U.S. economy. Consumer spending was also seen as a
potentially destabilizing force.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending has remained strong, the Association said,
but that has been spurred by strong equity valuations. However, if
consumer spending were to stall due to stock market problems of
concerns in other areas of the economy, U.S. growth could slow
abruptly.
</P>
<P>
With the introduction of the euro, the economic panel sees the
common currency as speeding the development of the European
capital markets, although the euro would not be a near-term rival
to the U.S. dollar as a reserve currency. Some economists at the
panel said the initial uncertainty of the new currency might drive
up interest rates in Europe and benefit U.S. markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0550 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair says Iraq Must be Diminished by Military Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Wednesday evening that Iraq must be degraded and
diminished by military forces, after U.S. and British forces
attacked Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Making a statement outside his Downing Street residence, he
said every care will be taken to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"Earlier today, I gave authority for UK forces to be deployed
against Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
Describing British involvement as significant, Blair accused
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein of "constant lies, prevarication
and breaching of the agreed conditions."
</P>
<P>
"We have no option but to act," Blair said, noting the strikes
were aimed at degrading Saddam's capability to build and use
weapons of mass destruction, and diminish the threat.
</P>
<P>
Attacking Saddam as a serial breaker of promises, Blair said
Britain had no quarrel with the Iraqi people and was taking every
possible care to avoid civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
"Our military actions are clear: to degrade the capability to
build a newest weapons of mass destruction, and to diminished the
military threat he poses to his neighbor. The targets chosen,
therefore, are targets connected with his military capabilities,
his weapons of mass destruction capacity, and his ability to
threaten his neighbors," he said.
</P>
<P>
"There is no realistic alternative to military force. We are
taking this military action with real regret but also with real
determination. We have exhausted all other avenues. We act because
we must," Blair said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
