<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Backs Social Development and Stabilization in Latin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-America
Development Bank (IDB) Wednesday announced the approval of more
than 3.5 billion U.S. dollar in loans for wide-ranging economic
and social development programs for five Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
These loans set new records for the largest amount of IDB
financing to be approved for a single day and for a single
country.
</P>
<P>
These loans include a 2.5 billion dollar emergency loan for
Argentina to help enhance the banking sector and deepen
macroeconomic reforms; 250 million dollars for Argentina's
municipal reform and Developmentt; 350 million dollars as the
emergency loan to support Colombia's modernization of the electric
power sector; 90 million dollars for Guatemala to meet the most
pressing social and economic needs of the poorest rural
populations; 310 million dollars to improve rural water supply and
sanitation services in Mexico and 70.4 million dollars to support
sustainable economic and social development of the Darien region
in Panama.
</P>
<P>
The IDB expects to provide about 2.5 billion dollars in
financing over the next few years to El Salvador, Guatemala,
Honduras, and Nicaragua, the four Central American nations hit the
hardest by Hurricane Mitch recently. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
