<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Begins Air Strike Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- The United States began
"substantive" air strikes against military and security targets in
Iraq at 0:49 a.m. local time (21:49 GMT) on Thursday to "deplete
and diminish" President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
Ear-deafening explosions can be heard all over Baghdad and the
sky over the city was lit up by flares as anti-aircraft guns
opened fire at dubious targets.
</P>
<P>
Bombs have been seen dropping in the direction of the one of
the presidential palace in Baghdad - the Radawaniya presidential
palace.
</P>
<P>
A huge smoke volume can be seen from the Mansur District in the
city center and flames also can be seen in the direction of the
Saddam International Airport.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said that the attack involves long-range cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
In Washington, the White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart said a
moment ago that U.S. President Bill Clinton had ordered the
strikes Wednesday morning after reading the latest U.N. report on
the noncompliance by the Iraqis and consulting with his national
security staff.
</P>
<P>
"At the direction of the president, the U.S. military forces
have launched a substantial military strike against Iraq,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military action has been immediately supported by
Britain. British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Wednesday night
that he had authorized British participation in an attack on Iraq
minutes before.
</P>
<P>
He said that "British involvement will be significant" in the
attack, codenamed "Operation Desert Fox."
</P>
<P>
Blair accused Iraq of "constant lies, prevarication and
breaching of agreed conditions."
</P>
<P>
The attack came just one day after the United Nations Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq pulled out all its staff
from Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler has accused Iraqi regime of not
cooperating with the commission in its inspections of suspected
sites as promised about one month ago.
</P>
<P>
On October 31, Baghdad announced suspension of all cooperation
with U.N. weapons inspectors in an attempt to bring about an early
lifting of U.N. sanctions, thus triggering a standoff with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Under U.S. military threat, President Saddam Hussein backed off
at the last minute by pledging unconditional resumption of
cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors on November 14. The move
narrowly spared the country of a punishing U.S. air attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0557 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
