<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Weighing Debate Plans Owing to Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Congressional leaders
said Wednesday they were considering whether impeachment debate on
President Bill Clinton should go ahead as scheduled on Thursday in
the event of air strikes against Iraq, but no decision had been
made.
</P>
<P>
Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt had met incoming speaker of
the House of Representatives Bob Livingston and they had agreed to
discuss the need for contingency plans at party caucus meetings
due later Wednesday, according to news reports.
</P>
<P>
Earlier CNN reported that Congressional leaders had decided to
postpone the debate because of the latest confrontation with Iraq,
which was sparked by a new U.N. report accusing Baghdad of
refusing to cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, a Republican,
said the decision would depend on how long any strikes went on and
whether they were successful.
</P>
<P>
"It would be awkward to have an impeachment vote during a
bombing in Iraq," Hyde said after the closed meeting of House
Republican leaders. Later he told reporters no decision had been
made.
</P>
<P>
"This is just some rumor going around," said Michelle Davis,
spokeswoman for House Majority Leader Dick Armey, when asked if
the debate had been postponed.
</P>
<P>
The House is scheduled to open its second presidential
impeachment debate in history on Thursday. The leadership was
meeting later in the day to decide exactly how the debate and vote
would proceed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
