<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updates with More details) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. White House spokesman
Joe Lockhart said President Bill Clinton ordered the strikes
Wednesday morning after reading the latest U.N. reports about
noncompliance by the Iraqis and consulting with his national
security staff.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's order to strike Iraq was made because of Iraq's
continued failure to allow U.N. weapons inspections, Lockhart
said.
</P>
<P>
Military sources here said the attack began with long-range
cruise missiles and would last up to four days.
</P>
<P>
"At the direction of the president, the United States military
forces have launched a substantial military strike against Iraq,"
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton planned to address the nation on television Wednesday
evening.
</P>
<P>
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott criticized the military
action even before it was formally announced.
</P>
<P>
"While I have been assured by administration officials that
there is no connection with the impeachment process in the House
of Representatives, I cannot support this military action in the
Persian Gulf at this time," his statement said.
</P>
<P>
At the Pentagon, top military officials put into action plans
that had been put on hold a month ago. The military planners
envisioned an attack lasting up to four days led by the cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
At the State Department, spokesman James Rubin read a long list
of U.S. grievances with Iraq that included barring inspection of
the office of the ruling Baath party, stripping suspect sites of
files and furniture and buzzing a U.N. helicopter.
</P>
<P>
"This is a grave matter," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"Both the timing and the policy are subject to question," he
said in a statement issued shortly before the sound of
anti-aircraft guns erupted over Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
The House was scheduled to begin debate on four articles of
impeachment against Clinton on Thursday, with votes likely on
Friday. House leaders were discussing plans to postpone
impeachment votes in the event of airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
The attack involved a series of cruise missile strikes against
large numbers of targets, said a senior military officer at the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
"Time on target was 5:05," the officer said, indicating that
the attack was to have taken place at late afternoon Washington
time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
