<HEADLINE> Anti-aircraft Guns Open Fire in Baghdad-Witnesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 17 (Xinhua) -- Anti-aircraft guns opened fire
in Baghdad early on Thursday, half an hour after air raid sirens
briefly sounded, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The sound of the gun fire thundered around the Baghdad Ministry
of Culture and Information offices where western journalists are
based, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
The air raid sirens had sounded in Baghdad for about 30 seconds
at around 0020 local time (2120 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Cars sped through a busy Baghdad street as the sirens sounded
but traffic appeared to be normal a few minutes later.
</P>
<P>
President Saddam Hussein put Iraq on a war footing on Wednesday
and urged his people to defy the West's attempt to make them
"kneel" as American warships and bombers in the Gulf awaited an
order to strike.  
</P>
</TEXT>
