<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Agrees to Disburse $957 Mln for Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) Wednesday announced the approval of disbursing about
957 million U.S. dollars for Indonesia to help the country to
overcome its economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the completion of the third review under the
Extended Fund Facility (EFF), Alassane D. Ouattara, Deputy
Managing Director of the international financial institution
noted, "the Indonesian economy has remained on the stabilization
path under the most difficult circumstances."
</P>
<P>
"Continued policy implementation, despite an environment of
political uncertainty, has helped improve market sentiment, and
the rupiah has strengthened considerably. Inflationary pressure
has eased and marked progress has been made in stabilizing the
food situation. There are also encouraging signs that business
confidence and the outlook for the real economy has begun to
improve," the IMF official said.
</P>
<P>
However, Ouattara also cautioned that Indonesia still faced
many challenges, "notably in restructuring the banking system and
the corporate sector."
</P>
<P>
The loan assistance is part of the IMF-led international aid
package totaling some 23 billion dollars for the crisis-ridden
country approved on October 31, last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
