<HEADLINE> IDB Agrees to Provide $2.75 Bln Loans for Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) Wednesday announced the approval of the
first of its emergency structural adjustment loan equivalent to
2.5 billion U.S. dollars to Argentina.
</P>
<P>
The resources will be utilized to help the country strengthen
the banking sector, deepen macroeconomic reforms and improve the
social safety net in such areas as education, health and
employment.
</P>
<P>
The loan, the largest single financing operation ever by the
IDB, is part of up to 9 billion dollar in emergency lending to
Latin America so far this year by the bank.
</P>
<P>
The IDB also approved a 350 million dollar emergency loan to
Colombia for reform of the energy sector, as well as a 250 million
dollar loan to Argentina for municipal reforms.
</P>
<P>
The emergency loans, to be disbursed in conjunction with
programs also supported by the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
and the World Bank, are designed to counteract global financial
shocks resulting from the Asian financial crisis triggered off
last year and this year's foreign debt default by Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
