<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees No Change of Course by Iraq on weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday it did not believe that Iraq would change course and
opt for cooperation with U.N. weapons inspectors.
</P>
<P>
"There is no end in sight for this pattern of obfuscation,
obstruction or outright violation," State Department spokesman
James Rubin told reporters. "We can find no grounds for optimism
that the Iraqi leadership, if left to its own devices, will
suddenly change course and opt for cooperation in the new year,
or, if it remains in power, in the new millennium."
</P>
<P>
Rubin described as "grave" the situation reported by UNSCOM
chairman Richard Butler who said Iraq had failed to fulfil a
pledge given one month ago not to hinder U.N. inspections of his
weapons systems.
</P>
<P>
Rubin's comment came as U.S. forces stood poised for a
possible attack on Iraq. But Rubin declined to discuss whether
President Bill Clinton might order a military strike, which the
president said could take place without further warning.
</P>
<P>
Asked what would happen next, he said: "Stay tuned." He said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had discussed Iraq on the
telephone with several foreign ministers, including those from
Britain -- the closest U.S. ally in the Gulf -- France and
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Rubin dismissed suggestions that the moves in Congress to
impeach Clinton over his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair
might affect decision-making on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He said the current situation was determined by Iraq.
"The timing here is generated by iraq's failure to comply."
</P>
</TEXT>
