<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-16 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Israel Heads Toward Early </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 16 (Xinhua) -- After two and a half years
in office, the government of Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu is heading towards the beginning of its end.
</P>
<P>
Facing a critical no-confidence vote in the parliament which
he seems certain to lose next Monday, Netanyahu said Wednesday he
would initiate early elections if he could not muster a necessary
majority for his policy on the peace process with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Likud gathering, Netanyahu defended his
decision, which was reaffirmed by the cabinet Wednesday morning,
to suspend the pending troop withdrawal from the West Bank
stipulated by a recent land-for-peace deal over alleged
Palestinian violations.
</P>
<P>
He said his principal that Israel will not carry out its part
of the agreement until the Palestinians fulfill all their
obligations "is needed by Israel" and is "widely supported."
</P>
<P>
He called on coalition members and opposition members in the
parliament to support his decision. "If there is no necessary
majority to support this decision...I will initiate new elections
in order to get from the people the mandate," he said.
</P>
<P>
His remarks were seen as a last bid to win back those
hardliners in his coalition who vowed to topple his government
and to form a unity government with the Labor Party before
being forced to initiate early elections.
</P>
<P>
But the last choice, early elections, seem to be Netanyahu's
only choice.
</P>
<P>
Some hardliners in his coalition, who were angered by his
signing of the Wye agreement with Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat and expressed support for early elections, would not
change their minds because of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu froze the troop withdrawal for two weeks and played
tough during U.S. President Bill Clinton's visit to the region by
insisting the Palestinians meet new demands before Israel begins
troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
His muscle flexing is widely viewed as a gesture to woo the
hard-liners rebels, but they said they had seen too much such
performances before and were unimpressed this time.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the Labor Party, which has been working to
advance early elections, will certainly not be interested in
rescuing the troubled prime minister from the brink of being
toppled.
</P>
<P>
Labor Party leader Ehud Barak rejected Netanyahu's remarks
Wednesday quickly, repeating his call for early elections. He has
already called in three top media experts from the United States
to help him run for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
As he often did before, Netanyahu could still be able to buy
more time to stablize the coalition.
</P>
<P>
He could withdraw the no-confidence motion, which was put
forward by a coalition party last week in an attempt to avoid an
immediate defeat in a vote on an early elections bill, and
returned to where he was at that time -- facing a bill to dissolve
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
But since some hardliners were determined to end his
government, he might still lose many other no-confidence
votes. Many cabinet minister believe that the current government
could not hang on any longer.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts point out that it's actually in his interest if
Netanyahu initiate early elections himself since it would enable
him to be in charge of setting the elections timetable.
</P>
<P>
Some say the earlier he does this, the better his chances of
being reelected. Actually, when Netanyahu made a tough speech
Tuesday after a three-way summit with Clinton and Arafat at the
Erez border crossing, some said he had started his election
campaign already. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
