<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at GMT 2120, December 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi leadership decided on Wednesday to establish
four defense bases to confront possible air strikes by the United
States against the country, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The four bases locate in the north, south, mid-Euphrates and
center of the country, said the agency report. (BC-Iraq-Military
Bases)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Wednesday he would initiate early elections next Monday if he
could not muster a necessary majority for his policy on the peace
process with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Likud gathering celebrating the Jewish festival
of Hanukka in Tev Aviv, Netanyahu urged his coalition members and
opposition to support his decision to suspend the pending troop
withdrawal from the West Bank stipulated under a recent
land-for-peace deal between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Palestinians of a series of failures to comply
with the agreement and reiterated that Israel would not carry out
its part of the accord until the Palestinians fulfill all their
obligations. The cabinet reaffirmed his decision Wednesday
morning. (BC-1st LD Writethru Israel-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has
expressed his support for holding early elections, Israel Radio
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted several sources close to the prime minister as
saying that Netanyahu has decided to hold early elections and will
announce his plan before Monday, the day when the parliament is
scheduled to vote on a no-confidence motion on the government.
</P>
<P>
The sources said Netanyahu has concluded that under the
current circumstance, early elections is the best
solution. (BC-1st LD Writethru Israel-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi leadership convened an urgent session on
Wednesday afternoon to discuss the situation after all U.N. arms
inspectors evacuated from the country, the Iraqi News Agency INA
reported.
</P>
<P>
INA said a joint meeting of the Revolutionary Command Council
and the ruling Baath Party, chaired by President Saddam Hussein,
discussed the measures Iraq would take to confront possible
U.S.-British air strikes against the country.
</P>
<P>
Saddam called on his people and armed forces to fully mobilize
and make all necessary arrangements to face the imminent U.S. air
strikes. (BC-1st LD Writethru Iraq-Session-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- All U.N. arms inspectors, about 120 personnels,
evaluated from Baghdad on Wednesday morning, a move that indicates
a possible U.S.-led air strike against Iraq is on its way.
</P>
<P>
The arms inspectors left Baghdad Monitoring and Verification
Center at around 9:40, possibly heading for Habaniya airport, 80
kilometers west of Baghdad, from where they would fly to Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
A reliable U.N. sources who asked anonymity told Xinhua ealier
Wednesday that U.N. arms inspectors have received notice from New
York asking them to get ready to evacuate from
Iraq. (BC-Iraq-UN-Inspectors-Pullout 1st lead EDS-Adds quotes and
backgrounds)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said here
Wednesday that chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler's report
aims to justify a U.S. military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency INA, Aziz stressed
that Iraq had committed to the content of the letter sent to
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan in mid-November in which Iraq
announced unconditional cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
This is the first official Iraqi response to the Butler's
report submitted to Annan on Tuesday in which Butler said Iraq
failed to fully cooperate with U.N. arms inspectors.
(BC-Iraq-UN-Aziz-Butler 1st lead EDS: Updates with
more quotes from Aziz) 
</P>
</TEXT>
