<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Surge with Prospects of Iraq Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 16 (Xinhua) - Oil prices rose sharply on
Wednesday as a new row between Iraq and the United Nations over
weapons inspections threatened to trigger a military strike by the
United States against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Benchmark Brent blend futures closed 79 cents higher at 11.38
U.S. dollars a barrel after dipping last week to a lowly 9.60
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Prices soared after the United Nations ordered its weapons
inspectors to leave Baghdad following a report by chief weapons
inspector Richard Butler accusing Iraq of failing to restore
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defence Department officials in Washington said that a
military strike could come quickly.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's ambassador to the United Nations, Nizar Hamdoon, said
oil exports would have to stop if the U.S. launches military
strikes against his country, according to a Reuters report.
Despite the brewing crisis, industry sources said Iraqi oil sales
under the U.N.'s oil-for-food exchange continued as normal on
Wednesday, according to Reuters.
</P>
<P>
Oil monitors are in place at Iraq's Gulf port of Mina al-Bakr
and at the northern border with Turkey where a pipeline runs crude
to the Turkish Mediterranean coast.
</P>
<P>
Dealers were also preparing for a meeting on Thursday of
ministers from OPEC (Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries) producers Saudi Arabia and Venezuela and non-OPEC
Mexico, the main architects of agreements earlier this year among
producers to cut 3.1 million barrels per day from world supplies.
</P>
<P>
The supply curbs thus far have failed to revive a market
weighed down by a towering stockpile and failing demand.
</P>
<P>
Oil this year averaging 13.46 dollars a barrel, is at a 22-year
low and down from 19.30 dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
