<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0587 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over Use of Sunscreen Increases Risk of Skin Cancer: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- Heavy use of sunscreen
may encourage excessive exposure to the sun, thus increasing the
risk of skin cancer, the Washington Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 631 European schoolchildren conducted by European
researchers suggested that those with the highest use of sunscreen
were also the ones most likely to have moles caused by sun
exposure, a predictor for developing skin cancer later in life.
</P>
<P>
The researchers concluded that sunscreen use is linked to
developing the moles because the lotion may encourage
recreational sun exposure.
</P>
<P>
Fewer moles were found among those who regularly wore
protective clothing or who had less sun exposure, said the
researchers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981217.0588 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Dips in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial
production declined 0.3 percent in November for the fourth time in
six months, the Federal Reserve said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dip was largely attributed to last month's unseasonable
warmth and the economic slump that began in Asia last year.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the continued low mortgage rates, the country's
housing construction remained strong.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production decline in November, followed a 0.2
percent increase the previous month, according to the Federal
Reserve. That was due to a 3.4 percent plunge in utility output.
Warm weather reduced the demand for electricity and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output was unchanged, as declines in production
of iron and steel, farm machinery, aircraft and autos offset
increases in computers, household appliances and construction
materials.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report released today, the Commerce Department
said builders started construction of new housing units at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.65 million, down 2.7 percent
from the previous month but still close to July's 11-year high of
1.70 million.
</P>
<P>
Apartment building recorded a steep drop but builders continued
to pour foundations for new single-family homes at a rapid rate.
</P>
<P>
November's decline in housing starts came entirely in
multi-unit buildings, down 26.4 percent to a rate of 298,000. In
contrast, single-family housing starts jumped 5 percent to a rate
of 1.35 million, the highest level since February 1984.
</P>
<P>
Even without December's results, 1998 already has proved to be
the busiest year for builders since 1987. During the first 11
months of the year, builders started 1.50 million units _ both
single-family and apartments. That compares with 1.47 million for
all of 1997 and 1.62 million during 1987.
</P>
<P>
Regionally in November, housing starts fell 5.6 percent in the
Northeast to an annual rate of 152,000, a six-month low. They were
also down in the Midwest, 7.2 percent to a rate of 324,000, and
the South, 6.5 percent to 772,000. But they jumped 12 percent to
401,000 in the West.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, building permits for housing, a leading indicator
of housing starts, fell 2.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.65 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
